{"title_page": "Spam (food)", "text_new": "{{About|the luncheon meat brand|the practice of sending unsolicited messages|Spamming|other uses|Spam (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Canned cooked pork meat product}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Spam\n| image            = [[File:SPAM logo.jpg|150px]]\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   =\n| country          = US  \n| region           =\n| creator          = [[Hormel|Hormel Foods Corporation]]\n| founded          = 1936 (80 years ago) \n| course           = Main course or ingredient\n| served           = Hot or cold\n| main_ingredient  = [[Pork]] \n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            = A precooked [[Canning|canned]] meat product}}\n'''Spam''' (stylized as '''SPAM''') is a brand of [[canning|canned]] cooked pork made by [[Hormel Foods Corporation]], based in [[Minnesota]]. It was first introduced in 1937 and gained popularity worldwide after its use during [[World War II]].<ref name=\"SeriousSpam\" /> By 2003, Spam was sold in 41 countries on six continents and trademarked in over 100 countries (not including the [[Middle East]] and [[North Africa]]).<ref name=\"hormelgoddess\">{{cite web | url= http://www.hormelfoods.com/brands/spam/ | publisher = Hormel Foods |year=2010 |title = Spam \u2013 Postwar Popularity|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215030819/http://www.hormelfoods.com/brands/spam/|archivedate=December 15, 2007}}</ref> Spam's basic ingredients are [[pork]] with [[ham]] meat added, salt, water, [[modified potato starch]] (as a [[Binder (material)|binder]]), sugar, and [[sodium nitrite]] (as a [[preservative]]). Natural [[gelatin]] is formed during cooking in its [[tin can|tins]] on the [[production line]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=Belinda|last2=Clapton|first2=Barbara|last3=Tipton|first3=Catherine|title=Food Technology|page=20|publisher=Heinemann|year=2002}}</ref> Many have raised concerns over Spam's [[nutritional]] attributes, in large part due to its high content of fat, [[Health effects of salt|sodium]], and [[preservative]]s.<ref>https://science.howstuffworks.com/innovation/edible-innovations/spam-food1.htm</ref>\n\nIt has become the subject of several appearances in pop culture, notably [[Spam (Monty Python)|a Monty Python sketch]], which led to its name being borrowed for [[Spamming|unsolicited electronic messages]], especially [[Email spam|email]].<ref name=\"tools.ietf.org\">{{cite web | url = http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2635 | title = RFC 2635 \u2013 DON'T SPEW A Set of Guidelines for Mass Unsolicited Mailings and Postings (spam*) | accessdate = September 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Sliced Spam.JPG|thumb|Sliced Spam]]\nSpam was introduced by Hormel on July 5, 1937.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America states that the product was intended to increase the sale of pork shoulder which was not a very popular cut.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|last=Waxman |first=Olivia B. |url=http://time.com/4827451/spam-history-80th-anniversary/ |title=Spam Turns 80: History and Origins of Canned Meat |publisher=Time.com |date=July 5, 2017 |accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> Ken Daigneau, brother of a company executive, won a $100 prize that year in a competition to name the new item.<ref name = \"history\" /> Hormel claims that the meaning of the name \"is known by only a small circle of former Hormel Foods executives\", but popular beliefs are that the name is an abbreviation of \"spiced ham\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><ref>{{Citation | contribution-url = http://www.spam.com/about | title = SPAM\u00ae Brand FAQ | contribution = What does the SPAM brand name mean? | publisher = Spam}}</ref>\nThe difficulty of delivering fresh meat to the front during World War II saw Spam become a ubiquitous part of the U.S. soldier's diet. It became variously referred to as \"ham that didn't pass its physical\", \"meatloaf without basic training\",<ref name = \"SeriousSpam\" /> and \"Special Army Meat\". Over {{convert|150|e6lb|t|order=flip|abbr=off}} of Spam were purchased by the military before the war's end.<ref name = \"OxfordSpam\" />\n\nDuring World War II and the occupations which followed, Spam was introduced into [[Guam]], [[Hawaii]], [[Okinawa]], the [[Philippines]], and other islands in the Pacific. Immediately absorbed into native diets, it has become a unique part of the history and effects of U.S. influence in the Pacific islands.<ref name=\"BurgerKingSpam\" />\n\nAs a consequence of [[Rationing in the United Kingdom|World War II rationing]] and the [[Lend-Lease Act]], Spam also gained prominence in the United Kingdom. British Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] later referred to it as a \"wartime delicacy\".<ref name=npr.org>{{cite news|author1=Howard Yoon|title=Spam: More than Junk Mail or Junk Meat|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=11714236|issue=npr.org|date=July 4, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stranska|first1=Hana|title=About Spam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/24/magazine/l-about-spam-740128.html|accessdate=October 1, 2014|work=The New York Times|date=July 24, 1994|ref=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/24/magazine/l-about-spam-740128.html}}</ref> In addition to increasing production for the U.K., Hormel expanded Spam output as part of Allied aid to the similarly beleaguered Soviet Union.<ref>{{cite book|title=Creating Minnesota: A History From the Inside Out|last=Atkins|first=Annette|year=2007|publisher=Minnesota Historical Society|location=Minnesota|isbn=978-0-87351-633-4|page=194|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUP6lBSdlrwC&pg |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref> In his memoir ''Khrushchev Remembers'', [[Nikita Khrushchev]] declared: \"Without Spam we wouldn't have been able to feed our army.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Smith|editor-first=Andrew F.|year=2012|title=The Oxford Encyclopaedia of Food and Drink in America|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=343|isbn=978-0199734962}}</ref> Throughout the war, countries ravaged by the conflict and faced with strict food rations came to appreciate Spam.<ref>Heydt, Bruce. \"Spam Again\" . America in WWII, June 2006.</ref>\n\nThe billionth can of Spam was sold in 1959,<ref>{{Citation |title=Spam Is Turning 80. Here's How the Canned Meat Took Over the World |last=Waxman |first=Olivia B. |date=July 5, 2017 |work=time.com |url= http://time.com/4827451/spam-history-80th-anniversary/ |accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref> the seven billionth can was sold in 2007,<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web | url= http://www.spam.com/about | title= Spam Brand History | accessdate= November 27, 2016 | publisher= Spam | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161127014422/http://www.spam.com/about | archive-date= November 27, 2016 | url-status= dead }}</ref> and the eight billionth can was sold in 2012.<ref>{{Citation |title=For Spam's 80th anniversary, 10 outrageous retro recipes by the Minnesota meat maker |first=Sharyn |last=Jackson |date= July 5, 2017 |work=startribune.com |url= http://www.startribune.com/for-spam-s-80th-anniversary-10-outrageous-retro-recipes-by-the-minn-meat-maker/432686623/ |accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International usage==\n===United States and territories===\n[[image:Baked Spam with Cloves.jpg|thumb|right|225px|Baked Spam]]\nDomestically, Spam's chief advantages were affordability, accessibility, and extended shelf life.<ref name=\"OxfordSpam\">{{cite book |last =Smith|first = Andrew |title=The Oxford Companion to American Food and Drink|date= May 1, 2007 | publisher= Oxford University Press|isbn = 978-0-19988576-3|pages = 559\u201360 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=GZVweuXhZlkC&pg=PA559}}</ref> At the time it was introduced, it was the only canned meat product on the market that needed no refrigeration.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ruvio|first=Ayalla A.|title=How Spam became one of the most iconic American brands of all time|url=https://theconversation.com/how-spam-became-one-of-the-most-iconic-american-brands-of-all-time-80030|accessdate=July 6, 2017|work=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|date=July 2, 2017}}</ref> Statistics from the 1990s say that 3.8 cans of Spam were consumed every second in the United States,<ref>{{cite magazine |last=|first= |title=Data Stream|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=25|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=January 1997|page=28}}</ref> totaling nearly 122 million cans annually. It became part of the diet of almost 30% of American households, perceived differently in various regions of the country.<ref>Kim, Sojin; Livengood, Mark (1995). [http://digest.champlain.edu/archivepdf/DIGESTvol15.pdf \u201cRamen Noodles and Spam: Popular Foods, Significant Tastes\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006180722/http://digest.champlain.edu/archivepdf/DIGESTvol15.pdf |date=October 6, 2014 }}, pp. 2\u201311. Retrieved September 18, 2014.</ref> It is also sometimes associated with economic hardship because of its relatively low cost.<ref name=\"SeriousSpam\" >{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/15/business/15spam.html|title=Spam Turns Serious and Hormel Turns Out More |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |first=Andrew |last=Martin |date=November 15, 2008 |accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSpam that is sold in North America, South America, and Australia is produced in [[Austin, Minnesota]] (also known as \"Spam Town USA\") and in [[Fremont, Nebraska]].<ref>Wyman, Carolyn. \"Spam: A Biography.\" Harvest Books, 1999</ref> Austin, Minnesota also has a restaurant with a menu devoted exclusively to Spam, called \"Johnny's SPAMarama Menu\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Spam Turns Serious and Hormel Turns Out More|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 14, 2008|accessdate=July 5, 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/15/business/15spam.html}}</ref>\n\n==== Hawaii ====\n[[File:Spam musubi at Ninja Sushi.jpg|thumb|right|[[Spam musubi]] is a popular snack and lunch food in [[Hawaiian food|Hawaii]]]]\nSpam is especially popular in the state of Hawaii, where residents have the highest per capita consumption in the United States. Its perception there is very different from on the mainland.<ref>{{cite book |title=Fashionable food: seven decades of food fads |last=Lovegren |first=Sylvia |year=2005 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=United States |isbn=978-0-226-49407-4 |page=190 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fZIRc28P5xYC&dq |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref> Hawaiians sometimes call it \"Portagee Steak\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Hawaii's Spam Cookbook |last=Corum |first=Ann Kondo |year=1987 |publisher=Bess Press |location=United States |isbn=0935848495|page=135|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8eTPLr0f2h0C&pg=PA135&lpg=PA135#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA popular local dish in Hawaii is [[Spam musubi]], where cooked Spam is placed atop [[rice]] and wrapped in a band of [[nori]], a form of ''[[onigiri]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatscookingamerica.net/History/Spam.htm|title=Spam&nbsp;\u2013 Hawaiian Spam Musubi|publisher=Whatscookingamerica.net|accessdate=July 5, 2013}}</ref>\nVarieties of Spam are found in Hawaii that are unavailable in other markets, including Honey Spam, Spam with Bacon, and Hot and Spicy Spam.<ref name=\"Star\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/2007/06/11/burger_giants_wage_spam_war.html |first=Jaymes |last=Song |date=June 11, 2007|work=The Star|title=Burger giants wage Spam war | location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\nHawaiian [[Burger King]] restaurants began serving Spam in 2007 to compete with the local [[McDonald's]] chains (which also serve Spam).<ref name=\"BurgerKingSpam\" >{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070611/ap_on_bi_ge/burger_king_Spam|title=Burger King to Serve Spam in Hawaii|publisher=Yahoo! News|accessdate=July 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kare11.com/news/news_article.aspx?storyid=254168|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120605005816/http://www.kare11.com/news/news_article.aspx?storyid=254168|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 5, 2012|title=Land of 10,000 Stories&nbsp;\u2013 Spam in Paradise|publisher=KARE11 News|first=Boyd|last=Huppert|date=May 17, 2007}}</ref> In Hawaii, Spam is so popular that it is sometimes referred to as \"The Hawaiian Steak\".<ref>{{cite news |title= The Spam That Isn't Via E-Mail |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E6DB1338F934A35757C0A9659C8B63 |work=The New York Times |date=April 7, 2003 |accessdate=December 28, 2007 }}</ref> There is even an annual Spam-themed festival on the island of Oahu that takes place every spring, known as the \"Waikiki Spam Jam\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spamjamhawaii.com/|title=Welcome - Waikiki Spam Jam|last=|first=|date=|website=Welcome|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2017}}</ref> Local chefs and restaurants compete to create new Spam-themed dishes, which are then sold in a massive street fair on Kalakaua Avenue in Waikiki.\n\nIn 2017, Hawaii was plagued by a rash of thefts of Spam.<ref name=\"SpamHeistsSingh\">{{cite news|last1=Singh|first1=Lakshmi|title=Hawaii's Spate Of Spam Heists|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/10/22/559403062/hawaiis-spate-of-spam-heists|accessdate=October 23, 2017|work=[[NPR]]|date=October 22, 2017}}</ref> Spam had long been a target of thieves in Hawaii, but the magnitude of the thefts ramped up, with incidents in which multiple cases of Spam were stolen at once. Local retailers believe organized crime was involved.<ref name=\"SpamHeistsSingh\"/> This came alongside increases in thefts of some other retail goods, such as [[corned beef]] and liquor. The president of the retail merchants of Hawaii attributed the rise in retail thefts to a recent change in criminal law, which raised the threshold at which a theft would lead to [[felony]] charges by approximately $400.<ref name=\"SpamHeistsSingh\"/>\n\n==== Guam and the Northern Marianas ====\nIn [[Guam]], average per capita consumption is 16 tins (cans) per year. It is also found on McDonald's menus there. The ''Spam Games'' also takes place in Guam, where locals sample and honor the best original, homemade Spam recipes.<ref>{{cite web | title =Why is Spam Brand a Household Name? | url =http://www.spam.com/spam-101/why-is-spam-a-household-brand | accessdate =October 6, 2014 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141010035126/http://www.spam.com/spam-101/why-is-spam-a-household-brand | archivedate =October 10, 2014 | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Northern Mariana Islands]], lawyers from Hormel have threatened to sue the local press for publishing articles alleging ill-effects of high Spam consumption on the health of the local population.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?newsID=59528&cat=3 |title=Organic smoke (and mirrors) |work=Saipan Tribune |date=July 21, 2006 |accessdate=June 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623203856/http://www.saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?newsID=59528&cat=3 |archivedate=June 23, 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?cat=3&newsID=59336 |title=A junkie waiting to happen |work=Saipan Tribune |date=July 14, 2006 |accessdate=June 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623203851/http://saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?cat=3&newsID=59336 |archivedate=June 23, 2008  }}</ref>\n\n==== Puerto Rico ====\nSandwich de Mezcla is a party staple in [[Puerto Rico]] containing Spam, [[Velveeta]], and [[pimiento]]s (made into a spread) between two slices of [[sandwich bread]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cafeculinario.com/2013/08/12/receta-sandwichitos-para-fiestas/|title=Receta: Sandwichitos para fiestas|date=August 12, 2013|accessdate=October 6, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141007220541/http://cafeculinario.com/2013/08/12/receta-sandwichitos-para-fiestas/|archivedate=October 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nAfter World War II, Newforge Foods, part of the Fitch Lovell group, was awarded the license to produce the product in the UK at its Gateacre factory, [[Liverpool]],<ref>The story of Fitch Lovell Ambrose Keevil Phillimore Press 1972 {{ISBN|978-0-85033-074-8}}</ref> where it stayed until production switched to the [[Danish Crown AmbA|Danish Crown Group]] (owners of the Tulip Food Company) in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.tulip.dk/ |title=Tulip Food Company |publisher=english.tulip.dk |accessdate=June 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814170842/http://english.tulip.dk/ |archivedate=August 14, 2009  }}</ref>\n\nThe United Kingdom has adopted Spam into various recipes. For example, recipes include Spam Yorkshire Breakfast, Spamish Omelette, and Spam Hash.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spam\u2014UK |url=http://www.spam-uk.com/recipes/ |accessdate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref> Spam can also be sliced, battered and [[Deep frying|deep-fried]] into [[Spam fritter]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spam Fritters |url=http://www.lbhf.gov.uk/Images/Spam_fritters_tcm21-170915.pdf |accessdate=October 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010114629/http://www.lbhf.gov.uk/Images/Spam_fritters_tcm21-170915.pdf |archivedate=October 10, 2014  }}</ref>\n\n===Southeast Asia===\n====Philippines====\n[[File:Spam Meal.jpg|thumb|\"[[Spamilog]]\", Spam with ''[[sinang\u00e1g]]'' (garlic [[fried rice]]) and [[Egg as food|eggs]], is a common [[Filipino food|Filipino]] breakfast combination.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casey |first1=Nell |title=Stay Warm With Filipino Brunch & A Cookie Competition This Weekend |url=http://gothamist.com/2016/12/16/weekend_food_roundup_97.php |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |work=Gothamist |agency=WNYC |date=December 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224150751/http://gothamist.com/2016/12/16/weekend_food_roundup_97.php |archive-date=February 24, 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>]]\n\nIn the Philippines, Spam (currently distributed by [[San_Miguel_Food_and_Beverage#Subsidiaries|The Purefoods-Hormel Company Inc.]]) is a popular food item and seen as a cultural symbol. As a former US territory, Spam reached the islands similar to how it reached [[Hawaii]] and [[Guam]]: as a result of [[World War II]] rationing. Spam is commonly eaten with rice (usually [[garlic fried rice]]) and a sunny-side up egg for breakfast. It is prepared and used in a variety of ways, including being fried, served alongside condiments, or used in sandwiches. It has also been featured in numerous Filipino [[fusion cuisine]] dishes including Spam burgers, Spam [[Filipino spaghetti|spaghetti]], Spam nuggets, and others.<ref name=\"Escalona2017\">{{cite news |last1=Escalona |first1=Katrina |work=Culture Trip|title=Why Spam and Rice is a Filipino Food Classic |url=https://theculturetrip.com/asia/philippines/articles/why-spam-and-rice-is-a-filipino-food-classic/ |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |date=September 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ke |first1=Bryan |title=Why Filipinos Love Spam So Much |url=https://nextshark.com/filipinos-love-spam-much/ |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |work=NextShark |date=December 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Agoncillo |first1=Anna |title=What Is SPAM And Why Are Filipinos Obsessed With It? |url=https://remit.com.au/what-is-spam-and-why-are-filipinos-obsessed-with-it/ |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |work=RemitBlog |date=September 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120144353/https://remit.com.au/what-is-spam-and-why-are-filipinos-obsessed-with-it/ |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ong |first1=Sherina |title=SPAM: A story of love and hate |url=https://www.rappler.com/move-ph/balikbayan/identity/60979-spam-love-hate |accessdate=January 20, 2019 |work=Rappler |date=June 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe popularity of Spam in the [[Philippines]] transcends economic class, and Spam gift sets are even used as homecoming gifts. There are at least ten different varieties of Spam currently available in the country and an estimated 1.25&nbsp;million kilos of the meat is sold every year in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite journal |last = Matejowsky |first = Ty |title = SPAM and Fast-food \"Glocalization\" in the Philippines |journal = Food, Culture and Society: An International Journal of Multidisciplinary Research |volume = 10 |issue = 1 |pages = 23\u201341 |date = March 1, 2007 |doi = 10.2752/155280107780154088 }}</ref> During the rescue efforts after [[Typhoon Ketsana|Typhoon Ondoy]] (Ketsana) in 2009, Hormel Foods donated over 30,000&nbsp;pounds of Spam to the [[Philippine National Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.webwire.com/ViewPressRel.asp?aId=105336 |title= Hormel Foods Announces Donation to Philippines | work=Web wire |date = October 8, 2009 | accessdate =September 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===East Asia===\n[[File:Spam served with rice.jpg|thumb|upright|Spam is often served with rice in [[Asian cuisine|Asia]].]]\n\n====China====\nIn China, Hormel decided to adopt a different strategy to market Spam, promoting it as a foreign, premium food product and changing the Spam formula to be meatier in order to accommodate local Chinese tastes.<ref name=\"china businessweek\">{{cite web | title = Spam's Long March in China | url = http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/spams-long-march-in-china-08042011.html | work = Bloomberg BusinessWeek | date = August 4, 2011 | accessdate = October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Japan====\nIn [[Okinawan cuisine|Okinawa]], [[Japanese cuisine|Japan]], the product is added into [[onigiri]] alongside eggs and used as a staple ingredient in the traditional Okinawan dish ''[[chanpur\u016b]]'', and a Spam burger is sold by local fast food chain [[Jef (fast food restaurant)|Jef]]. For the 70th anniversary of Spam in 2007, cans with special designs were sold in Japan due to its popularity, primarily in Okinawa.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/idINT22925620080312|title=Okinawa cuisine: tofu, Spam and root beer | agency=Reuters | first=Linda | last=Sieg |date=March 12, 2008 |accessdate=September 24, 2010}}</ref>\nFollowing the March 2011 earthquake, Spam sales in Japan declined and Hormel shifted its focus to China,<ref name=\"china businessweek\"/> although Hormel did pledge to donate $100,000 along with cans of Spam for relief efforts.<ref>{{cite news | title = Hormel Foods Pledges to Relief Efforts in Japan | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/17/idUS140792+17-Mar-2011+BW20110317 | agency = Reuters | date = March 17, 2011 | accessdate = October 6, 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141010204435/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/17/idUS140792+17-Mar-2011+BW20110317 | archivedate = October 10, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\nIn the summer of 2011, Burger King introduced its own version of a burger made of Spam, called 'BK Shot' Spam Burgers. These small burgers are filled with slices of the canned meat and were an attempt by Burger King to capitalize on Spam's popularity in Japan.<ref>{{cite web | title = Forget Spam fritters, now Burger King is selling Spam burgers\u2026 for women | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2003298/Burger-King-sell-Spam-burgers-Japan--women.html | work = Daily Mail | date = June 15, 2011 | accessdate = October 5, 2014}}</ref> In early 2014, Burger King also introduced the Spam and Cheese burger as a breakfast menu item.<ref>{{cite news | last = Bleier | first = Evan | title = Burger King introduces Spam and cheese burger in Japan, for breakfast | url = http://www.upi.com/Odd_News/2014/05/01/Burger-King-introduces-SPAM-and-cheese-burger-in-Japan-for-breakfast/7611398966149/ | agency = United Press International | date = May 1, 2014 | accessdate = October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Hong Kong====\nIn [[Cuisine of Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] after World War II, meat was scarce and expensive, so Spam was an accessible, affordable alternative. The luncheon meat has been incorporated into dishes such as macaroni with fried egg and spam in chicken soup, as well as [[ramen]].<ref>{{cite web |title = Why is Spam served in Hong Kong diners on top of macaroni noodles? | work = HK Magazine | url = http://hk-magazine.com/restaurants/column/why-spam-served-hong-kong-diners-top-macaroni-noodles |accessdate= October 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nIn later years, the surfeit of Spam in both North and South Korea during the [[Korean War]] led to the establishment of the Spam ''[[kimbap]]'' (rice and vegetable filled seaweed roll). Because of a scarcity of fish and other traditional kimbap products such as kimchi or fermented cabbage, Spam was added to a rice roll with kimchi and cucumber and wrapped in seaweed. Spam was also used by US soldiers in Korea as a means of trading for items, services or information around their bases.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2014/09/05/in-korea-its-spam-time-of-year/|title=In Korea, It's Spam Time of Year}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Korean cuisine|South Korea]], Spam ({{ko-hhrm|hangul= \uc2a4\ud338 |rr=seupaem}}, licensed from Hormel by [[CJ CheilJedang]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cj.co.kr/cj-kr/brands/spam|title=\uc2a4\ud338 (SPAM)|publisher=[[CJ CheilJedang]]|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref>) is popular with a majority of the population, and outranks [[Coca-Cola]] and [[KFC]] in status as a foodstuff. Today, South Korea produces and consumes more Spam than any other country except the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|title=From Minnesota Fat to Seoul Food: Spam in America and the Pacific Rim|last=Lewis|first=George H.|publisher=The Journal of Popular Culture, volume 34, issue 2|year=2004}}, [http://0-onlinelibrary.wiley.com.mercury.concordia.ca/doi/10.1111/j.0022-3840.2000.3402_83.x/pdf]</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=In South Korea, Spam Is the Stuff Gifts Are Made Of | work = The New York Times | date = January 26, 2014 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/27/world/asia/in-south-korea-spam-is-the-stuff-gifts-are-made-of.html}}></ref>\n\nSpam is also an original ingredient in ''[[budae jjigae]]'' (literally \"army base stew\"), a spicy stew with different types of preserved meat.<ref>{{cite book |title=Korea in the middle: Korean studies and area studies : essays in honour of Boudewijn Walraven |last1=Walraven |first1=Boudewijn |first2=Remco E. |last2=Breuker |year=2007 |publisher=CNWS Publications |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-5789-153-3 |pages=255\u2013257 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yCDZtFu_1UIC&dq |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East===\nIn [[Mandatory Palestine]], demand for kosher canned meats increased as Spam became more popular during World War II. Canned meat was briefly mentioned during wartime from 1939\u201343, but the true boom in kosher canned meat came in 1945. This is when kosher canned meat became the key item in Europe's Jewish war victim relief packages. Then in 1946, the Chicago Kosher Sausage Manufacturing Company registered a patent for a kosher canned meat product called Breef. Made of beef, Breef has a similar texture to Spam but tastes like corned beef.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kosher Spam: A Breef History |url=http://www.jta.org/2011/11/20/the-archive-blog/kosher-spam-a-breef-history |accessdate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref> Also, a [[kosher]] variant of Spam, known as [[Loof]] ({{Lang-he|\u05dc\u05d5\u05e3}}, a Hebrew linguistic play on [[meatloaf]]), was produced by Richard Levi, and mostly used as part of [[field ration]]s by the [[Israel Defense Forces]]. A [[Glatt kosher]] version was also produced. It was phased out of field rations during the early 2000s and was finally removed from rations when production ceased in 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.mouse.co.il/CM.articles_item,1018,209,47535,.aspx|title=\u05d4\u05e6\u05d3\u05e2\u05d4 \u05dc\u05dc\u05d5\u05e3, \u05e9\u05d9\u05d9\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8\u05d5 \u05d4\u05d5\u05e4\u05e1\u05e7 \u05d1\u05d0\u05d7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\n|publisher=mouse.co.il|accessdate=September 19, 2010|trans-title= Salute for Loof, production of which was recently ceased in Israel}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[file:Spam Treet and Great Value Luncheon Meat.jpg|thumb|250px|Others have made similar products: Spam (L), [[Treet]] (C), and Walmart Great Value Luncheon Meat (R)]]\nBeginning in 1940, Spam sponsored [[George Burns]] and [[Gracie Allen]] on their [[George Burns#Radio stars|radio program]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U3rJxPYT32MC&pg=PA762&dq=burns+and+allen+and+1940+and+spam#v=onepage&q=burns%20%20allen%201940%20spam&f=false|title=The Guide to United States Popular Culture|author=Brown, Ray Broadus|page=762|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|date=2001|isbn=9780879728212}}</ref>\n\nDuring WWII, Spam was not only eaten but was also incorporated into many other aspects of the war (grease for guns, cans for scrap metal, etc.); it was so prominent that [[Uncle Sam]] was nicknamed \"Uncle Spam\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Civitello|first1=Linda|title=Cuisine and Culture: A History of Food and People|date=March 29, 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470403716|page=347|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uaRl9ZUtBYkC&pg=PA347}}</ref> Other terms influenced by the product's name include the European invasion fleet, or the \"Spam Fleet\". Furthermore, the [[United Service Organizations]] (USO) toured the \"Spam Circuit\".<ref name=\"OxfordSpam\"/>\n\nIn the United States in the aftermath of World War II, a troupe of former servicewomen was assembled by Hormel Foods to promote Spam from coast to coast. The group was known as the Hormel Girls and associated the food with being patriotic. In 1948, two years after its formation, the troupe had grown to 60 women with 16 forming an orchestra. The show went on to become a radio program where the main selling point was Spam. The Hormel Girls were disbanded in 1953.<ref>{{cite news|jstor=40071663|title=The Hormel Girls, ''American Music, Vol. 25, No. 3 (Fall, 2007), pp. 282\u2013311''| publisher=University of Illinois Press | first=Jill M. Sullivan | last=Danelle D. Keck | year=2007 }}</ref>\n\nSpam has long had a somewhat dubious reputation in the United States and (to a lesser degree) United Kingdom as a [[poverty food]]. The image of Spam as a low cost meat product gave rise to the Scottish colloquial term \"Spam valley\" to describe certain affluent housing areas where residents appear to be wealthy but in reality may be living at poverty levels.<ref>{{cite book |title=Human geography of the UK: an introduction |last1=Hardill |first1=Irene |first2=David |last2=Graham |first3=Eleonore |last3=Kofman |year=2001 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |isbn=978-0-415-21426-1 |pages=96\u201397 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NlQurpB-0aYC&dq |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSpam was featured in an iconic 1970 [[Monty Python]] sketch called \"[[Spam (Monty Python)|Spam]]\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> Set in a caf\u00e9 which mostly served dishes containing Spam, including \"egg and Spam, egg bacon and Spam, Spam egg sausage and Spam, Spam egg Spam Spam bacon and Spam \",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://montypython.net/scripts/spam.php |title=Spam |publisher=Monty Python |date= |accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> the piece also featured a companion song. Because of its use in a line of a song in ''[[Monty Python and the Holy Grail]]'', the title of the musical version of the film became ''[[Spamalot]]''.\n\nBy the 1990s, Spam's perceived ubiquity led to its name being adopted for [[Spam (electronic)|unsolicited electronic messages]], especially [[Spam (email)|spam email]].<ref>{{cite dictionary|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/spam|dictionary=Merriam-Webster|title=Merriam Webster Dictionary}}</ref> \n\nSpam is the subject of the [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]] song \"Spam\", which is a parody of the [[R.E.M.]] song \"[[Stand (R.E.M. song)|Stand]]\".<ref name=\"SPAMlyrics\">{{cite web\n| title=WEIRD AL YANKOVIC \u2013 SPAM LYRICS\n| url=http://www.songlyrics.com/weird-al-yankovic/spam-lyrics/\n| accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOther offshoots of Spam in popular culture include a book of [[haiku]]s about Spam titled ''Spam-Ku: Tranquil Reflections on Luncheon Loaf''. There is also a mock Church of Spam, and a Spam Cam which is a webcam trained on a can of decaying Spam.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Oxford Companion to American Food and Drink |isbn = 9780199885763|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GZVweuXhZlkC&pg=PA559 |accessdate=October 6, 2014 |last1 = Smith|first1 = Andrew F.|date = May 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1982 film ''[[Sophie's Choice (film)|Sophie's Choice]]'', the character Stingo brings a carton of Spam to his newly-rented room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/103307/tnr-film-classics-sophies-choice-january-10-1983|title=TNR Film Classics: 'Sophie's Choice' (January 10, 1983)|website=newrepublic.com|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSpam is referred to in ''[[Island of the Sequined Love Nun]]'' by [[Christopher Moore (author)|Christopher Moore]], where SPAM is explained as ''Shaped Pork Approximating Man'', which was used to explain its popularity amongst Pacific Island Cannibals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aol.com/article/2008/12/29/the-magical-mystical-world-of-spam/1413829/ |title=The magical, mystical world of SPAM - AOL Finance |publisher=Aol.com |date=December 29, 2008 |accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Pumpkin_Spice_Spam|Pumpkin Spice]] flavour, introduced in September 2019, has gained the attention of the media and public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/09/23/spam-pumpkin-spice-hormel-foods/2416749001/|title=Pumpkin spice version of Spam?! Hormel Foods introduces limited-edition Spam|last=Bomey|first=Nathan|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=September 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Spam celebrations===\n\n[[File:SpamMuseumAustinMN2006-05-20.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Former [[Spam Museum]] in [[Austin, Minnesota]]]]\n[[File:Spam Museum Sign.JPG|thumb|Facade of new [[Spam Museum]]]]\n\nSpam is celebrated in Austin, Minnesota, home to the [[Spam Museum]]. The museum tells the history of the Hormel company, the origin of Spam, and its place in world culture, including Hawaii where Spam is eaten daily by locals.\n\nAustin is also the location of final judging in the national Spam recipe competition. Competing recipes are collected from winning submissions at the top 40 state fairs in the nation. The Spamettes are a quartet from Austin who only sing about Spam in parodies of popular songs. They first performed at the first Spam Jam in 1990 and continue to perform at various events.<ref>{{cite web| title=Singing Spam's praises|url=http://www.austindailyherald.com/2008/07/singing-spams-praises/|date=July 7, 2008|accessdate=October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHawaii holds an annual [[Spam Jam]] in [[Waikiki]] during the last week of April.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spamjamhawaii.com/ |title=Spam Jam Waikiki 2010 |author=Hormel Foods |year=2010 |publisher=Hormel Foods Corporation |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref> The small town of [[Shady Cove, Oregon]] is home to the annual Spam Parade and Festival, with the city allocating US$1,500 for it.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://urindependent.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3573:shady-cove-issues-riparian-event-insurance-and-liability&catid=13:local&Itemid=35 |title=Shady Cove issues- riparian, event insurance and liability |newspaper=Upper Rogue Independent |first=Christy |last=Pitto |date=December 7, 2010 |accessdate=December 13, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717173519/http://urindependent.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3573:shady-cove-issues-riparian-event-insurance-and-liability&catid=13:local&Itemid=35 |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n[[Spamarama]] was a yearly festival held around [[April Fool's Day]] in [[Austin, Texas]]. The theme of Spamarama was a gentle parody of Spam, rather than a straightforward celebration: the event at the heart of the festival was a Spam [[cook-off]] that originated as a challenge to produce the most appetizing recipe for the meat. A rule of the event was that contestants had to be prepared to eat the Spam dish if requested by a judge. The festival included light sporting activities and musical acts, in addition to the cook-off.<ref name=\"Spamarama\">{{cite web\n| title=Spamarama website\n| url=http://www.Spamarama.org/\n| accessdate=August 11, 2006}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Nutritional data==\n[[File:Spam 2.jpg|thumb|A can of low-salt \"Spam 25% Less Sodium\"]]\n[[File:Spam Can Nutritional Label.jpg|thumb|Nutritional label for \"Spam 25% Less Sodium\"]]\nThe ingredients of Spam vary according to variety and market; those of variety \"Spam Classic\" are: pork, ham, salt, water, potato starch, sugar, and sodium nitrite.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spam.com/spam-101/what-is-spam-classic|title=What is Spam Classic?|website=Spam.com|publisher=Hormel Foods|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20150617231636/http://www.spam.com/spam%2D101/what%2Dis%2Dspam%2Dclassic|archive-date=June 17, 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=September 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Nutritional Information for Original Spam<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-C00001-01c20Nk.html|title=Nutritional Facts and Analysis for Spam|publisher=Nutritiondata.com|accessdate= July 5, 2013}}</ref>'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|\nNet weight per package: 340 grams (12 oz.)\n\nServing size: 100g\n|-\n!\n!Quantity per 100g\n|-\n| Energy || 1,300 kJ (310 [[Food energy|Calories or kilocalories]])\n|-\n| [[Protein]] || 13g (26% Daily Value or DV)\n|-\n| Total Fat || 27g (41% DV)\n|-\n| &emsp; \u2013 [[saturated fat]] || 10g (49% DV)\n|-\n| [[Carbohydrate]]s || 3g (1% DV)\n|-\n| Sodium || 1369&nbsp;mg (57% DV)\n|-\n| Cholesterol|| 70&nbsp;mg (23% DV)\n|-\n| [[Vitamin]]s and [[Dietary mineral|Minerals]] (% DV)|| 1% Vitamin C, 1% Calcium, 5% Iron,\n\n3% Magnesium, 9% Potassium, 12% Zinc,\n\nand 5% Copper\n|}\n\n==Varieties==\nAs listed on the official Spam website, there are numerous different flavors of Spam products, including:\n* Spam Classic \u2013 original flavor\n* Spam Hot & Spicy \u2013 with [[Tabasco sauce|Tabasco]] flavor\n* Jalape\u00f1o Spam\n* Spam with Black Pepper\n* Spam Low Sodium \u2013 \"25% less sodium\"\n* Spam Lite \u2013 \"33% fewer calories, 25% less sodium, and 50% less fat\" \u2013 made from pork with ham, and mechanically separated chicken\n* Spam Oven Roasted Turkey\n* Spam Hickory Smoked\n* Spam Spread \u2013 \"if you're a spreader, not a slicer&nbsp;... just like Spam Classic, but in a spreadable form\"\n* Spam Bacon\n* Spam Cheese\n* Spam Garlic\n* Spam Teriyaki\n* Spam Chorizo \n* Spam Boricua \u2013 seasoned Puerto Rican-style flavor\n* Spam Macadamia Nuts \u2013 Partnered with Hamakua Plantation\n* Spam Turkey\n* Spam Tocino\n* Spam Portuguese Sausage\n*[[Pumpkin Spice Spam|Spam Pumpkin Spice]] - limited edition variety released in late September 2019\n* In addition to the variety of flavors, Spam is sold in tins smaller than the twelve-ounce standard size. Spam Singles are also available, which are single sandwich-sized slices of Spam Classic or Lite, sealed in [[retort pouch]]es.<ref name=\"varieties\">{{cite web|url=https://store.spam.com/products/default.aspx|title=SPAM&copy; Products|publisher=Store.spam.com|accessdate=July 5, 2013}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* {{annotated link|Bologna sausage}}\n* {{annotated link|Breakfast}}\n* {{annotated link|Corned beef}}\n* {{annotated link|Loco moco}} \u2013 a Hawaiian dish that uses Spam in some versions\n* {{annotated link|Pork roll}}\n* {{annotated link|Potted meat food product}}\n* {{annotated link|Spam (Monty Python)}} - Humour and Song\n* {{annotated link|Treet}}\n* {{annotated link|Tushonka}} \u2013 a canned, stewed meat\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wiktionary|spam}} \n* {{Official website|http://www.spam.com}} \u2013 United States\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170213164423/http://gogd.tjs-labs.com/gallery-view?product=spam Collection of mid-twentieth century advertising featuring Spam] from The TJS Labs Gallery of Graphic Design.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spam (Food)}}\n[[Category:American brands]]\n[[Category:Brand name meats]]\n[[Category:Hawaiian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Hormel brands]]\n[[Category:Pork]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1937]]\n[[Category:Spam (food)|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the luncheon meat brand|the practice of sending unsolicited messages|Spamming|other uses|Spam (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Canned cooked pork meat product}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Spam\n| image            = [[File:SPAM logo.jpg|150px]]\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   =\n| country          = US  \n| region           =\n| creator          = [[Hormel|Hormel Foods Corporation]]\n| founded          = 1936 (80 years ago) \n| course           = Main course or ingredient\n| served           = Hot or cold\n| main_ingredient  = [[Pork]] \n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            = A precooked [[Canning|canned]] meat product}}\n'''Spam''' (stylized as '''SPAM''') is a brand of [[canning|canned]] cooked pork made by [[Hormel Foods Corporation]], based in [[Minnesota]]. It was first introduced in 1937 and gained popularity worldwide after its use during [[World War II]].<ref name=\"SeriousSpam\" /> By 2003, Spam was sold in 41 countries on six continents and trademarked in over 100 countries (not including the [[Middle East]] and [[North Africa]]).<ref name=\"hormelgoddess\">{{cite web | url= http://www.hormelfoods.com/brands/spam/ | publisher = Hormel Foods |year=2010 |title = Spam \u2013 Postwar Popularity|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215030819/http://www.hormelfoods.com/brands/spam/|archivedate=December 15, 2007}}</ref> Spam's basic ingredients are [[pork]] with [[ham]] meat added, salt, water, [[modified potato starch]] (as a [[Binder (material)|binder]]), sugar, and [[sodium nitrite]] (as a [[preservative]]). Natural [[gelatin]] is formed during cooking in its [[tin can|tins]] on the [[production line]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=Belinda|last2=Clapton|first2=Barbara|last3=Tipton|first3=Catherine|title=Food Technology|page=20|publisher=Heinemann|year=2002}}</ref> Many have raised concerns over Spam's [[nutritional]] attributes, in large part due to its high content of fat, [[Health effects of salt|sodium]], and [[preservative]]s.<ref>https://science.howstuffworks.com/innovation/edible-innovations/spam-food1.htm</ref>\n\nIt has become the subject of several appearances in pop culture, notably [[Spam (Monty Python)|a Monty Python sketch]], which led to its name being borrowed for [[Spamming|unsolicited electronic messages]], especially [[Email spam|email]].<ref name=\"tools.ietf.org\">{{cite web | url = http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2635 | title = RFC 2635 \u2013 DON'T SPEW A Set of Guidelines for Mass Unsolicited Mailings and Postings (spam*) | accessdate = September 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Sliced Spam.JPG|thumb|Sliced Spam]]\nSpam was introduced by Hormel on July 5, 1937.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America states that the product was intended to increase the sale of pork shoulder which was not a very popular cut.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|last=Waxman |first=Olivia B. |url=http://time.com/4827451/spam-history-80th-anniversary/ |title=Spam Turns 80: History and Origins of Canned Meat |publisher=Time.com |date=July 5, 2017 |accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> Ken Daigneau, brother of a company executive, won a $100 prize that year in a competition to name the new item.<ref name = \"history\" /> Hormel claims that the meaning of the name \"is known by only a small circle of former Hormel Foods executives\", but popular beliefs are that the name is an abbreviation of \"spiced ham\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><ref>{{Citation | contribution-url = http://www.spam.com/about | title = SPAM\u00ae Brand FAQ | contribution = What does the SPAM brand name mean? | publisher = Spam}}</ref>\nThe difficulty of delivering fresh meat to the front during World War II saw Spam become a ubiquitous part of the U.S. soldier's diet. It became variously referred to as \"ham that didn't pass its physical\", \"meatloaf without basic training\",<ref name = \"SeriousSpam\" /> and \"Special Army Meat\". Over {{convert|150|e6lb|t|order=flip|abbr=off}} of Spam were purchased by the military before the war's end.<ref name = \"OxfordSpam\" />\n\nDuring World War II and the occupations which followed, Spam was introduced into [[Guam]], [[Hawaii]], [[Okinawa]], the [[Philippines]], and other islands in the Pacific. Immediately absorbed into native diets, it has become a unique part of the history and effects of U.S. influence in the Pacific islands.<ref name=\"BurgerKingSpam\" />\n\nAs a consequence of [[Rationing in the United Kingdom|World War II rationing]] and the [[Lend-Lease Act]], Spam also gained prominence in the United Kingdom. British Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] later referred to it as a \"wartime delicacy\".<ref name=npr.org>{{cite news|author1=Howard Yoon|title=Spam: More than Junk Mail or Junk Meat|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=11714236|issue=npr.org|date=July 4, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stranska|first1=Hana|title=About Spam|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/24/magazine/l-about-spam-740128.html|accessdate=October 1, 2014|work=The New York Times|date=July 24, 1994|ref=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/24/magazine/l-about-spam-740128.html}}</ref> In addition to increasing production for the U.K., Hormel expanded Spam output as part of Allied aid to the similarly beleaguered Soviet Union.<ref>{{cite book|title=Creating Minnesota: A History From the Inside Out|last=Atkins|first=Annette|year=2007|publisher=Minnesota Historical Society|location=Minnesota|isbn=978-0-87351-633-4|page=194|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUP6lBSdlrwC&pg |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref> In his memoir ''Khrushchev Remembers'', [[Nikita Khrushchev]] declared: \"Without Spam we wouldn't have been able to feed our army.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Smith|editor-first=Andrew F.|year=2012|title=The Oxford Encyclopaedia of Food and Drink in America|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=343|isbn=978-0199734962}}</ref> Throughout the war, countries ravaged by the conflict and faced with strict food rations came to appreciate Spam.<ref>Heydt, Bruce. \"Spam Again\" . America in WWII, June 2006.</ref>\n\nThe billionth can of Spam was sold in 1959,<ref>{{Citation |title=Spam Is Turning 80. Here's How the Canned Meat Took Over the World |last=Waxman |first=Olivia B. |date=July 5, 2017 |work=time.com |url= http://time.com/4827451/spam-history-80th-anniversary/ |accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref> the seven billionth can was sold in 2007,<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web | url= http://www.spam.com/about | title= Spam Brand History | accessdate= November 27, 2016 | publisher= Spam | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161127014422/http://www.spam.com/about | archive-date= November 27, 2016 | url-status= dead }}</ref> and the eight billionth can was sold in 2012.<ref>{{Citation |title=For Spam's 80th anniversary, 10 outrageous retro recipes by the Minnesota meat maker |first=Sharyn |last=Jackson |date= July 5, 2017 |work=startribune.com |url= http://www.startribune.com/for-spam-s-80th-anniversary-10-outrageous-retro-recipes-by-the-minn-meat-maker/432686623/ |accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International usage==\n===United States and territories===\n[[image:Baked Spam with Cloves.jpg|thumb|right|225px|Baked Spam]]\nDomestically, Spam's chief advantages were affordability, accessibility, and extended shelf life.<ref name=\"OxfordSpam\">{{cite book |last =Smith|first = Andrew |title=The Oxford Companion to American Food and Drink|date= May 1, 2007 | publisher= Oxford University Press|isbn = 978-0-19988576-3|pages = 559\u201360 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=GZVweuXhZlkC&pg=PA559}}</ref> At the time it was introduced, it was the only canned meat product on the market that needed no refrigeration.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ruvio|first=Ayalla A.|title=How Spam became one of the most iconic American brands of all time|url=https://theconversation.com/how-spam-became-one-of-the-most-iconic-american-brands-of-all-time-80030|accessdate=July 6, 2017|work=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|date=July 2, 2017}}</ref> Statistics from the 1990s say that 3.8 cans of Spam were consumed every second in the United States,<ref>{{cite magazine |last=|first= |title=Data Stream|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=25|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=January 1997|page=28}}</ref> totaling nearly 122 million cans annually. It became part of the diet of almost 30% of American households, perceived differently in various regions of the country.<ref>Kim, Sojin; Livengood, Mark (1995). [http://digest.champlain.edu/archivepdf/DIGESTvol15.pdf \u201cRamen Noodles and Spam: Popular Foods, Significant Tastes\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006180722/http://digest.champlain.edu/archivepdf/DIGESTvol15.pdf |date=October 6, 2014 }}, pp. 2\u201311. Retrieved September 18, 2014.</ref> It is also sometimes associated with economic hardship because of its relatively low cost.<ref name=\"SeriousSpam\" >{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/15/business/15spam.html|title=Spam Turns Serious and Hormel Turns Out More |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |first=Andrew |last=Martin |date=November 15, 2008 |accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSpam that is sold in North America, South America, and Australia is produced in [[Austin, Minnesota]] (also known as \"Spam Town USA\") and in [[Fremont, Nebraska]].<ref>Wyman, Carolyn. \"Spam: A Biography.\" Harvest Books, 1999</ref> Austin, Minnesota also has a restaurant with a menu devoted exclusively to Spam, called \"Johnny's SPAMarama Menu\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Spam Turns Serious and Hormel Turns Out More|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 14, 2008|accessdate=July 5, 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/15/business/15spam.html}}</ref>\n\n==== Hawaii ====\n[[File:Spam musubi at Ninja Sushi.jpg|thumb|right|[[Spam musubi]] is a popular snack and lunch food in [[Hawaiian food|Hawaii]]]]\nSpam is especially popular in the state of Hawaii, where residents have the highest per capita consumption in the United States. Its perception there is very different from on the mainland.<ref>{{cite book |title=Fashionable food: seven decades of food fads |last=Lovegren |first=Sylvia |year=2005 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=United States |isbn=978-0-226-49407-4 |page=190 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fZIRc28P5xYC&dq |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref> Hawaiians sometimes call it \"Portagee Steak\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Hawaii's Spam Cookbook |last=Corum |first=Ann Kondo |year=1987 |publisher=Bess Press |location=United States |isbn=0935848495|page=135|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8eTPLr0f2h0C&pg=PA135&lpg=PA135#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA popular local dish in Hawaii is [[Spam musubi]], where cooked Spam is placed atop [[rice]] and wrapped in a band of [[nori]], a form of ''[[onigiri]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatscookingamerica.net/History/Spam.htm|title=Spam&nbsp;\u2013 Hawaiian Spam Musubi|publisher=Whatscookingamerica.net|accessdate=July 5, 2013}}</ref>\nVarieties of Spam are found in Hawaii that are unavailable in other markets, including Honey Spam, Spam with Bacon, and Hot and Spicy Spam.<ref name=\"Star\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/2007/06/11/burger_giants_wage_spam_war.html |first=Jaymes |last=Song |date=June 11, 2007|work=The Star|title=Burger giants wage Spam war | location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\nHawaiian [[Burger King]] restaurants began serving Spam in 2007 to compete with the local [[McDonald's]] chains (which also serve Spam).<ref name=\"BurgerKingSpam\" >{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070611/ap_on_bi_ge/burger_king_Spam|title=Burger King to Serve Spam in Hawaii|publisher=Yahoo! News|accessdate=July 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kare11.com/news/news_article.aspx?storyid=254168|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120605005816/http://www.kare11.com/news/news_article.aspx?storyid=254168|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 5, 2012|title=Land of 10,000 Stories&nbsp;\u2013 Spam in Paradise|publisher=KARE11 News|first=Boyd|last=Huppert|date=May 17, 2007}}</ref> In Hawaii, Spam is so popular that it is sometimes referred to as \"The Hawaiian Steak\".<ref>{{cite news |title= The Spam That Isn't Via E-Mail |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E6DB1338F934A35757C0A9659C8B63 |work=The New York Times |date=April 7, 2003 |accessdate=December 28, 2007 }}</ref> There is even an annual Spam-themed festival on the island of Oahu that takes place every spring, known as the \"Waikiki Spam Jam\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spamjamhawaii.com/|title=Welcome - Waikiki Spam Jam|last=|first=|date=|website=Welcome|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2017}}</ref> Local chefs and restaurants compete to create new Spam-themed dishes, which are then sold in a massive street fair on Kalakaua Avenue in Waikiki.\n\nIn 2017, Hawaii was plagued by a rash of thefts of Spam.<ref name=\"SpamHeistsSingh\">{{cite news|last1=Singh|first1=Lakshmi|title=Hawaii's Spate Of Spam Heists|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/10/22/559403062/hawaiis-spate-of-spam-heists|accessdate=October 23, 2017|work=[[NPR]]|date=October 22, 2017}}</ref> Spam had long been a target of thieves in Hawaii, but the magnitude of the thefts ramped up, with incidents in which multiple cases of Spam were stolen at once. Local retailers believe organized crime was involved.<ref name=\"SpamHeistsSingh\"/> This came alongside increases in thefts of some other retail goods, such as [[corned beef]] and liquor. The president of the retail merchants of Hawaii attributed the rise in retail thefts to a recent change in criminal law, which raised the threshold at which a theft would lead to [[felony]] charges by approximately $400.<ref name=\"SpamHeistsSingh\"/>\n\n==== Guam and the Northern Marianas ====\nIn [[Guam]], average per capita consumption is 16 tins (cans) per year. It is also found on McDonald's menus there. The ''Spam Games'' also takes place in Guam, where locals sample and honor the best original, homemade Spam recipes.<ref>{{cite web | title =Why is Spam Brand a Household Name? | url =http://www.spam.com/spam-101/why-is-spam-a-household-brand | accessdate =October 6, 2014 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141010035126/http://www.spam.com/spam-101/why-is-spam-a-household-brand | archivedate =October 10, 2014 | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Northern Mariana Islands]], lawyers from Hormel have threatened to sue the local press for publishing articles alleging ill-effects of high Spam consumption on the health of the local population.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?newsID=59528&cat=3 |title=Organic smoke (and mirrors) |work=Saipan Tribune |date=July 21, 2006 |accessdate=June 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623203856/http://www.saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?newsID=59528&cat=3 |archivedate=June 23, 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?cat=3&newsID=59336 |title=A junkie waiting to happen |work=Saipan Tribune |date=July 14, 2006 |accessdate=June 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623203851/http://saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?cat=3&newsID=59336 |archivedate=June 23, 2008  }}</ref>\n\n==== Puerto Rico ====\nSandwich de Mezcla is a party staple in [[Puerto Rico]] containing Spam, [[Velveeta]], and [[pimiento]]s (made into a spread) between two slices of [[sandwich bread]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cafeculinario.com/2013/08/12/receta-sandwichitos-para-fiestas/|title=Receta: Sandwichitos para fiestas|date=August 12, 2013|accessdate=October 6, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141007220541/http://cafeculinario.com/2013/08/12/receta-sandwichitos-para-fiestas/|archivedate=October 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nAfter World War II, Newforge Foods, part of the Fitch Lovell group, was awarded the license to produce the product in the UK at its Gateacre factory, [[Liverpool]],<ref>The story of Fitch Lovell Ambrose Keevil Phillimore Press 1972 {{ISBN|978-0-85033-074-8}}</ref> where it stayed until production switched to the [[Danish Crown AmbA|Danish Crown Group]] (owners of the Tulip Food Company) in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.tulip.dk/ |title=Tulip Food Company |publisher=english.tulip.dk |accessdate=June 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814170842/http://english.tulip.dk/ |archivedate=August 14, 2009  }}</ref>\n\nThe United Kingdom has adopted Spam into various recipes. For example, recipes include Spam Yorkshire Breakfast, Spamish Omelette, and Spam Hash.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spam\u2014UK |url=http://www.spam-uk.com/recipes/ |accessdate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref> Spam can also be sliced, battered and [[Deep frying|deep-fried]] into [[Spam fritter]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spam Fritters |url=http://www.lbhf.gov.uk/Images/Spam_fritters_tcm21-170915.pdf |accessdate=October 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010114629/http://www.lbhf.gov.uk/Images/Spam_fritters_tcm21-170915.pdf |archivedate=October 10, 2014  }}</ref>\n\n===Southeast Asia===\n====Philippines====\n[[File:Spam Meal.jpg|thumb|\"[[Spamilog]]\", Spam with ''[[sinang\u00e1g]]'' (garlic [[fried rice]]) and [[Egg as food|eggs]], is a common [[Filipino food|Filipino]] breakfast combination.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casey |first1=Nell |title=Stay Warm With Filipino Brunch & A Cookie Competition This Weekend |url=http://gothamist.com/2016/12/16/weekend_food_roundup_97.php |accessdate=20 January 2019 |work=Gothamist |agency=WNYC |date=16 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224150751/http://gothamist.com/2016/12/16/weekend_food_roundup_97.php |archive-date=February 24, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>]]\n\nIn the Philippines, Spam (currently distributed by [[San_Miguel_Food_and_Beverage#Subsidiaries|The Purefoods-Hormel Company Inc.]]) is a popular food item and seen as a cultural symbol. As a former US territory, Spam reached the islands similar to how it reached [[Hawaii]] and [[Guam]]: as a result of [[World War II]] rationing. Spam is commonly eaten with rice (usually [[garlic fried rice]]) and a sunny-side up egg for breakfast. It is prepared and used in a variety of ways, including being fried, served alongside condiments, or used in sandwiches. It has also been featured in numerous Filipino [[fusion cuisine]] dishes including Spam burgers, Spam [[Filipino spaghetti|spaghetti]], Spam nuggets, and others.<ref name=\"Escalona2017\">{{cite news |last1=Escalona |first1=Katrina |work=Culture Trip|title=Why Spam and Rice is a Filipino Food Classic |url=https://theculturetrip.com/asia/philippines/articles/why-spam-and-rice-is-a-filipino-food-classic/ |accessdate=20 January 2019 |date=18 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ke |first1=Bryan |title=Why Filipinos Love Spam So Much |url=https://nextshark.com/filipinos-love-spam-much/ |accessdate=20 January 2019 |work=NextShark |date=12 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Agoncillo |first1=Anna |title=What Is SPAM And Why Are Filipinos Obsessed With It? |url=https://remit.com.au/what-is-spam-and-why-are-filipinos-obsessed-with-it/ |accessdate=20 January 2019 |work=RemitBlog |date=29 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120144353/https://remit.com.au/what-is-spam-and-why-are-filipinos-obsessed-with-it/ |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ong |first1=Sherina |title=SPAM: A story of love and hate |url=https://www.rappler.com/move-ph/balikbayan/identity/60979-spam-love-hate |accessdate=20 January 2019 |work=Rappler |date=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe popularity of Spam in the [[Philippines]] transcends economic class, and Spam gift sets are even used as homecoming gifts. There are at least ten different varieties of Spam currently available in the country and an estimated 1.25&nbsp;million kilos of the meat is sold every year in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite journal |last = Matejowsky |first = Ty |title = SPAM and Fast-food \"Glocalization\" in the Philippines |journal = Food, Culture and Society: An International Journal of Multidisciplinary Research |volume = 10 |issue = 1 |pages = 23\u201341 |date = March 1, 2007 |doi = 10.2752/155280107780154088 }}</ref> During the rescue efforts after [[Typhoon Ketsana|Typhoon Ondoy]] (Ketsana) in 2009, Hormel Foods donated over 30,000&nbsp;pounds of Spam to the [[Philippine National Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.webwire.com/ViewPressRel.asp?aId=105336 |title= Hormel Foods Announces Donation to Philippines | work=Web wire |date = October 8, 2009 | accessdate =September 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===East Asia===\n[[File:Spam served with rice.jpg|thumb|upright|Spam is often served with rice in [[Asian cuisine|Asia]].]]\n\n====China====\nIn China, Hormel decided to adopt a different strategy to market Spam, promoting it as a foreign, premium food product and changing the Spam formula to be meatier in order to accommodate local Chinese tastes.<ref name=\"china businessweek\">{{cite web | title = Spam's Long March in China | url = http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/spams-long-march-in-china-08042011.html | work = Bloomberg BusinessWeek | date = August 4, 2011 | accessdate = October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Japan====\nIn [[Okinawan cuisine|Okinawa]], [[Japanese cuisine|Japan]], the product is added into [[onigiri]] alongside eggs and used as a staple ingredient in the traditional Okinawan dish ''[[chanpur\u016b]]'', and a Spam burger is sold by local fast food chain [[Jef (fast food restaurant)|Jef]]. For the 70th anniversary of Spam in 2007, cans with special designs were sold in Japan due to its popularity, primarily in Okinawa.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/idINT22925620080312|title=Okinawa cuisine: tofu, Spam and root beer | agency=Reuters | first=Linda | last=Sieg |date=March 12, 2008 |accessdate=September 24, 2010}}</ref>\nFollowing the March 2011 earthquake, Spam sales in Japan declined and Hormel shifted its focus to China,<ref name=\"china businessweek\"/> although Hormel did pledge to donate $100,000 along with cans of Spam for relief efforts.<ref>{{cite news | title = Hormel Foods Pledges to Relief Efforts in Japan | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/17/idUS140792+17-Mar-2011+BW20110317 | agency = Reuters | date = March 17, 2011 | accessdate = October 6, 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141010204435/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/17/idUS140792+17-Mar-2011+BW20110317 | archivedate = October 10, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\nIn the summer of 2011, Burger King introduced its own version of a burger made of Spam, called 'BK Shot' Spam Burgers. These small burgers are filled with slices of the canned meat and were an attempt by Burger King to capitalize on Spam's popularity in Japan.<ref>{{cite web | title = Forget Spam fritters, now Burger King is selling Spam burgers\u2026 for women | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2003298/Burger-King-sell-Spam-burgers-Japan--women.html | work = Daily Mail | date = June 15, 2011 | accessdate = October 5, 2014}}</ref> In early 2014, Burger King also introduced the Spam and Cheese burger as a breakfast menu item.<ref>{{cite news | last = Bleier | first = Evan | title = Burger King introduces Spam and cheese burger in Japan, for breakfast | url = http://www.upi.com/Odd_News/2014/05/01/Burger-King-introduces-SPAM-and-cheese-burger-in-Japan-for-breakfast/7611398966149/ | agency = United Press International | date = May 1, 2014 | accessdate = October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Hong Kong====\nIn [[Cuisine of Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] after World War II, meat was scarce and expensive, so Spam was an accessible, affordable alternative. The luncheon meat has been incorporated into dishes such as macaroni with fried egg and spam in chicken soup, as well as [[ramen]].<ref>{{cite web |title = Why is Spam served in Hong Kong diners on top of macaroni noodles? | work = HK Magazine | url = http://hk-magazine.com/restaurants/column/why-spam-served-hong-kong-diners-top-macaroni-noodles |accessdate= October 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nIn later years, the surfeit of Spam in both North and South Korea during the [[Korean War]] led to the establishment of the Spam ''[[kimbap]]'' (rice and vegetable filled seaweed roll). Because of a scarcity of fish and other traditional kimbap products such as kimchi or fermented cabbage, Spam was added to a rice roll with kimchi and cucumber and wrapped in seaweed. Spam was also used by US soldiers in Korea as a means of trading for items, services or information around their bases.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2014/09/05/in-korea-its-spam-time-of-year/|title=In Korea, It's Spam Time of Year}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Korean cuisine|South Korea]], Spam ({{ko-hhrm|hangul= \uc2a4\ud338 |rr=seupaem}}, licensed from Hormel by [[CJ CheilJedang]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cj.co.kr/cj-kr/brands/spam|title=\uc2a4\ud338 (SPAM)|publisher=[[CJ CheilJedang]]|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref>) is popular with a majority of the population, and outranks [[Coca-Cola]] and [[KFC]] in status as a foodstuff. Today, South Korea produces and consumes more Spam than any other country except the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|title=From Minnesota Fat to Seoul Food: Spam in America and the Pacific Rim|last=Lewis|first=George H.|publisher=The Journal of Popular Culture, volume 34, issue 2|year=2004}}, [http://0-onlinelibrary.wiley.com.mercury.concordia.ca/doi/10.1111/j.0022-3840.2000.3402_83.x/pdf]</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=In South Korea, Spam Is the Stuff Gifts Are Made Of | work = The New York Times | date = January 26, 2014 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/27/world/asia/in-south-korea-spam-is-the-stuff-gifts-are-made-of.html}}></ref>\n\nSpam is also an original ingredient in ''[[budae jjigae]]'' (literally \"army base stew\"), a spicy stew with different types of preserved meat.<ref>{{cite book |title=Korea in the middle: Korean studies and area studies : essays in honour of Boudewijn Walraven |last1=Walraven |first1=Boudewijn |first2=Remco E. |last2=Breuker |year=2007 |publisher=CNWS Publications |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-5789-153-3 |pages=255\u2013257 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yCDZtFu_1UIC&dq |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East===\nIn [[Mandatory Palestine]], demand for kosher canned meats increased as Spam became more popular during World War II. Canned meat was briefly mentioned during wartime from 1939\u201343, but the true boom in kosher canned meat came in 1945. This is when kosher canned meat became the key item in Europe's Jewish war victim relief packages. Then in 1946, the Chicago Kosher Sausage Manufacturing Company registered a patent for a kosher canned meat product called Breef. Made of beef, Breef has a similar texture to Spam but tastes like corned beef.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kosher Spam: A Breef History |url=http://www.jta.org/2011/11/20/the-archive-blog/kosher-spam-a-breef-history |accessdate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref> Also, a [[kosher]] variant of Spam, known as [[Loof]] ({{Lang-he|\u05dc\u05d5\u05e3}}, a Hebrew linguistic play on [[meatloaf]]), was produced by Richard Levi, and mostly used as part of [[field ration]]s by the [[Israel Defense Forces]]. A [[Glatt kosher]] version was also produced. It was phased out of field rations during the early 2000s and was finally removed from rations when production ceased in 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.mouse.co.il/CM.articles_item,1018,209,47535,.aspx|title=\u05d4\u05e6\u05d3\u05e2\u05d4 \u05dc\u05dc\u05d5\u05e3, \u05e9\u05d9\u05d9\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8\u05d5 \u05d4\u05d5\u05e4\u05e1\u05e7 \u05d1\u05d0\u05d7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\n|publisher=mouse.co.il|accessdate=September 19, 2010|trans-title= Salute for Loof, production of which was recently ceased in Israel}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[file:Spam Treet and Great Value Luncheon Meat.jpg|thumb|250px|Others have made similar products: Spam (L), [[Treet]] (C), and Walmart Great Value Luncheon Meat (R)]]\nBeginning in 1940, Spam sponsored [[George Burns]] and [[Gracie Allen]] on their [[George Burns#Radio stars|radio program]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U3rJxPYT32MC&pg=PA762&dq=burns+and+allen+and+1940+and+spam#v=onepage&q=burns%20%20allen%201940%20spam&f=false|title=The Guide to United States Popular Culture|author=Brown, Ray Broadus|page=762|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|date=2001|isbn=9780879728212}}</ref>\n\nDuring WWII, Spam was not only eaten but was also incorporated into many other aspects of the war (grease for guns, cans for scrap metal, etc.); it was so prominent that [[Uncle Sam]] was nicknamed \"Uncle Spam\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Civitello|first1=Linda|title=Cuisine and Culture: A History of Food and People|date=March 29, 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470403716|page=347|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uaRl9ZUtBYkC&pg=PA347}}</ref> Other terms influenced by the product's name include the European invasion fleet, or the \"Spam Fleet\". Furthermore, the [[United Service Organizations]] (USO) toured the \"Spam Circuit\".<ref name=\"OxfordSpam\"/>\n\nIn the United States in the aftermath of World War II, a troupe of former servicewomen was assembled by Hormel Foods to promote Spam from coast to coast. The group was known as the Hormel Girls and associated the food with being patriotic. In 1948, two years after its formation, the troupe had grown to 60 women with 16 forming an orchestra. The show went on to become a radio program where the main selling point was Spam. The Hormel Girls were disbanded in 1953.<ref>{{cite news|jstor=40071663|title=The Hormel Girls, ''American Music, Vol. 25, No. 3 (Fall, 2007), pp. 282\u2013311''| publisher=University of Illinois Press | first=Jill M. Sullivan | last=Danelle D. Keck | year=2007 }}</ref>\n\nSpam has long had a somewhat dubious reputation in the United States and (to a lesser degree) United Kingdom as a [[poverty food]]. The image of Spam as a low cost meat product gave rise to the Scottish colloquial term \"Spam valley\" to describe certain affluent housing areas where residents appear to be wealthy but in reality may be living at poverty levels.<ref>{{cite book |title=Human geography of the UK: an introduction |last1=Hardill |first1=Irene |first2=David |last2=Graham |first3=Eleonore |last3=Kofman |year=2001 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |isbn=978-0-415-21426-1 |pages=96\u201397 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NlQurpB-0aYC&dq |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSpam was featured in an iconic 1970 [[Monty Python]] sketch called \"[[Spam (Monty Python)|Spam]]\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> Set in a caf\u00e9 which mostly served dishes containing Spam, including \"egg and Spam, egg bacon and Spam, Spam egg sausage and Spam, Spam egg Spam Spam bacon and Spam \",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://montypython.net/scripts/spam.php |title=Spam |publisher=Monty Python |date= |accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> the piece also featured a companion song. Because of its use in a line of a song in ''[[Monty Python and the Holy Grail]]'', the title of the musical version of the film became ''[[Spamalot]]''.\n\nBy the 1990s, Spam's perceived ubiquity led to its name being adopted for [[Spam (electronic)|unsolicited electronic messages]], especially [[Spam (email)|spam email]].<ref>{{cite dictionary|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/spam|dictionary=Merriam-Webster|title=Merriam Webster Dictionary}}</ref> \n\nSpam is the subject of the [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]] song \"Spam\", which is a parody of the [[R.E.M.]] song \"[[Stand (R.E.M. song)|Stand]]\".<ref name=\"SPAMlyrics\">{{cite web\n| title=WEIRD AL YANKOVIC \u2013 SPAM LYRICS\n| url=http://www.songlyrics.com/weird-al-yankovic/spam-lyrics/\n| accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOther offshoots of Spam in popular culture include a book of [[haiku]]s about Spam titled ''Spam-Ku: Tranquil Reflections on Luncheon Loaf''. There is also a mock Church of Spam, and a Spam Cam which is a webcam trained on a can of decaying Spam.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Oxford Companion to American Food and Drink |isbn = 9780199885763|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GZVweuXhZlkC&pg=PA559 |accessdate=October 6, 2014 |last1 = Smith|first1 = Andrew F.|date = May 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1982 film ''[[Sophie's Choice (film)|Sophie's Choice]]'', the character Stingo brings a carton of Spam to his newly-rented room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/103307/tnr-film-classics-sophies-choice-january-10-1983|title=TNR Film Classics: 'Sophie's Choice' (January 10, 1983)|website=newrepublic.com|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSpam is referred to in ''[[Island of the Sequined Love Nun]]'' by [[Christopher Moore (author)|Christopher Moore]], where SPAM is explained as ''Shaped Pork Approximating Man'', which was used to explain its popularity amongst Pacific Island Cannibals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aol.com/article/2008/12/29/the-magical-mystical-world-of-spam/1413829/ |title=The magical, mystical world of SPAM - AOL Finance |publisher=Aol.com |date=December 29, 2008 |accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Pumpkin_Spice_Spam|Pumpkin Spice]] flavour, introduced in September 2019, has gained the attention of the media and public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/09/23/spam-pumpkin-spice-hormel-foods/2416749001/|title=Pumpkin spice version of Spam?! Hormel Foods introduces limited-edition Spam|last=Bomey|first=Nathan|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\n===Spam celebrations===\n\n[[File:SpamMuseumAustinMN2006-05-20.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Former [[Spam Museum]] in [[Austin, Minnesota]]]]\n[[File:Spam Museum Sign.JPG|thumb|Facade of new [[Spam Museum]]]]\n\nSpam is celebrated in Austin, Minnesota, home to the [[Spam Museum]]. The museum tells the history of the Hormel company, the origin of Spam, and its place in world culture, including Hawaii where Spam is eaten daily by locals.\n\nAustin is also the location of final judging in the national Spam recipe competition. Competing recipes are collected from winning submissions at the top 40 state fairs in the nation. The Spamettes are a quartet from Austin who only sing about Spam in parodies of popular songs. They first performed at the first Spam Jam in 1990 and continue to perform at various events.<ref>{{cite web| title=Singing Spam's praises|url=http://www.austindailyherald.com/2008/07/singing-spams-praises/|date=July 7, 2008|accessdate=October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHawaii holds an annual [[Spam Jam]] in [[Waikiki]] during the last week of April.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spamjamhawaii.com/ |title=Spam Jam Waikiki 2010 |author=Hormel Foods |year=2010 |publisher=Hormel Foods Corporation |accessdate=December 13, 2010}}</ref> The small town of [[Shady Cove, Oregon]] is home to the annual Spam Parade and Festival, with the city allocating US$1,500 for it.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://urindependent.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3573:shady-cove-issues-riparian-event-insurance-and-liability&catid=13:local&Itemid=35 |title=Shady Cove issues- riparian, event insurance and liability |newspaper=Upper Rogue Independent |first=Christy |last=Pitto |date=December 7, 2010 |accessdate=December 13, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717173519/http://urindependent.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3573:shady-cove-issues-riparian-event-insurance-and-liability&catid=13:local&Itemid=35 |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Spamarama]] was a yearly festival held around [[April Fool's Day]] in [[Austin, Texas]]. The theme of Spamarama was a gentle parody of Spam, rather than a straightforward celebration: the event at the heart of the festival was a Spam [[cook-off]] that originated as a challenge to produce the most appetizing recipe for the meat. A rule of the event was that contestants had to be prepared to eat the Spam dish if requested by a judge. The festival included light sporting activities and musical acts, in addition to the cook-off.<ref name=\"Spamarama\">{{cite web\n| title=Spamarama website\n| url=http://www.Spamarama.org/\n| accessdate=August 11, 2006}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Nutritional data==\n[[File:Spam 2.jpg|thumb|A can of low-salt \"Spam 25% Less Sodium\"]]\n[[File:Spam Can Nutritional Label.jpg|thumb|Nutritional label for \"Spam 25% Less Sodium\"]]\nThe ingredients of Spam vary according to variety and market; those of variety \"Spam Classic\" are: pork, ham, salt, water, potato starch, sugar, and sodium nitrite.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spam.com/spam-101/what-is-spam-classic|title=What is Spam Classic?|website=Spam.com|publisher=Hormel Foods|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20150617231636/http://www.spam.com/spam%2D101/what%2Dis%2Dspam%2Dclassic|archive-date=June 17, 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=September 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Nutritional Information for Original Spam<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-C00001-01c20Nk.html|title=Nutritional Facts and Analysis for Spam|publisher=Nutritiondata.com|accessdate= July 5, 2013}}</ref>'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|\nNet weight per package: 340 grams (12 oz.)\n\nServing size: 100g\n|-\n!\n!Quantity per 100g\n|-\n| Energy || 1,300 kJ (310 [[Food energy|Calories or kilocalories]])\n|-\n| [[Protein]] || 13g (26% Daily Value or DV)\n|-\n| Total Fat || 27g (41% DV)\n|-\n| &emsp; \u2013 [[saturated fat]] || 10g (49% DV)\n|-\n| [[Carbohydrate]]s || 3g (1% DV)\n|-\n| Sodium || 1369&nbsp;mg (57% DV)\n|-\n| Cholesterol|| 70&nbsp;mg (23% DV)\n|-\n| [[Vitamin]]s and [[Dietary mineral|Minerals]] (% DV)|| 1% Vitamin C, 1% Calcium, 5% Iron,\n\n3% Magnesium, 9% Potassium, 12% Zinc,\n\nand 5% Copper\n|}\n\n==Varieties==\nAs listed on the official Spam website, there are numerous different flavors of Spam products, including:\n* Spam Classic \u2013 original flavor\n* Spam Hot & Spicy \u2013 with [[Tabasco sauce|Tabasco]] flavor\n* Jalape\u00f1o Spam\n* Spam with Black Pepper\n* Spam Low Sodium \u2013 \"25% less sodium\"\n* Spam Lite \u2013 \"33% fewer calories, 25% less sodium, and 50% less fat\" \u2013 made from pork with ham, and mechanically separated chicken\n* Spam Oven Roasted Turkey\n* Spam Hickory Smoked\n* Spam Spread \u2013 \"if you're a spreader, not a slicer&nbsp;... just like Spam Classic, but in a spreadable form\"\n* Spam Bacon\n* Spam Cheese\n* Spam Garlic\n* Spam Teriyaki\n* Spam Chorizo \n* Spam Boricua \u2013 seasoned Puerto Rican-style flavor\n* Spam Macadamia Nuts \u2013 Partnered with Hamakua Plantation\n* Spam Turkey\n* Spam Tocino\n* Spam Portuguese Sausage\n*[[Pumpkin Spice Spam|Spam Pumpkin Spice]] - limited edition variety released in late September 2019\n* In addition to the variety of flavors, Spam is sold in tins smaller than the twelve-ounce standard size. Spam Singles are also available, which are single sandwich-sized slices of Spam Classic or Lite, sealed in [[retort pouch]]es.<ref name=\"varieties\">{{cite web|url=https://store.spam.com/products/default.aspx|title=SPAM&copy; Products|publisher=Store.spam.com|accessdate=July 5, 2013}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* {{annotated link|Bologna sausage}}\n* {{annotated link|Breakfast}}\n* {{annotated link|Corned beef}}\n* {{annotated link|Loco moco}} \u2013 a Hawaiian dish that uses Spam in some versions\n* {{annotated link|Pork roll}}\n* {{annotated link|Potted meat food product}}\n* {{annotated link|Spam (Monty Python)}} - Humour and Song\n* {{annotated link|Treet}}\n* {{annotated link|Tushonka}} \u2013 a canned, stewed meat\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wiktionary|spam}} \n* {{Official website|http://www.spam.com}} \u2013 United States\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170213164423/http://gogd.tjs-labs.com/gallery-view?product=spam Collection of mid-twentieth century advertising featuring Spam] from The TJS Labs Gallery of Graphic Design.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spam (Food)}}\n[[Category:American brands]]\n[[Category:Brand name meats]]\n[[Category:Hawaiian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Hormel brands]]\n[[Category:Pork]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1937]]\n[[Category:Spam (food)|*]]\n", "name_user": "Kind Tennis Fan", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spam_(food)"}
{"title_page": "Eric Abidal", "text_new": "{{short description|French association football player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Eric Abidal\n| image = \u00c9ric Abidal - 001.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Abidal training with [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in 2008\n| fullname = Eric Sylvain Abidal<ref>{{cite web|url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=8847|title=Acta del partido celebrado el 16 de agosto de 2009, en Bilbao|trans-title=Minutes of the match held on 16 August 2009, in Bilbao|publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]]|language=Spanish|date=16 August 2009|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|9|11|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifadata.com/document/fcwc/2011/pdf/fcwc_2011_squadlists.pdf|title=FIFA Club World Cup Japan 2011 presented by TOYOTA: List of Players: FC Barcelona|publisher=FIFA|page=5|format=PDF|date=14 December 2011|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Saint-Genis-Laval]], France\n| height = 1.86 m<ref name=Lequipe>{{cite news|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/FootballFicheJoueur5000000000000000000010618.html|title=Eric Abidal|newspaper=[[L'\u00c9quipe]]|location=Paris|language=French|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] (director of football)\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[AS Lyon Duch\u00e8re|Lyon Duch\u00e8re]]\n| years1 = 1999\u20132000 | clubs1 = [[AS Lyon Duch\u00e8re|Lyon Duch\u00e8re]] | caps1 = | goals1 = \n| years2 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs2 = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco B]] | caps2 = 8 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2000\u20132002 | clubs3 = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] | caps3 = 22 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2002\u20132004 | clubs4 = [[Lille OSC|Lille]] | caps4 = 62 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2004\u20132007 | clubs5 = [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] | caps5 = 76 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2007\u20132013 | clubs6 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] | caps6 = 125 | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs7 = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] | caps7 = 26 | goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2014 | clubs8 = [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] | caps8 = 9 | goals8 = 0\n| totalcaps = 328 | totalgoals = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2004\u20132013 | nationalteam1 = [[France national football team|France]] | nationalcaps1 = 67 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}{{MedalCountry|{{fb|FRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 Germany]]|}}\n}}\n'''Eric Sylvain Abidal''' ({{IPA-fr|e\u0281ik abidal}}; born 11 September 1979) is a French former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[left back]] or [[centre back]], and the current [[director of football]] at [[FC Barcelona]].\n\nIn his career, he played mainly for [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] and [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], winning 18 titles with both teams combined, including two [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] trophies with the latter. His later career was marred by a liver tumour, which resulted in a [[Liver transplantation|transplant]].\n\nA [[France national football team|French international]] across nine years, Abidal represented the nation in two [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]] \u2013 [[2006 FIFA World Cup|finishing second in 2006]] \u2013 and [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nBorn in [[Saint-Genis-Laval]], Lyon Metropolis,<ref name=Lequipe/> Abidal started playing with [[AS Lyon Duch\u00e8re]], an amateur team in the suburbs. He started his professional career with [[AS Monaco FC]],<ref name=Graft>{{cite web|url=http://uk.uefa.com/uefasupercup/news/newsid=1665733.html|title=Graft not glitz defines Abidal's Monaco memories|publisher=UEFA|first=Graham|last=Hunter|date=24 August 2011|accessdate=10 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023063606/http://uk.uefa.com/uefasupercup/news/newsid%3D1665733.html|archivedate=23 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> making his [[Ligue 1]] debut on 16 September 2000 in a 3\u20130 home win against [[Toulouse FC]] but only appearing in 22 league matches over the course of two full seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.francefootball.fr/diaporama/Ils-sont-passes-de-lille-a-monaco-ou-inversement/6343/#1|title=Ils sont pass\u00e9s de Lille \u00e0 Monaco, ou inversement|trans-title=They went from Lille to Monaco, or the other way around|publisher=[[France Football]]|language=French|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAbidal transferred to fellow league club [[Lille OSC]] for [[2002\u201303 Ligue 1|2002\u201303]],<ref name=Returns>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/10/10/sport/football/abidal-barcelona-liver-football/index.html|title=Barcelona star Abidal returns to training after liver transplant|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=10 October 2012|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref> reuniting with former manager [[Claude Puel]]<ref name=Graft/> and being first-choice during his spell. Subsequently, he returned to his native region and joined [[Olympique Lyonnais]].<ref name=Returns/>\n\n===Lyon===\nDuring his later years in France, where he won three consecutive national championships \u2013 of the seven the team won \u2013 Abidal's confidence was shown when Lyon played [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and he was in charge of marking [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]: ''\"As a defender, my aim is to infuriate the opponent,\"'' he explained. ''\"I want him to be so sick of the sight of me that he has to move somewhere else on the pitch to get away.\"''<ref name=Focus>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/french_football/focus/abidal.html|title=French Focus: Eric Abidal (Lyon)|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|accessdate=9 October 2007}}</ref> His defensive teammates at ''L'OL'' included [[Fran\u00e7ois Clerc]], [[Gr\u00e9gory Coupet]] and [[Anthony R\u00e9veill\u00e8re]], as well as [[Brazil national football team|Brazilian]] internationals [[Ca\u00e7apa]] and [[Cris (footballer, born 1977)|Cris]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/apr/04/minutebyminute.sport|title=Milan 3\u20131 Lyon (Agg: 3\u20131)|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 April 2006|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/6378137.stm|title=Roma 0\u20130 Lyon|website=[[BBC Sport]]|date=21 February 2007|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 November 2004, Abidal scored the first goal of his career, in a 2\u20133 loss at former club Lille for [[2004\u201305 Coupe de la Ligue|the season]]'s [[Coupe de la Ligue]] [[Single-elimination tournament|round-of-32]]. As a result of his exploit, his parents agreed to get married after a 35-year union.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=258405.html|title=Abidal punishment|publisher=UEFA|date=19 November 2004|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nAbidal missed the first months of the [[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306 campaign]] after fracturing his [[metatarsus]] in a [[Exhibition game|friendly game]] with [[Once Caldas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=320130.html#lyon+learn+worst+about+abidal|title=Lyon learn worst about Abidal|publisher=UEFA|date=25 July 2005|accessdate=19 September 2012}}</ref> He still managed to appear in 15 matches as Lyon won its fifth national championship in a row<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/apr/17/newsstory.sport4|title=Bordeaux slip gives Lyon fifth straight title|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 April 2006|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref> (the second with the player).\n\n===Barcelona===\n[[File:Forcejeo Real Madrid - FC Barcelona.jpg|thumb|right|Abidal (far right) playing against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].]]\n[[File:Jeffren-Abidal-Bojan.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Abidal (center) with [[Jeffr\u00e9n Su\u00e1rez]] (left) and [[Bojan Krki\u0107]] during a training session with [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].]]\n\nOn 29 June 2007, Abidal signed a four-year contract with [[FC Barcelona]] for \u20ac9&nbsp;million, after repeatedly stating that he would not return to training with Lyon if he was not allowed to move.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/SPORT/football/06/29/barca.abidal.reut/index.html?section=cnn_latest|title=Abidal completes move to Barcelona|publisher=CNN|date=29 June 2007|accessdate=30 June 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> He was given the number 22 jersey, as the number 20 he wore at Lyon was already taken by [[Deco]]; club president [[Joan Laporta]] also mentioned that his contract contained a \u20ac90&nbsp;million release clause, and that Lyon would receive an extra \u20ac500,000 if Barcelona won the [[UEFA Champions League]] in any of the following four seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=541071.html|title=Abidal joins Barcelona|publisher=FIFA|date=29 June 2007|accessdate=30 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nAbidal made his [[La Liga]] debut on 26 August 2007 in a 0\u20130 away draw against [[Racing de Santander]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arxiu.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada07-08/08/n070825100780.html|title=The first squad list|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=25 August 2007|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?we_cat=8&art_id=52200&sid=15113581&con_type=1&d_str=20070828&fc=2|title=`Fantastic Four' fail to fire for Barca|newspaper=[[The Standard (Hong Kong)|The Standard]]|date=28 August 2007|accessdate=10 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023061156/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?we_cat=8&art_id=52200&sid=15113581&con_type=1&d_str=20070828&fc=2|archivedate=23 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and completed [[2007\u201308 La Liga|his first season]] with 30 games as ''Bar\u00e7a'' finished in third place in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=241320&cc=5739|title=Murcia 3\u20135 Barcelona: Dos Santos hits treble|website=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=17 May 2008|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref> He missed the [[2009 UEFA Champions League Final|2009 Champions League Final]] against Manchester United after picking up a [[red card (association football)|red card]] in the semi-final against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]: the [[Referee (association football)|referee]] deemed Abidal to have fouled countryman [[Nicolas Anelka]] and denying a scoring opportunity, although video evidence suggested that any contact was minimal;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/266494?cc=5739|title=Iniesta's late heartbreaker|website=ESPN Soccernet|date=6 May 2009|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> again through suspension<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/253005?cc=5739|title=Llorente the party pooper|website=ESPN Soccernet|date=10 May 2009|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> he also did not dress up for [[2009 Copa del Rey Final|the decisive match]] of the [[Copa del Rey]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=646187&sec=europe&root=europe&cc=5739#|title=One title closer to the treble|website=ESPN Soccernet|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref> as the team won [[Treble (association football)|the treble]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8071196.stm|title=Guardiola praises Barca bravery|website=BBC Sport|date=26 May 2009|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310]], Abidal continued to be the starter for the [[Pep Guardiola]]-led side, even after the arrival of [[Maxwell (footballer, born 1981)|Maxwell]] from [[Inter Milan]]. He scored his first goal on 5 January 2011, netting at the [[San Mam\u00e9s Stadium (1913)|San Mam\u00e9s Stadium]] in the [[2010\u201311 Copa del Rey|Spanish Cup round-of-16 second leg]] (1\u20131 away draw, [[away goals rule]] qualification).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2011/01/05/futbol/1294253950.html|title=Sin magia tambi\u00e9n se puede en San Mam\u00e9s|trans-title=Magic not needed in San Mam\u00e9s|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|last=Herguedas|language=Spanish|date=5 January 2011|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Abidal vs Atlante.JPG|thumb|Abidal during the [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup|2009 Club World Cup]] in [[Abu Dhabi]].]]\n\nOn 18 January 2012, Abidal scored his second goal for Barcelona, also in the [[2011\u201312 Copa del Rey|domestic cup]], helping the visitors come from behind to win it 2\u20131 at [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] (eventually 4\u20133 on aggregate).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/335877?cc=5739|title=Barca fight back at the Bernabeu|website=ESPN Soccernet|date=18 January 2012|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> He renewed his contract early into the following month, keeping him at the [[Camp Nou]] until 30 June 2013,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.as.com/futbol/articulo/abidal-2013-quiero-seguir-haciendo/20120203dasdasftb_19/Tes|title=Abidal, hasta 2013: \"Quiero seguir haciendo historia\"|trans-title=Abidal, until 2013: \"I want to continue making history\"|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|language=Spanish|date=3 February 2012|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> but on 30 May of that year it was announced that the club would not further extend it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/abidal-im-going-and-ill-definitely-be-back|title=Abidal: \"I'm going and I'll definitely be back\"|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=29 May 2013|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/may/30/barcelona-release-eric-abidal|title=Barcelona release Eric Abidal after his return from liver transplant|newspaper=The Guardian|date=30 May 2013|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Health issues====\nOn 15 March 2011, Barcelona announced that Abidal had been diagnosed with a [[tumour]] in his [[liver]], and the player underwent surgery two days later.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1366647/Eric-Abidal-undergo-surgery-Barcelona-diagnosed-liver-tumour.html|title=Eric Abidal to undergo surgery after Barcelona full-back diagnosed with a liver tumour|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=16 March 2011|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref>{{Deprecated inline|date=March 2020}} Citing privacy concerns as wished by the player, the club did not release additional information in regards to his condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada10-11/03/15/n110315116321.html|title=Abidal diagnosed with tumour on liver|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=15 March 2011|accessdate=16 March 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802094710/http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada10-11/03/15/n110315116321.html|archive-date=2 August 2012}}</ref> In response to the announcement, players and fans around the world dedicated well wishes to him on various [[social networking service]] and sports websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/894640/barcelona-defender-eric-abidal-to-undergo-surgery-on-liver-tumour?cc=5901|title=Barca's Abidal set for surgery on tumour|website=ESPN Soccernet|date=15 March 2011|accessdate=16 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundodeportivo.es/gen/20110315/54128249124/noticia/el-mundo-del-deporte-se-vuelca-con-abidal.html|title=El mundo del deporte se vuelca con Abidal|trans-title=Sports world supports Abidal|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=Spanish|date=18 March 2011|accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nBefore their [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|round-of-16 match in the Champions League]], both Real Madrid and Lyon players took the pitch wearing ''\u00c1nimo Abidal'' (Get Well Abidal) T-shirts, with the same message being displayed on the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]]'s scoreboards, in a show of support and solidarity.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/03/16/futbol/equipos/real_madrid/1300304703.html|title='\u00c1nimo Abidal', mensaje de \u00e1nimo en el Bernab\u00e9u|trans-title='Get well Abidal', message of support at the Bernab\u00e9u|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=Spanish|date=16 March 2011|accessdate=16 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/blogs/pitchside-europe/abidal-still-climbing-mountains-france-face-spain-111601395.html|title=Abidal still climbing mountains as France face Spain|website=[[Yahoo Sports]]|date=16 October 2012|accessdate=10 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019074539/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/blogs/pitchside-europe/abidal-still-climbing-mountains-france-face-spain-111601395.html|archivedate=19 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During Barcelona's match with [[Getafe CF]] on 19 March 2011, the fans at the stadium clapped for the entire 22nd minute (the player's shirt number).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/04/03/eric-abidal-looks-for-a-repeat-of-heart-warming-recovery-as-football-family-comes-together-again/|title=Eric Abidal looks for a repeat of heart-warming recovery as football family comes together again|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|first=Nicholas|last=Rigg|date=3 April 2012|accessdate=10 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012071829/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/04/03/eric-abidal-looks-for-a-repeat-of-heart-warming-recovery-as-football-family-comes-together-again/|archivedate=12 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 28 May 2011, in the [[2011 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League Final]] against Manchester United, he played the full 90 minutes of Barcelona's 3\u20131 triumph and, in a gesture to mark his recovery, [[Carles Puyol]] handed him his [[Captain (association football)|captain]]'s armband and allowed him to be the first to lift the trophy in front of 85,000 people at [[Wembley Stadium]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/abidal-lifts-the-4th-trophy|title=Abidal lifts the 4th trophy|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=26 May 2011|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2012, it was announced that Abidal would have to undergo a [[liver transplant]] because of problems which were unresolved with the previous operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17384984|title=Barcelona defender Eric Abidal to have a liver transplant|website=BBC Sport|date=15 March 2012|accessdate=15 March 2012}}</ref> On 10 April he underwent surgery, with his cousin G\u00e9rard being the donor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/la-liga/9197679/Barcelona-defender-Eric-Abidal-recovering-well-after-liver-transplant-surgery.html|title=Barcelona defender Eric Abidal recovering well after liver transplant surgery|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=11 April 2012|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref> On the same day Barcelona beat Getafe 4\u20130, and the victory was dedicated to the player in the post-game press conference;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1047721/barcelona-players-dedicate-win-to-eric-abidal?cc=5739|title=Barcelona dedicate win to Abidal|website=ESPN Soccernet|date=11 April 2012|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/sports/2012-04/11/c_131520382.htm|title=Guardiola dedicates Getafe win to Eric Abidal|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=11 April 2012|accessdate=10 November 2012}}</ref> he later revealed that his friend and teammate [[Dani Alves]] offered to donate part of his liver for the transplant, but he denied because it would have affected the latter's playing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/sep/16/eric-abidal-dani-alves-barcelona-liver|title=Eric Abidal says Dani Alves offered him part of his liver for transplant|newspaper=The Guardian|date=16 September 2013|accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2012, Abidal was released from hospital to resume the recovery process at his home.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1075679/barcelona-defender-eric-abidal-leaves-hospital?cc=5901 Abidal leaves hospital]; ESPN Soccernet, 21 May 2012</ref> He returned to training in the [[Pyrenees]] in October 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11833/8154194/Barcelona-defender-Eric-Abidal-has-begun-training-again-following-his-liver-transplant-earlier-this-year|title=Barcelona defender Eric Abidal has begun training again following his liver transplant earlier this year|website=[[Sky Sports]]|date=10 October 2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> but, the following month, he stated that his priority was a return to full health rather than resuming his football career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2012/11/06/3505955/abidal-returning-to-football-not-my-objective|title=Abidal: Returning to football not my objective|website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Stefan|last=Coerts|date=6 November 2012|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 December 2012, Abidal was given the green light to start training again,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3277/la-liga/2012/12/18/3612779/barcelonas-abidal-given-the-green-light-to-play-football|title=Barcelona's Abidal given the green light to play football again|website=Goal|first=Simon|last=Harrison|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref> and he returned to active in January of the following year. On 19 March of the following year he played 65 minutes for [[FC Barcelona B]] in a practice match with [[FC Istres]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/eric-abidal-plays-practice-match-against-istres|title=\u00c9ric Abidal plays practice match against Istres|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=19 March 2013|accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref> and on 6 April he returned to official play, replacing [[Gerard Piqu\u00e9]] for the last 20 minutes of a 5\u20130 home win against [[RCD Mallorca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/uk/en/report/348240/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=5739|title=Fabregas fires Barca to victory|website=ESPN FC|date=6 April 2013|accessdate=7 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/04/06/futbol/equipos/barcelona/1365285487.html|title=Abidal: \"Gracias a mi primo, sin \u00e9l no estar\u00eda aqu\u00ed\"|trans-title=Abidal: \"Thanks to my cousin, i would not be here without him\"|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=7 April 2013|accessdate=7 April 2013}}</ref> Two weeks later he played the full 90 minutes for the first time since his comeback, featuring in a 1\u20130 home success over [[Levante UD]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/report?id=348220&cc=5739|title=Below-par Barca leave it late|website=ESPN FC|date=20 April 2013|accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Monaco return===\nOn 8 July 2013, 33-year-old Abidal returned to Monaco after more than one decade, signing for one season with the option of a further one.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asm-fc.com/fr/actualites/equipe/le-retour-d-eric-abidal|title=Le retour d'Eric Abidal|trans-title=The return of Eric Abidal|publisher=AS Monaco FC|language=French|date=8 July 2013|accessdate=10 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130708130017/http://www.asm-fc.com/fr/actualites/equipe/le-retour-d-eric-abidal|archivedate=8 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After helping the principality team [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League|secure a place in the Champions League]] in [[2013\u201314 Ligue 1|his debut campaign]], he agreed to a one-year contract extension.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sport.es/es/noticias/planeta-barca/abidal-seguira-ano-mas-monaco-3349905|title=Abidal seguir\u00e1 un a\u00f1o m\u00e1s en el M\u00f3naco|trans-title=Abidal to continue one more year with Monaco|newspaper=[[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]]|language=Spanish|date=3 June 2014|accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Olympiacos===\nOn 5 July 2014, two days after renewing his link to Monaco, Abidal signed a two-year contract with [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28180379|title=Eric Abidal leaves Monaco for Olympiakos|website=BBC Sport|date=5 July 2014|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> On 19 December, however, he retired from the game for personal reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2880682/Former-Barcelona-France-defender-Eric-Abidal-announces-retirement-football.html|title=Former Barcelona and France defender Eric Abidal announces retirement from football|newspaper=Daily Mail|first=Pete|last=Hall|date=19 December 2014|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref>{{Deprecated inline|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Return to Barcelona===\nAbidal returned to Barcelona in June 2018, replacing [[Roberto Fern\u00e1ndez Bonillo|Roberto Fern\u00e1ndez]] as the club's [[director of football]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/06/07/sports/soccer/07reuters-soccer-spain-fcb-abidal.html|title=Soccer-Abidal Returns to Barcelona as sporting director|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=7 June 2018|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11409722/eric-abidal-returns-to-barcelona-as-sporting-director|title=Eric Abidal returns to Barcelona as sporting director|website=Sky Sports|first=Danny|last=Gallagher|date=19 June 2018|accessdate=20 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAbidal earned 67 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for the [[France national football team|France national team]],<ref name=SwedenInvite>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-au/news/4037/euro-2012/2012/06/13/3170275/french-football-federation-invite-abidal-as-guest-for-sweden|title=French football federation invite Abidal as guest for Sweden clash|website=Goal|first=Karthick|last=Arvinth|date=13 June 2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> his debut coming on 18 August 2004 in a friendly with [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref name=\"Focus\"/><ref name=SwedenInvite/> He was selected for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], playing all the games and minutes in the country's runner-up campaign as left back, with the exception of France's match against [[Togo national football team|Togo]], from which he was suspended<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/5058836.stm|title=Togo 0\u20132 France \u2013 Stats/action|website=BBC Sport|date=23 June 2006|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> after earning two yellow cards in the first two games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4852856.stm|title=France 0\u20130 Switzerland|website=BBC Sport|date=13 June 2006|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853220.stm|title=France 1\u20131 South Korea|website=BBC Sport|date=18 June 2006|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> In [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]] against [[Italy national football team|Italy]], he scored his [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] attempt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/5148796.stm|title=Italy 1\u20131 France (aet)|website=BBC Sport|date=9 July 2006|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nAgain under [[Raymond Domenech]], Abidal was first-choice during the [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]] [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying|qualifying campaign]]. In the final stages he appeared against Italy as a centre-back, but conceded a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] and was sent off in the first half of an eventual 0\u20132 loss and group stage exit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/7363384.stm|title=France 0\u20132 Italy & Netherlands 2\u20130 Romania|website=BBC Sport|date=17 June 2008|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> He played against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] again at centre-back,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/11/world-cup-2010-uruguay-france-live|title=World Cup 2010: Uruguay v France \u2013 as it happened|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Barry|last=Glendenning|date=11 June 2010|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/world-cup-2010/news/7830659/France-v-Mexico-live.html|title=France v Mexico: as it happened|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|first=Sandy|last=Macaskill|date=17 June 2010|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> opting out of the next game against host country [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2890/world-cup-2010/2010/06/22/1989991/world-cup-2010-eric-abidal-chose-not-to-play-against-south|title=World Cup 2010: Eric Abidal chose not to play against South Africa \u2013 France coach Raymond Domenech|website=Goal|first=Rupert|last=Fryer|date=22 June 2010|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> as the French side again left the competition after only three matches.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/22/world-cup-2010-france-south-africa1|title=World Cup 2010: South Africa beat red-faced France and both bow out|newspaper=The Guardian|first=David|last=Hytner|date=22 June 2010|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nAbidal was a tactically intelligent and versatile defender, capable of featuring as a centre or left back due to his positional sense and his ability to read the game. In his prime, he was also quick and strong which, along with his technical ability and distribution, allowed him run up the wing to assist his team offensively as well as defensively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arxiu.fcbarcelona.cat/web/castellano/futbol/temporada_10-11/plantilla/jugadors/abidal.html|title=\u00c9ric Abidal|publisher=FC Barcelona|language=Spanish|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/iht/2006/07/08/sports/IHT-08wcplayers.html?pagewanted=print|title=France and Italy \u2013 Settled and similar|newspaper=The New York Times|first=Peter|last=Berlin|date=8 July 2006|accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAbidal married former gymnast Hayet Kebir in 2003, fathering children M\u00e9liana, Can\u00e9lia, Leyna, Kenya and Edan.<ref name=20WAGs>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/396211-2010-fifa-world-cup-ranking-the-top-20-wags-of-the-soccer-elite/page/6|title=2010 FIFA World Cup: Ranking the Top 20 WAGs of the Soccer Elite \u2013 16. Hayet Abidal|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=24 May 2010|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ie.msn.com/sports/football/euro-2012/features/gallery.aspx?cp-documentid=161352190&page=22|title=Euro 2012: Wives and girlfriends \u2013 France: Hayet & \u00c9ric Abidal|publisher=[[MSN]]|date=24 April 2012|accessdate=15 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023064411/http://news.ie.msn.com/sports/football/euro-2012/features/gallery.aspx?cp-documentid=161352190&page=22|archive-date=23 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.fr/People/Style/Trajectoire-mode/Femmes-de-footballeurs-qui-sont-elles/Hayet-et-Eric-Abidal|title=Femmes de footballeurs: qui sont-elles? \u2013 Hayet et Eric Abidal|trans-title=Footballers' wives: who are they? \u2013 Hayet and Eric Abidal|publisher=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|language=French|date=|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.terrafemina.com/article/eric-abidal-heureux-papa-de-quatre-filles-avec-sa-femme-hayet-photos_a317635/1|title=Eric Abidal: heureux papa de quatre filles avec sa femme Hayet (photos)|trans-title=Eric Abidal: proud daddy of four daughters with his wife Hayet (photos)|publisher=Terra Femina|first=Marie|last=Deghetto|language=French|date=6 August 2016|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/eric-abidal/535/|title=E. Abidal|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{ESPN FC|10551}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<ref group=\"nb\">Includes [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe<ref group=\"nb\">Includes [[UEFA Super Cup]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|[[AS Monaco FC|Monaco B]]\n|2000\u201301\n|[[Championnat National 2]]\n|8||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||8||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]\n|[[2000\u201301 French Division 1|2000\u201301]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ligue 1]]\n|8||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0||9||0\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 French Division 1|2001\u201302]]\n|14||0||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||17||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|'''Total'''\n!22!!0!!3!!0!!1!!0!!26!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Lille OSC|Lille]]\n|[[2002\u201303 Ligue 1|2002\u201303]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Ligue 1\n|27||0||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||0\n|-\n|[[2003\u201304 Ligue 1|2003\u201304]]\n|35||0||3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||38||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|'''Total'''\n!62!!0!!6!!1!!0!!0!!68!!1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]]\n|[[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Ligue 1\n|29||0|| 5|| 1||7||0||41||1\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306]]\n|14||0||2||0||6||0||22||0\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Ligue 1|2006\u201307]]\n|33||0||4||1||7||0||44||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|'''Total'''\n!76!!0!!11!!2!!20!!0!!107!!2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n|[[2007\u201308 FC Barcelona season|2007\u201308]]\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[La Liga]]\n|30||0||6||0||10||0||46||0\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 FC Barcelona season|2008\u201309]]\n|25||0||2||0||5||0||32||0\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 FC Barcelona season|2009\u201310]]\n|17||0||4||0||10||0||31||0\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 FC Barcelona season|2010\u201311]]\n|26||0||7||1||8||0||41||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 FC Barcelona season|2011\u201312]]\n|22||0||7||1||9||0||38||1\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 FC Barcelona season|2012\u201313]]\n|5||0||0||0||0||0||5||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|'''Total'''\n!125!!0!!26!!2!!42!!0!!193!!2\n|-\n|Monaco\n|[[2013\u201314 AS Monaco FC season|2013\u201314]]\n|[[Ligue 1]]\n|26||0||3||0||0||0||29||0\n|-\n|[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n|[[2014\u201315 Olympiacos F.C. season|2014\u201315]]\n|[[Superleague Greece|Superleague]]\n|9||0||0||0||6||0||15||0\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Career total\n!328!!0!!49!!5!!69!!0!!446!!5\n|}\n\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n===International===\n:Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=26426|title=\u00c9ric Abidal|website=EU-Football.info|accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! National team !! Year !! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"10\" valign=\"center\"|[[France national football team|France]]\n| 2004 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| 2005 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| 2006 || 15 || 0\n|-\n| 2007 || 12 || 0\n|-\n| 2008 || 9 || 0\n|-\n| 2009 || 5 || 0\n|-\n| 2010 || 6 || 0\n|-\n| 2011 || 9 || 0\n|-\n| 2012 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| 2013 || 6 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total !! 67 !! 0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:Abidal Barcelona.jpg|thumb|right|Abidal signing autographs at the [[Camp Nou]]]]\n\n'''Lyon'''\n*[[Ligue 1]]: [[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305]], [[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306]], [[2006\u201307 Ligue 1|2006\u201307]]<ref name=Lequipe/>\n\n'''Barcelona'''\n*[[La Liga]]: [[2008\u201309 La Liga|2008\u201309]], [[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310]], [[2010\u201311 La Liga|2010\u201311]], [[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313]]<ref name=Honours>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/22719441|title=Eric Abidal leaves Barcelona but plans to continue playing|website=BBC Sport|date=30 May 2013|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[2008\u201309 Copa del Rey|2008\u201309]], [[2011\u201312 Copa del Rey|2011\u201312]]<ref name=Honours/>\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[2009 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2009]], [[2010 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2010]], [[2011 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2011]]<ref name=Honours/>\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|2008\u201309]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2198456.html|title=\u00c9ric Abidal: 'An example to us all'|publisher=UEFA|first1=Richard|last1=Martin|first2=Christian|last2=Ch\u00e2telet|first3=Vassiliki|last3=Papantonopoulou|date=19 December 2014|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|2010\u201311]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/13576522.stm|title=Barcelona 3\u20131 Man Utd|website=BBC Sport|first=Phil|last=McNulty|date=28 May 2011|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[2009 UEFA Super Cup|2009]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/matches/season=2009/round=2000023/match=2001219/index.html|title=Pedro pounces to add to Bar\u00e7a glory|publisher=UEFA|date=28 August 2009|accessdate=8 March 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024171140/https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/matches/season=2009/round=2000023/match=2001219/index.html|archivedate=24 October 2018}}</ref> [[2011 UEFA Super Cup|2011]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/matches/season=2011/round=2000258/match=2006776/index.html|title=Barcelona beat Porto for fourth UEFA Super Cup|publisher=UEFA|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=8 March 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024170931/https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/matches/season=2011/round=2000258/match=2006776/index.html|archivedate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n*[[FIFA Club World Cup]]: [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup|2009]], [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup|2011]]<ref name=Honours/>\n\n'''Olympiacos'''\n*[[Superleague Greece]]: [[2014\u201315 Superleague Greece|2014\u201315]]{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''France'''\n*[[FIFA World Cup]] runner-up: [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/SPORT/football/07/11/france.domenech/|title=Domenech to remain as France coach|publisher=CNN|date=12 July 2006|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#Team of the Year|Ligue 1 Team of the Year]]: 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ol.fr/fr-fr/contenus/articles/2005/05/22/lol-plebiscite-par-les-oscars-du-foot-3264|title=L'OL pl\u00e9biscit\u00e9 par les Oscars du foot|trans-title=OL honoured by footy Oscars|publisher=Olympique Lyonnais|language=French|date=22 May 2005|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.fr/football/ligue-1/2005-2006/juninho-l-elu_sto880862/story.shtml|title=Juninho, l'\u00e9lu|trans-title=Juninho, the chosen one|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|language=French|date=7 May 2006|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> 2007<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/football/2007/05/20/02003-20070520ARTSPO00008-malouda-recompense.php|title=Malouda r\u00e9compens\u00e9|trans-title=Malouda rewarded|newspaper=[[Le Figaro]]|language=French|date=20 May 2007|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Team of the Year]]: 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/community/teamoftheyear/history/season=2007/index.html|title=Team of the Year 2007|publisher=UEFA|first=Adrian|last=Harte|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[La Liga Awards|LFP Defender of the Year]]: 2011<ref>{{cite news|url=http://agencias.abc.es/agencias/noticia.asp?noticia=1292480|title=Ganadores de las cuatro ediciones de premios de la LFP|trans-title=Winners of the four PFL awards editions|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=Spanish|date=13 November 2012|accessdate=9 March 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116110429/http://agencias.abc.es/agencias/noticia.asp?noticia=1292480|archivedate=16 January 2016}}</ref>\n*[[FC Barcelona]] Player of the Season ([[Trofeo Aldo Rovira]]): 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2011-2012/abidal-wins-aldo-rovira-award-2011-12|title=Abidal wins Aldo Rovira Award 2011/12|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=28 June 2012|accessdate=11 May 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Globe Soccer Awards]]: Player Career Award 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globesoccer.com/awards/walloffame/|title=Wall of Fame|publisher=Globe Soccer|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Premio internazionale Giacinto Facchetti]]: 2013<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio_Estero/30-10-2013/ad-abidal-premio-facchetti-un-altra-vita-vorrei-cosi-201469162472.shtml|title=Ad Abidal il Premio Facchetti \u2013 \"Un'altra vita? La vorrei cos\u00ec\"|trans-title=To Abidal the Facchetti Award \u2013 \"Another life? I would want it like this\"|newspaper=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|first=Gianfelice|last=Facchetti|language=Italian|date=30 October 2013|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{LFP}}\n* {{BDFutbol}}\n* {{UEFA player}}\n* {{FFF male player}}\n* {{NFT}}\n* {{FIFA player}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = France squads\n| bg = #002395\n| fg = white\n| bordercolor = #ED2939\n| list1 = \n{{France squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{France squad UEFA Euro 2008}}\n{{France squad 2010 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| titlestyle = background: gold\n| list1 = \n{{2004\u201305 Ligue 1 UNFP Team of the Year}}\n{{2005\u201306 Ligue 1 UNFP Team of the Year}}\n{{2006\u201307 Ligue 1 UNFP Team of the Year}}\n{{La Liga Defender of the Year}}\