201314]]\n|[[Ligue 1]]\n|26||0||3||0||0||0||29||0\n|-\n|[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n|[[2014\u201315 Olympiacos F.C. season|2014\u201315]]\n|[[Superleague Greece|Superleague]]\n|9||0||0||0||6||0||15||0\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Career total\n!328!!0!!49!!5!!69!!0!!446!!5\n|}\n\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n===International===\n:Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=26426|title=\u00c9ric Abidal|website=EU-Football.info|accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! National team !! Year !! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"10\" valign=\"center\"|[[France national football team|France]]\n| 2004 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| 2005 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| 2006 || 15 || 0\n|-\n| 2007 || 12 || 0\n|-\n| 2008 || 9 || 0\n|-\n| 2009 || 5 || 0\n|-\n| 2010 || 6 || 0\n|-\n| 2011 || 9 || 0\n|-\n| 2012 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| 2013 || 6 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total !! 67 !! 0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:Abidal Barcelona.jpg|thumb|right|Abidal signing autographs at the [[Camp Nou]]]]\n\n'''Lyon'''\n*[[Ligue 1]]: [[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305]], [[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306]], [[2006\u201307 Ligue 1|2006\u201307]]<ref name=Lequipe/>\n\n'''Barcelona'''\n*[[La Liga]]: [[2008\u201309 La Liga|2008\u201309]], [[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310]], [[2010\u201311 La Liga|2010\u201311]], [[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313]]<ref name=Honours>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/22719441|title=Eric Abidal leaves Barcelona but plans to continue playing|website=BBC Sport|date=30 May 2013|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[2008\u201309 Copa del Rey|2008\u201309]], [[2011\u201312 Copa del Rey|2011\u201312]]<ref name=Honours/>\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[2009 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2009]], [[2010 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2010]], [[2011 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2011]]<ref name=Honours/>\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|2008\u201309]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2198456.html|title=\u00c9ric Abidal: 'An example to us all'|publisher=UEFA|first1=Richard|last1=Martin|first2=Christian|last2=Ch\u00e2telet|first3=Vassiliki|last3=Papantonopoulou|date=19 December 2014|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|2010\u201311]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/13576522.stm|title=Barcelona 3\u20131 Man Utd|website=BBC Sport|first=Phil|last=McNulty|date=28 May 2011|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[2009 UEFA Super Cup|2009]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/matches/season=2009/round=2000023/match=2001219/index.html|title=Pedro pounces to add to Bar\u00e7a glory|publisher=UEFA|date=28 August 2009|accessdate=8 March 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024171140/https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/matches/season=2009/round=2000023/match=2001219/index.html|archivedate=24 October 2018}}</ref> [[2011 UEFA Super Cup|2011]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/matches/season=2011/round=2000258/match=2006776/index.html|title=Barcelona beat Porto for fourth UEFA Super Cup|publisher=UEFA|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=8 March 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024170931/https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/matches/season=2011/round=2000258/match=2006776/index.html|archivedate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n*[[FIFA Club World Cup]]: [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup|2009]], [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup|2011]]<ref name=Honours/>\n\n'''Olympiacos'''\n*[[Superleague Greece]]: [[2014\u201315 Superleague Greece|2014\u201315]]{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''France'''\n*[[FIFA World Cup]] runner-up: [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/SPORT/football/07/11/france.domenech/|title=Domenech to remain as France coach|publisher=CNN|date=12 July 2006|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#Team of the Year|Ligue 1 Team of the Year]]: 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ol.fr/fr-fr/contenus/articles/2005/05/22/lol-plebiscite-par-les-oscars-du-foot-3264|title=L'OL pl\u00e9biscit\u00e9 par les Oscars du foot|trans-title=OL honoured by footy Oscars|publisher=Olympique Lyonnais|language=French|date=22 May 2005|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.fr/football/ligue-1/2005-2006/juninho-l-elu_sto880862/story.shtml|title=Juninho, l'\u00e9lu|trans-title=Juninho, the chosen one|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|language=French|date=7 May 2006|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> 2007<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/football/2007/05/20/02003-20070520ARTSPO00008-malouda-recompense.php|title=Malouda r\u00e9compens\u00e9|trans-title=Malouda rewarded|newspaper=[[Le Figaro]]|language=French|date=20 May 2007|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Team of the Year]]: 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/community/teamoftheyear/history/season=2007/index.html|title=Team of the Year 2007|publisher=UEFA|first=Adrian|last=Harte|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[La Liga Awards|LFP Defender of the Year]]: 2011<ref>{{cite news|url=http://agencias.abc.es/agencias/noticia.asp?noticia=1292480|title=Ganadores de las cuatro ediciones de premios de la LFP|trans-title=Winners of the four PFL awards editions|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=Spanish|date=13 November 2012|accessdate=9 March 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116110429/http://agencias.abc.es/agencias/noticia.asp?noticia=1292480|archivedate=16 January 2016}}</ref>\n*[[FC Barcelona]] Player of the Season ([[Trofeo Aldo Rovira]]): 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2011-2012/abidal-wins-aldo-rovira-award-2011-12|title=Abidal wins Aldo Rovira Award 2011/12|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=28 June 2012|accessdate=11 May 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Globe Soccer Awards]]: Player Career Award 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globesoccer.com/awards/walloffame/|title=Wall of Fame|publisher=Globe Soccer|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Premio internazionale Giacinto Facchetti]]: 2013<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio_Estero/30-10-2013/ad-abidal-premio-facchetti-un-altra-vita-vorrei-cosi-201469162472.shtml|title=Ad Abidal il Premio Facchetti \u2013 \"Un'altra vita? La vorrei cos\u00ec\"|trans-title=To Abidal the Facchetti Award \u2013 \"Another life? I would want it like this\"|newspaper=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|first=Gianfelice|last=Facchetti|language=Italian|date=30 October 2013|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{LFP}}\n* {{BDFutbol}}\n* {{UEFA player}}\n* {{FFF male player}}\n* {{NFT}}\n* {{FIFA player}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = France squads\n| bg = #002395\n| fg = white\n| bordercolor = #ED2939\n| list1 = \n{{France squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{France squad UEFA Euro 2008}}\n{{France squad 2010 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| titlestyle = background: gold\n| list1 = \n{{2004\u201305 Ligue 1 UNFP Team of the Year}}\n{{2005\u201306 Ligue 1 UNFP Team of the Year}}\n{{2006\u201307 Ligue 1 UNFP Team of the Year}}\n{{La Liga Defender of the Year}}\n{{2007 UEFA Team of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abidal, Eric}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Saint-Genis-Laval]]\n[[Category:French people of Martiniquais descent]]\n[[Category:Black French sportspeople]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:AS Monaco FC players]]\n[[Category:Lille OSC players]]\n[[Category:Olympique Lyonnais players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona players]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece players]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:France international footballers]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2010 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2008 players]]\n[[Category:French expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Monaco]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\t\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Greece]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:People with cancer]]\n[[Category:Liver transplant recipients]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor intro tweak.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Abidal"}
{"title_page": "First term of the presidency of Ferdinand Marcos", "text_new": "[[Ferdinand Marcos]] was inaugurated to his '''first term as the [[List of Presidents of the Philippines|Tenth]] [[President of the Philippines]]''' on 30 December 1965.  His inauguration marked the beginning of his two-decade long stay in power, even though the 1935 Philippine Constitution had set a limit of only two four-year terms of office.  Marcos had won the [[1965 Philippine presidential election|Philippine presidential election of 1965]] against the incumbent president, [[Diosdado Macapagal]].\n\nBefore Marcos' Presidency, the Philippines was the second largest economy in Asia, behind only Japan.<ref name=\"Galang20110221\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/213564/opinion/the-economic-decline-that-led-to-marcos-fall/ |title=The economic decline that led to Marcos' fall |last=Galang |first=Ping |date=2011-02-21 |access-date=2018-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529093920/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/opinion/content/213564/the-economic-decline-that-led-to-marcos-fall/story/ |archive-date=2018-05-29 |url-status=live |language=en-US}}</ref>  He pursued an aggressive program of infrastructure development funded by foreign loans,<ref name=\"Galang20110221\"/> making him very popular throughout almost all of his first term and eventually making him the first and only President of the Third Philippine republic to win a second term, although it would also trigger an inflationary crisis which would lead to social unrest in his second term, and would eventually lead to his declaration of Martial Law in 1972.<ref name=Balbosas1992>{{Cite journal |last=Balbosa |first=Joven Zamoras |date=1992 |title=IMF Stabilization Program and Economic Growth: The Case of the Philippines |journal=Journal of Philippine Development |volume=XIX |issue=35}}</ref><ref name=\"Cororaton1997\">{{Cite journal |last=Cororaton |first=Cesar B. |title=Exchange Rate Movements in the Philippines |journal=DPIDS Discussion Paper Series 97-05 |pages=3, 19}}</ref>\n\n== 1965 Election Campaign ==\nFerdinand Marcos was a member of the Liberal Party (LP) in 1965, becoming [[Senate of the Philippines|Senate President]] during the presidential term of fellow Liberal Macapagal. Marcos found his ambitions to run for president blocked when Macapagal decided to run for a second term, so Marcos jumped from the LP to the Nacionalista Party (NP), eventually becoming the NP's candidate for president.<ref name=\"Pe20160703\">{{Cite news |url=http://opinion.inquirer.net/95478/turncoatism-in-ph |title=Turncoatism in PH |last=Pe |first=Roger |date=2016-07-03 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |access-date=2018-05-29 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAn acknowledged \"master of populist imagery\", Marcos projected a persona of youth and virility, having himself photographed by rice farmers in their fields.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\">{{Cite book |title=Kasaysayan, The Story of the Filipino People Volume 9:A Nation Reborn. |publisher=Asia Publishing Company Limited |year=1998 |editor-last=Magno |editor-first=Alexander R. |location=Hong Kong |chapter=Democracy at the Crossroads}}</ref> He also cast himself as a war hero, claiming to be the \"most decorated war hero of the Philippines\" on the strength of 27 supposed war medals and decorations which were later revealed to be mostly propaganda,<ref name=\"Mijares246\">{{Cite book |title=The conjugal dictatorship of Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos : revised and annotated |last=Primitivo |first=Mijares |isbn=9789715507813 |edition=Revised |location=Quezon City |pages=246\u2013254 |oclc=988749288|year = 2017}}</ref> being inaccurate or untrue.<ref name=\"Bondoc20110428\">{{Cite news |url=http://globalbalita.com/2011/04/28/marcos-medals-only-2-of-33-given-in-battle/ |title=Marcos medals: Only 2 of 33 given in battle |last=Bondoc  |first=Jarius  |date=April 28, 2011 |publisher=Global Balita}}</ref><ref name=\"chicagoTribune1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-09-29/news/8901180123_1_mr-marcos-ferdinand-edralin-marcos-martial-law/2|title=Marcos Was More Than Just Another Deposed Dictator|last=Reaves|first=Joseph A.|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=September 29, 1989}}</ref><ref name=\"USDODdatabase\">{{cite web|url=http://valor.defense.gov/Recipients/ArmyDistinguishedServiceCrossRecipients.aspx|title=US Department of Defense official database of Distinguished Service Cross recipients}}</ref>\n\nMarcos won the election with 51.94% of the vote, Macapagal having garnered 42.88% while Raul Manglapus of the Party for Philippine Progress got 5.17%.  About 0.01%. of the votes went to nine other candidates who ran for the post under various independent parties.<ref name=\"PhilippinePresidencyProjectElectionResults\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.pangulo.ph/election_results.php |title=Results of the Past Presidential & Vice-Presidential Elections |website=The Philippine Presidency Project |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824115409/http://www.pangulo.ph/election_results.php |archive-date=2007-08-24 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Administration ==\n{{see also|First inauguration of Ferdinand Marcos}}\n\nUpon winning the election, Marcos appointed a cabinet composed mostly of [[technocrat]]s and intellectuals, most notably Executive Secretary [[Rafael Salas]], Education Secretary [[Onofre Corpuz]], Finance Secrtetary [[Cesar Virata]], and National Economic and Development Authority Director General [[Gerardo Sicat]].<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\n=== Agricultural and rural development projects===\n{{see also|IR8}}\nIn an effort to strengthen the influence of the Office of the President and simultaneously weaken the strong patronage bonds which rural Filipinos had with their local leaders, Marcos created the Presidential Arm on Community Development (PACD), which would initiate development projects at the barrio level without going through the Barrio and Municipal governments.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\nMarcos also took credit for the dramatic increase in rice production caused by the 1968 introduction of a new \"miracle rice\" variety, [[IR8]], by the [[International Rice Research Institute]] in [[Los Ba\u00f1os, Laguna]] - although the IRRI program that developed the variety had started as early as 1962, during the Macapagal administration, and was the product of an International consortium, not the Philippine government.<ref name=\"IRRI2016\">{{cite web |url=http://irri.org/ir8 |title=IR8: Rice that Changed the World |publisher=International Rice Research Institute |access-date=October 19, 2017|date=November 2016 |website=IRRI.org}}</ref>\n\n=== Formation of Industrial Monopolies ===\n{{main|Monopolies in the Philippines (1965\u20131986)|Cronies of Ferdinand Marcos}}\nDuring this first term, Marcos also began systematically cultivating a group entrepreneurs and industrialists loyal to him, rather than the Philippines' ruling class of landowners, making these cronies richer and more powerful through what would later be called \"[[behest loans]]\", which funnelled foreign assistance and \"soft loans\" to their businesses on the pretense of spurring industrial development.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\n=== Expansion of the Philippine Military ===\nOne of Marcos' earliest initiatives upon becoming president was to significantly expand the Philippine Military. In an unprecedented move, Marcos chose to concurrently serve as his own Defense Secretary, allowing him to have a direct hand in running the Military.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/> He also significantly increased the budget of the armed forces, tapping them in civil projects such as the construction of schools.  Generals loyal to Marcos were allowed to stay in their positions past their retirement age, or were rewarded with civilian government posts, leading Senator [[Benigno Aquino Jr.|Benigno S. Aquino Jr.]] to accuse Marcos in 1968 of trying to establish \"a garrison state.\"<ref name=\"GovPh29thNinoyAnniv\">{{Cite web |url=http://president.gov.ph/gov_at_work/phl-marks-29th-anniversary-of-aquinos-assassination-on-tuesday/ |title=PHL marks 29th anniversary of Aquino's assassination on Tuesday |date=August 20, 2012 |publisher=Office of the President of the Philippines |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208022821/http://president.gov.ph/gov_at_work/phl-marks-29th-anniversary-of-aquinos-assassination-on-tuesday/ |archive-date=February 8, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Sending troops to the Vietnam War====\nUnder intense pressure from the administration of [[Lyndon B. Johnson]],<ref name=\"McMahon1999\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=lx0MWRuKtUkC&pg=PA141&lpg=PA141#v=onepage&f=false |title=The Limits of Empire: The United States and Southeast Asia Since World War II |last=McMahon |first=Robert J. |last2=Mcmahon |first2=Robert |date=1999 |publisher=Columbia University Press |isbn=9780231108812 }}</ref> Marcos reversed his pre-presidency position of not sending Philippine forces to Vietnam War,<ref name=\"Tan20050603\">{{Cite news |url=http://opinion.inquirer.net/85440/ph-vietnam-ties |title=PH-Vietnam ties |last=Tan |first=Michael L. |date=2005-06-03 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |access-date=2018-05-28 |language=en}}</ref> and consented to a limited involvement,<ref name=agoncillo508>{{Harvp|Agoncillo|1990|pp=508\u2013510}}.</ref> asking Congress to approve sending a [[combat engineer]] unit.  Despite opposition to the new plan, the Marcos government gained Congressional approval and Philippine troops were sent from the middle of 1966 as the Philippines Civic Action Group (PHILCAG). PHILCAG reached a strength of some 1,600 troops in 1968 and between 1966 and 1970 over 10,000 Filipino soldiers served in South Vietnam, mainly being involved in civilian infrastructure projects.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Larsen |first1=Stanley Robert |last2=Collins |first2=James Lawton, Jr. |orig-year=1985 |year=2005 |chapter-url=http://www.history.army.mil/books/Vietnam/allied/ch03.htm |chapter=Chapter III: The Philippines |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029203725/http://www.history.army.mil/books/Vietnam/allied/ch03.htm |archive-date=October 29, 2013 |url=https://history.army.mil/html/books/090/90-5-1/CMH_Pub_90-5-1.pdf |title=Allied Participation in Vietnam |publisher=U.S. Department of the Army}}</ref>\n\n=== Loans for Infrastructure Development ===\n{{main|Edifice complex}}\nWith an eye towards becoming the first president of the third republic to be reelected to a second term, the Marcos administration began taking up massive foreign loans to fund \"rice, roads, and schoolbuildings\" - the lynchpin slogan of his reelection campaign.  The Omnibus Tax Law of 1969 was passed too late by congress to be useful to Marcos' publicity efforts, and at any rate, did not succeed in raising signfiicant new funds.  So it was foreign loans that funded the 70% increase in infrastructure spending from 1966-1970 (compared to the Macapagal administration's spending from 1961-1965) which included the [[North Luzon Expressway]] and the [[Maharlika Highway]], and the construction of 58, 745 pre-fabricated and 38,705 regular schoolbuildings.  The first Marcos administration's budget deficit was thus 72% higher than the Philippine government's annual deficit from 1961\u20131965.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\nThis began a pattern of loan-funded spending which the Marcos administration would continue until the Marcoses were deposed in 1986, resulting in economic instability still being felt today, and of debts that experts say the Philippines will have to keep paying well into 2025. The grandest infrastructure projects of Marcos' first term, especially the [[Cultural Center of the Philippines]] complex, also marked the beginning of what critics would call Ferdinand Marcos and First Lady Imelda Marcos' [[Edifice complex]], with grand public infrastructures projects prioritized for public funding because of their propaganda value.\n\n==Jabidah expose and Muslim reactions ==\n{{main|Jabidah massacre|Moro conflict}}\nIn March 1968 a Muslim man named Jibin Arula was fished out of the waters of Manila Bay, having been shot.  He was brought to then-Cavite Governor Delfin N. Montano, to whom he recounted the story of the Jabidah Massacre, saying that numerous [[Moro people|Moro]] army recruits had been executed en-masse by members of the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] (AFP) on 18 March 1968.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/24025-jabidah-massacre-merdeka-sabah|title=Jabidah and Merdeka: The inside story|author1=Marites Da\u00f1guilan Vitug|author2=Glenda M. Gloria|work=[[Rappler]]|date=18 March 2013|access-date=13 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913010948/http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/24025-jabidah-massacre-merdeka-sabah|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>  This became the subject of a senate expose by opposition Senator [[Benigno Aquino Jr.]]. <ref name=\"sfof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.ph/1968/03/28/jabidah-special-forces-of-evil-by-senator-benigno-s-aquino-jr/|title=Jabidah! Special Forces of Evil?|author=Senator Benigno S. Aquino Jr.|work=Delivered at the Legislative Building, Manila, on 28 March 1968|publisher=[[Government of the Philippines]]|date=28 March 1968|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913005535/http://www.gov.ph/1968/03/28/jabidah-special-forces-of-evil-by-senator-benigno-s-aquino-jr/|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Nasser A. Marohomsalic|title=Aristocrats of the Malay Race: A Historic of the Bangsa Moro in the Philippines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s3ZwAAAAMAAJ|year=2001|publisher=N.A. Marohomsalic}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the lack of living witnesses other than Arula severely hampered the probes on the incident, it became a major flashpoint that ignited the [[Moro insurgency in the Philippines]].<ref name=\"George1980\">{{cite book|author=T. J. S. George|title=Revolt in Mindanao: The Rise of Islam in Philippine Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HmYKAQAAIAAJ|year=1980|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-580429-4}}</ref> Despite undergoing numerous trials and hearings, none of the officers implicated in the massacre were ever convicted, leading many Filipino Muslims to believe that the \u201cChristian\u201d government in Manila had little regard for them.<ref name=\"Larousse2001\">{{cite book|author=William Larousse|title=A Local Church Living for Dialogue: Muslim-Christian Relations in Mindanao-Sulu, Philippines : 1965\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qyo-Hti0-KAC|year=2001|publisher=Gregorian Biblical BookShop|isbn=978-88-7652-879-8}}</ref> <ref name=\"Majul1985\">{{cite book|author=Cesar Adib Majul|title=The contemporary Muslim movement in the Philippines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6rpwAAAAMAAJ|date=October 1985|publisher=Mizan Press|isbn=978-0-933782-16-7}}</ref> \nThis created a furor within the Muslim community in the Philippines, especially among the educated youth,<ref name=\"MuslimPresident1994\">{{cite book|author1=Macapado Abaton Muslim|author2=Philippines. Office of the President|author3=Mindanao State University. College of Public Affairs|title=The Moro armed struggle in the Philippines: the nonviolent autonomy alternative|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4ERxAAAAMAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Office of the President and College of Public Affairs, Mindanao State University|isbn=978-971-11-1130-4}}</ref> and among Muslim intellectuals, who had no discernible interest in politics prior to the incident.<ref name=\"George1980\" /> Educated or not, the story of the Jabidah massacre led many Filipino Muslims to believe that all opportunities for integration and accommodation with the Christians were lost and further marginalised.<ref name=\"Smith2015\">{{cite book|author=Paul J. Smith|title=Terrorism and Violence in Southeast Asia: Transnational Challenges to States and Regional Stability: Transnational Challenges to States and Regional Stability|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nG6sBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT5|date=26 March 2015|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-45886-9|pages=5\u2013}}</ref> \n\nThis eventually led to the formation of the [[Mindanao Independence Movement]] in 1968, the Bangsamoro Liberation Organization (BMLO) in 1969, and the consilidation of these various forces into the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) in October 1972.<ref name=\"BetweenIntegrationandSecession\">{{Cite book|title = Between Integration and Secession: The Muslim Communities of the Southern Philippines, Southern Thailand and Western Burma/Myanmar|last = Yegar|first = Moshe|publisher = Lexington Books|year = 2002|isbn =|location =|pages = 267\u2013268}}</ref>\n\n== Re-election Campaign, 1969 ==\n{{main|Ferdinand Marcos presidential campaign, 1969}}\nWhen the time came for the [[Philippine presidential election, 1969|Philippine Presidential election of 1969]], it was taken for granted that Ferdinand Marcos and Fernando Lopez would be unanimously nominated as the respective presidential and vice presidential candidates of the Nacionalista party.  Nevertheless, the party's ruling junta met in Makati a week earlier before the July 1969 Nacionalista Party National Convention at the Manila Pavilion, in order to assure that the nomination would be unanimous.  The duo went against the Liberal Party's candidates, Sergio Osmena, Jr and Genaro Magsaysay.\n\nWith his popularity already beefed up by debt-funded spending, Marcos' popularity made it very likely that he would win the election, but he decided, as National Artist for Literature [[Nick Joaquin]] reported in the [[Philippines Free Press]], \"''leave nothing to chance''.\"  Time and Newsweek would eventually call the 1969 election the \"dirtiest, most violent and most corrupt\" in Philippine modern history, with the term \"Three Gs\", meaning \"guns, goons, and gold\"<ref name=\"Parsa2000\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=41_EXD1hWlgC&pg=PA45&lpg=PA45&dq=guns+goons+and+gold+1969#v=onepage&q=guns%2520goons%2520and%2520gold%25201969&f=false |title=States, Ideologies, and Social Revolutions: A Comparative Analysis of Iran, Nicaragua, and the Philippines |last=Parsa |first=Misagh |date=2000-08-17 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521774307 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite paper |url=http://library.fes.de/pdf-files/bueros/philippinen/50071.pdf |title=Election Violence in the Philippines |author1=Patrick Patino |author2=Djorina Velasco |last-author-amp=yes |year=2004 |publisher=FES Philippine Office }}</ref> coined<ref name=\"SunStarEditorial20160229\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/60678/ |title=Editorial: Protecting the vote |date=2016-02-29 |work=Sunstar |access-date=2018-05-22 |language=en-GB}}</ref> to describe administration's election tactics of vote-buying, terrorism and ballot snatching.<ref name=\"DeQuiros1997\">{{Cite book |title=Dead aim : how Marcos ambushed Philippine democracy|last=Conrado.|first=De Quiros|date=1997|publisher=Foundation for Worldwide People's Power|others=Foundation for Worldwide People Power (Manila, Philippines)|isbn=9719167033|location=Pasig City|oclc=39051509}}</ref>\n\nMarcos used the military and the government bureaucracy for his campaign,<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>  and also went on a campaign spending spree, initiating US$50 million worth in infrastructure projects meant to impress the electorate.<ref name=Burton1989>{{Cite book  |title=Impossible Dream: The Marcoses, the Aquinos, and the Unfinished Revolution.  |last=Burton  |first=Sandra  |publisher=Warner Books  |year=1989  |isbn=0446513989  |url-access=registration  |url=https://archive.org/details/impossibledreamm00burt  }}</ref>\n\nThe most infamous incidents of violence took place in Batanes, where Philippine Constabulary officers, paramilitary groups and hired guns essentially took over the island, and motorcycle-riding thugs rode around terrorizing voters and Comelec officials, and beating up opposition leaders.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\nRapid campaign spending was so massive that it would be responsible for the Balance of Payments Crisis of 1970. Marcos was reported to have spent PhP 100 for every PhP 1 that Osmena spent, using up PhP 24 Million in Cebu alone.<ref name=\"DeQuiros1997\"/>  By the following year, however, the government would be unable to pay its debts, and would decide to enter into a debt rescheduling arrangement plan with the [[International Monetary Fund]]. The stabilization plan involved in the agreement included numerous macroeconomic interventions, such as significantly devaluating the Philippine Peso.  However, the inflationary effect these interventions had on the local economy brought about the social unrest which motivated the proclamation of Martial Law in 1972.<ref name=Balbosas1992/><ref name=\"Cororaton1997\"/><ref name=\"Dohner&IntalInSachs1989\">{{Cite book |title=Developing country debt and the world economy  |last=Dohner |first=Robert  |last2= Intal |first2= Ponciano |date=1989 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=0226733386 |editor-last=Sachs |editor-first=Jeffrey D. |editor-link=Jeffrey Sachs |location=Chicago |chapter=Debt Crisis and Adjustment in the Philippines |oclc=18351577}}</ref>\n\nThe 1969 elections were held on 11 November, and Marcos won an unprecedented second full term as [[President of the Philippines]]. His running mate, incumbent Vice President [[Fernando Lopez]] was also elected to a third full term as [[Vice President of the Philippines]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Presidency of Ferdinand Marcos]]\n", "text_old": "[[Ferdinand Marcos]] was inaugurated to his '''first term as the [[List of Presidents of the Philippines|Tenth]] [[President of the Philippines]]''' on 30 December 1965.  His inauguration marked the beginning of his two-decade long stay in power, even though the 1935 Philippine Constitution had set a limit of only two four-year terms of office.  Marcos had won the [[1965 Philippine presidential election|Philippine presidential election of 1965]] against the incumbent President, [[Diosdado Macapagal]].\n\nBefore Marcos' Presidency, the Philippines was the second largest economy in Asia, behind only Japan.<ref name=\"Galang20110221\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/213564/opinion/the-economic-decline-that-led-to-marcos-fall/ |title=The economic decline that led to Marcos' fall |last=Galang |first=Ping |date=2011-02-21 |access-date=2018-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529093920/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/opinion/content/213564/the-economic-decline-that-led-to-marcos-fall/story/ |archive-date=2018-05-29 |url-status=live |language=en-US}}</ref>  He pursued an aggressive program of infrastructure development funded by foreign loans,<ref name=\"Galang20110221\"/> making him very popular throughout almost all of his first term and eventually making him the first and only President of the Third Philippine republic to win a second term, although it would also trigger an inflationary crisis which would lead to social unrest in his second term, and would eventually lead to his declaration of Martial Law in 1972.<ref name=Balbosas1992>{{Cite journal |last=Balbosa |first=Joven Zamoras |date=1992 |title=IMF Stabilization Program and Economic Growth: The Case of the Philippines |journal=Journal of Philippine Development |volume=XIX |issue=35}}</ref><ref name=\"Cororaton1997\">{{Cite journal |last=Cororaton |first=Cesar B. |title=Exchange Rate Movements in the Philippines |journal=DPIDS Discussion Paper Series 97-05 |pages=3, 19}}</ref>\n\n== 1965 Election Campaign ==\nFerdinand Marcos was a member of the Liberal Party (LP) in 1965, becoming [[Senate of the Philippines|Senate President]] during the presidential term of fellow Liberal Macapagal. Marcos found his ambitions to run for president blocked when Macapagal decided to run for a second term, so Marcos jumped from the LP to the Nacionalista Party (NP), eventually becoming the NP's candidate for President.<ref name=\"Pe20160703\">{{Cite news |url=http://opinion.inquirer.net/95478/turncoatism-in-ph |title=Turncoatism in PH |last=Pe |first=Roger |date=2016-07-03 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |access-date=2018-05-29 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAn acknowledged \"master of populist imagery\", Marcos projected a persona of youth and virility, having himself photographed by rice farmers in their fields.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\">{{Cite book |title=Kasaysayan, The Story of the Filipino People Volume 9:A Nation Reborn. |publisher=Asia Publishing Company Limited |year=1998 |editor-last=Magno |editor-first=Alexander R. |location=Hong Kong |chapter=Democracy at the Crossroads}}</ref> He also cast himself as a war hero, claiming to be the \"most decorated war hero of the Philippines\" on the strength of 27 supposed war medals and decorations which were later revealed to be mostly propaganda,<ref name=\"Mijares246\">{{Cite book |title=The conjugal dictatorship of Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos : revised and annotated |last=Primitivo |first=Mijares |isbn=9789715507813 |edition=Revised |location=Quezon City |pages=246\u2013254 |oclc=988749288|year = 2017}}</ref> being inaccurate or untrue.<ref name=\"Bondoc20110428\">{{Cite news |url=http://globalbalita.com/2011/04/28/marcos-medals-only-2-of-33-given-in-battle/ |title=Marcos medals: Only 2 of 33 given in battle |last=Bondoc  |first=Jarius  |date=April 28, 2011 |publisher=Global Balita}}</ref><ref name=\"chicagoTribune1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-09-29/news/8901180123_1_mr-marcos-ferdinand-edralin-marcos-martial-law/2|title=Marcos Was More Than Just Another Deposed Dictator|last=Reaves|first=Joseph A.|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=September 29, 1989}}</ref><ref name=\"USDODdatabase\">{{cite web|url=http://valor.defense.gov/Recipients/ArmyDistinguishedServiceCrossRecipients.aspx|title=US Department of Defense official database of Distinguished Service Cross recipients}}</ref>\n\nMarcos won the election with 51.94% of the vote, Macapagal having garnered 42.88% while Raul Manglapus of the Party for Philippine Progress got 5.17%.  About 0.01%. of the votes went to nine other candidates who ran for the post under various independent parties.<ref name=\"PhilippinePresidencyProjectElectionResults\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.pangulo.ph/election_results.php |title=Results of the Past Presidential & Vice-Presidential Elections |website=The Philippine Presidency Project |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824115409/http://www.pangulo.ph/election_results.php |archive-date=2007-08-24 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Administration ==\n{{see also|First inauguration of Ferdinand Marcos}}\n\nUpon winning the election, Marcos appointed a cabinet composed mostly of [[technocrat]]s and intellectuals, most notably Executive Secretary [[Rafael Salas]], Education Secretary [[Onofre Corpuz]], Finance Secrtetary [[Cesar Virata]], and National Economic and Development Authority Director General [[Gerardo Sicat]].<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\n=== Agricultural and rural development projects===\n{{see also|IR8}}\nIn an effort to strengthen the influence of the Office of the President and simultaneously weaken the strong patronage bonds which rural Filipinos had with their local leaders, Marcos created the Presidential Arm on Community Development (PACD), which would initiate development projects at the barrio level without going through the Barrio and Municipal governments.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\nMarcos also took credit for the dramatic increase in rice production caused by the 1968 introduction of a new \"miracle rice\" variety, [[IR8]], by the [[International Rice Research Institute]] in [[Los Ba\u00f1os, Laguna]] - although the IRRI program that developed the variety had started as early as 1962, during the Macapagal administration, and was the product of an International consortium, not the Philippine government.<ref name=\"IRRI2016\">{{cite web |url=http://irri.org/ir8 |title=IR8: Rice that Changed the World |publisher=International Rice Research Institute |access-date=October 19, 2017|date=November 2016 |website=IRRI.org}}</ref>\n\n=== Formation of Industrial Monopolies ===\n{{main|Monopolies in the Philippines (1965\u20131986)|Cronies of Ferdinand Marcos}}\nDuring this first term, Marcos also began systematically cultivating a group entrepreneurs and industrialists loyal to him, rather than the Philippines' ruling class of landowners, making these cronies richer and more powerful through what would later be called \"[[behest loans]]\", which funnelled foreign assistance and \"soft loans\" to their businesses on the pretense of spurring industrial development.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\n=== Expansion of the Philippine Military ===\nOne of Marcos' earliest initiatives upon becoming president was to significantly expand the Philippine Military. In an unprecedented move, Marcos chose to concurrently serve as his own Defense Secretary, allowing him to have a direct hand in running the Military.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/> He also significantly increased the budget of the armed forces, tapping them in civil projects such as the construction of schools.  Generals loyal to Marcos were allowed to stay in their positions past their retirement age, or were rewarded with civilian government posts, leading Senator [[Benigno Aquino Jr.|Benigno S. Aquino Jr.]] to accuse Marcos in 1968 of trying to establish \"a garrison state.\"<ref name=\"GovPh29thNinoyAnniv\">{{Cite web |url=http://president.gov.ph/gov_at_work/phl-marks-29th-anniversary-of-aquinos-assassination-on-tuesday/ |title=PHL marks 29th anniversary of Aquino's assassination on Tuesday |date=August 20, 2012 |publisher=Office of the President of the Philippines |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208022821/http://president.gov.ph/gov_at_work/phl-marks-29th-anniversary-of-aquinos-assassination-on-tuesday/ |archive-date=February 8, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Sending troops to the Vietnam War====\nUnder intense pressure from the administration of [[Lyndon B. Johnson]],<ref name=\"McMahon1999\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=lx0MWRuKtUkC&pg=PA141&lpg=PA141#v=onepage&f=false |title=The Limits of Empire: The United States and Southeast Asia Since World War II |last=McMahon |first=Robert J. |last2=Mcmahon |first2=Robert |date=1999 |publisher=Columbia University Press |isbn=9780231108812 }}</ref> Marcos reversed his pre-presidency position of not sending Philippine forces to Vietnam War,<ref name=\"Tan20050603\">{{Cite news |url=http://opinion.inquirer.net/85440/ph-vietnam-ties |title=PH-Vietnam ties |last=Tan |first=Michael L. |date=2005-06-03 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |access-date=2018-05-28 |language=en}}</ref> and consented to a limited involvement,<ref name=agoncillo508>{{Harvp|Agoncillo|1990|pp=508\u2013510}}.</ref> asking Congress to approve sending a [[combat engineer]] unit.  Despite opposition to the new plan, the Marcos government gained Congressional approval and Philippine troops were sent from the middle of 1966 as the Philippines Civic Action Group (PHILCAG). PHILCAG reached a strength of some 1,600 troops in 1968 and between 1966 and 1970 over 10,000 Filipino soldiers served in South Vietnam, mainly being involved in civilian infrastructure projects.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Larsen |first1=Stanley Robert |last2=Collins |first2=James Lawton, Jr. |orig-year=1985 |year=2005 |chapter-url=http://www.history.army.mil/books/Vietnam/allied/ch03.htm |chapter=Chapter III: The Philippines |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029203725/http://www.history.army.mil/books/Vietnam/allied/ch03.htm |archive-date=October 29, 2013 |url=https://history.army.mil/html/books/090/90-5-1/CMH_Pub_90-5-1.pdf |title=Allied Participation in Vietnam |publisher=U.S. Department of the Army}}</ref>\n\n=== Loans for Infrastructure Development ===\n{{main|Edifice complex}}\nWith an eye towards becoming the first president of the third republic to be reelected to a second term, the Marcos administration began taking up massive foreign loans to fund \"rice, roads, and schoolbuildings\" - the lynchpin slogan of his reelection campaign.  The Omnibus Tax Law of 1969 was passed too late by congress to be useful to Marcos' publicity efforts, and at any rate, did not succeed in raising signfiicant new funds.  So it was foreign loans that funded the 70% increase in infrastructure spending from 1966-1970 (compared to the Macapagal administration's spending from 1961-1965) which included the [[North Luzon Expressway]] and the [[Maharlika Highway]], and the construction of 58, 745 pre-fabricated and 38,705 regular schoolbuildings.  The first Marcos administration's budget deficit was thus 72% higher than the Philippine government's annual deficit from 1961-1965.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\nThis began a pattern of loan-funded spending which the Marcos administration would continue until the Marcoses were deposed in 1986, resulting in economic instability still being felt today, and of debts that experts say the Philippines will have to keep paying well into 2025. The grandest infrastructure projects of Marcos' first term, especially the [[Cultural Center of the Philippines]] complex, also marked the beginning of what critics would call Ferdinand Marcos and First Lady Imelda Marcos' [[Edifice complex]], with grand public infrastructures projects prioritized for public funding because of their propaganda value.\n\n==Jabidah expose and Muslim reactions ==\n{{main|Jabidah massacre|Moro conflict}}\nIn March 1968 a muslim man named Jibin Arula was fished out of the waters of Manila Bay, having been shot.  He was brought to then-Cavite Governor Delfin N. Montano, to whom he recounted the story of the Jabidah Massacre, saying that numerous [[Moro people|Moro]] army recruits had been executed en-masse by members of the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] (AFP) on 18 March 1968.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/24025-jabidah-massacre-merdeka-sabah|title=Jabidah and Merdeka: The inside story|author1=Marites Da\u00f1guilan Vitug|author2=Glenda M. Gloria|work=[[Rappler]]|date=18 March 2013|access-date=13 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913010948/http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/24025-jabidah-massacre-merdeka-sabah|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>  This became the subject of a senate expose by opposition Senator [[Benigno Aquino Jr.]]. <ref name=\"sfof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.ph/1968/03/28/jabidah-special-forces-of-evil-by-senator-benigno-s-aquino-jr/|title=Jabidah! Special Forces of Evil?|author=Senator Benigno S. Aquino Jr.|work=Delivered at the Legislative Building, Manila, on 28 March 1968|publisher=[[Government of the Philippines]]|date=28 March 1968|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913005535/http://www.gov.ph/1968/03/28/jabidah-special-forces-of-evil-by-senator-benigno-s-aquino-jr/|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Nasser A. Marohomsalic|title=Aristocrats of the Malay Race: A Historic of the Bangsa Moro in the Philippines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s3ZwAAAAMAAJ|year=2001|publisher=N.A. Marohomsalic}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the lack of living witnesses other than Arula severely hampered the probes on the incident, it became a major flashpoint that ignited the [[Moro insurgency in the Philippines]].<ref name=\"George1980\">{{cite book|author=T. J. S. George|title=Revolt in Mindanao: The Rise of Islam in Philippine Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HmYKAQAAIAAJ|year=1980|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-580429-4}}</ref> Despite undergoing numerous trials and hearings, none of the officers implicated in the massacre were ever convicted, leading many Filipino Muslims to believe that the \u201cChristian\u201d government in Manila had little regard for them.<ref name=\"Larousse2001\">{{cite book|author=William Larousse|title=A Local Church Living for Dialogue: Muslim-Christian Relations in Mindanao-Sulu, Philippines : 1965\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qyo-Hti0-KAC|year=2001|publisher=Gregorian Biblical BookShop|isbn=978-88-7652-879-8}}</ref> <ref name=\"Majul1985\">{{cite book|author=Cesar Adib Majul|title=The contemporary Muslim movement in the Philippines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6rpwAAAAMAAJ|date=October 1985|publisher=Mizan Press|isbn=978-0-933782-16-7}}</ref> \nThis created a furor within the Muslim community in the Philippines, especially among the educated youth,<ref name=\"MuslimPresident1994\">{{cite book|author1=Macapado Abaton Muslim|author2=Philippines. Office of the President|author3=Mindanao State University. College of Public Affairs|title=The Moro armed struggle in the Philippines: the nonviolent autonomy alternative|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4ERxAAAAMAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Office of the President and College of Public Affairs, Mindanao State University|isbn=978-971-11-1130-4}}</ref> and among Muslim intellectuals, who had no discernible interest in politics prior to the incident.<ref name=\"George1980\" /> Educated or not, the story of the Jabidah massacre led many Filipino Muslims to believe that all opportunities for integration and accommodation with the Christians were lost and further marginalised.<ref name=\"Smith2015\">{{cite book|author=Paul J. Smith|title=Terrorism and Violence in Southeast Asia: Transnational Challenges to States and Regional Stability: Transnational Challenges to States and Regional Stability|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nG6sBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT5|date=26 March 2015|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-45886-9|pages=5\u2013}}</ref> \n\nThis eventually led to the formation of the [[Mindanao Independence Movement]] in 1968, the Bangsamoro Liberation Organization (BMLO) in 1969, and the consilidation of these various forces into the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) in October 1972.<ref name=\"BetweenIntegrationandSecession\">{{Cite book|title = Between Integration and Secession: The Muslim Communities of the Southern Philippines, Southern Thailand and Western Burma/Myanmar|last = Yegar|first = Moshe|publisher = Lexington Books|year = 2002|isbn =|location =|pages = 267\u2013268}}</ref>\n\n== Re-election Campaign, 1969 ==\n{{main|Ferdinand Marcos presidential campaign, 1969}}\nWhen the time came for the [[Philippine presidential election, 1969|Philippine Presidential election of 1969]], it was taken for granted that Ferdinand Marcos and Fernando Lopez would be unanimously nominated as the respective presidential and vice presidential candidates of the Nacionalista party.  Nevertheless, the party's ruling junta met in Makati a week earlier before the July 1969 Nacionalista Party National Convention at the Manila Pavilion, in order to assure that the nomination would be unanimous.  The duo went against the Liberal Party's candidates, Sergio Osmena, Jr and Genaro Magsaysay.\n\nWith his popularity already beefed up by debt-funded spending, Marcos' popularity made it very likely that he would win the election, but he decided, as National Artist for Literature [[Nick Joaquin]] reported in the [[Philippines Free Press]], \"''leave nothing to chance''.\"  Time and Newsweek would eventually call the 1969 election the \"dirtiest, most violent and most corrupt\" in Philippine modern history, with the term \"Three Gs\", meaning \"guns, goons, and gold\"<ref name=\"Parsa2000\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=41_EXD1hWlgC&pg=PA45&lpg=PA45&dq=guns+goons+and+gold+1969#v=onepage&q=guns%2520goons%2520and%2520gold%25201969&f=false |title=States, Ideologies, and Social Revolutions: A Comparative Analysis of Iran, Nicaragua, and the Philippines |last=Parsa |first=Misagh |date=2000-08-17 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521774307 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite paper |url=http://library.fes.de/pdf-files/bueros/philippinen/50071.pdf |title=Election Violence in the Philippines |author1=Patrick Patino |author2=Djorina Velasco |last-author-amp=yes |year=2004 |publisher=FES Philippine Office }}</ref> coined<ref name=\"SunStarEditorial20160229\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/60678/ |title=Editorial: Protecting the vote |date=2016-02-29 |work=Sunstar |access-date=2018-05-22 |language=en-GB}}</ref> to describe administration's election tactics of vote-buying, terrorism and ballot snatching.<ref name=\"DeQuiros1997\">{{Cite book |title=Dead aim : how Marcos ambushed Philippine democracy|last=Conrado.|first=De Quiros|date=1997|publisher=Foundation for Worldwide People's Power|others=Foundation for Worldwide People Power (Manila, Philippines)|isbn=9719167033|location=Pasig City|oclc=39051509}}</ref>\n\nMarcos used the military and the government bureaucracy for his campaign,<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>  and also went on a campaign spending spree, initiating USD50 million worth in infrastructure projects meant to impress the electorate.<ref name=Burton1989>{{Cite book  |title=Impossible Dream: The Marcoses, the Aquinos, and the Unfinished Revolution.  |last=Burton  |first=Sandra  |publisher=Warner Books  |year=1989  |isbn=0446513989  |url-access=registration  |url=https://archive.org/details/impossibledreamm00burt  }}</ref>\n\nThe most infamous incidents of violence took place in Batanes, where Philippine Constabulary officers, paramilitary groups and hired guns essentially took over the island, and motorcycle-riding thugs rode around terrorizing voters and Comelec officials, and beating up opposition leaders.<ref name=\"Kasaysayan9ch10\"/>\n\nRapid campaign spending was so massive that it would be responsible for the Balance of Payments Crisis of 1970. Marcos was reported to have spent PhP 100 for every PhP 1 that Osmena spent, using up PhP 24 Million in Cebu alone.<ref name=\"DeQuiros1997\"/>  By the following year, however, the government would be unable to pay its debts, and would decide to enter into a debt rescheduling arrangement plan with the [[International Monetary Fund]]. The stabilization plan involved in the agreement included numerous macroeconomic interventions, such as significantly devaluating the Philippine Peso.  However, the inflationary effect these interventions had on the local economy brought about the social unrest which motivated the proclamation of Martial Law in 1972.<ref name=Balbosas1992/><ref name=\"Cororaton1997\"/><ref name=\"Dohner&IntalInSachs1989\">{{Cite book |title=Developing country debt and the world economy  |last=Dohner |first=Robert  |last2= Intal |first2= Ponciano |date=1989 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=0226733386 |editor-last=Sachs |editor-first=Jeffrey D. |editor-link=Jeffrey Sachs |location=Chicago |chapter=Debt Crisis and Adjustment in the Philippines |oclc=18351577}}</ref>\n\nThe 1969 elections were held on 11 November, and Marcos won an unprecedented second full term as [[President of the Philippines]]. His running mate, incumbent Vice President [[Fernando Lopez]] was also elected to a third full term as [[Vice President of the Philippines]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Presidency of Ferdinand Marcos]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: President \u2192 president (2),typo(s) fixed: USD \u2192 US$, muslim \u2192 Muslim, 1961-1965 \u2192 1961\u20131965", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_term_of_the_presidency_of_Ferdinand_Marcos"}
{"title_page": "Ben Askren", "text_new": "{{short description|American Olympic wrestler and mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Ben Askren        \n| image_size      = 200px\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1984|7|18}}\n| birth_place     = [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]], United States\n| residence       = \n| nationality     = American\n| height_ft       = 5\n| height_in       = 10\n| height_footnote = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ufc.com/athlete/ben-askren|title=Ben Askren UFC Profile|work=UFC.com|accessdate=July 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| weight_lb       = 170.5\n| weight_class    = [[Welterweight (MMA)|Welterweight (170 lbs)]] (2009\u20132016, 2019) <br> [[Middleweight (MMA)|Middleweight (185 lbs)]] (2016\u20132017){{efn|During Askren's tenure in ONE Championship, he competed at 185 lbs. ONE Championship refers to their 185 lb division as Welterweight, but per the Association of Boxing Commissions in the United States, 185 lbs is considered Middleweight.}}\n| reach_in        = 72\n| reach_footnote  = <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ufc.com/athlete/ben-askren|title=Ben Askren {{!}} UFC|website=www.ufc.com|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n| style           = [[Wrestling]]\n| stance          = \n| fighting_out_of = [[Hartland, Wisconsin]], United States\n| team            = [[Duke Roufus|Roufusport]]<br />[[Evolve MMA]]\n| wrestling       = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[Collegiate wrestling|Wrestling]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teamusa.org/usa-wrestling/athletes/Ben-Askren|title=Ben Askren|publisher=United States Olympic Committee|website=teamusa.org|accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref> <br> Olympic [[Freestyle wrestling|Freestyle Wrestling]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.flocombat.com/articles/6050393-ben-askren-complete-story-of-a-wrestling-legend|title=Ben Askren: Complete Story Of A Wrestling Legend|website=flocombat.com|author=Duane Finley|date=November 23, 2017}}</ref>\n| years_active    = 2009\u20132019\n| mma_kowin       = 6\n| mma_subwin      = 6\n| mma_decwin      = 7\n| mma_koloss      = 1\n| mma_subloss     = 1\n| mma_decloss     = \n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_nc          = 1\n| occupation      = \n| university      = [[University of Missouri]]\n| spouse          = \n| relatives       = Max Askren (brother)\n| students        = \n| club            = [[Sunkist Kids]]\n| school          = [[Arrowhead High School]]\n| url             = \n| sherdog         = 42390\n| footnotes       = \n| updated         = \n}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Freestyle Wrestling|freestyle wrestling]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | Pan American Championships }}\n{{MedalGold | 2005 Guatemala City|-84 kg }}\n{{MedalCompetition | United States Championships }}\n{{MedalGold | 2008 Las Vegas|-84 kg }}\n{{MedalSport | [[Collegiate Wrestling]]}}{{MedalCountry | the}} [[Missouri Tigers]] {{MedalCompetition|[[NCAA Division I Wrestling Championships]]}} {{MedalSilver|2004 [[St. Louis]]|174 lb}} {{MedalSilver|2005 [[St. Louis]]|174 lb}} {{MedalGold|2006 [[Oklahoma City]]|174 lb}} {{MedalGold|2007 [[Auburn Hills]]|174 lb}}{{MedalCompetition|Big 12 Championships}}\n{{MedalSilver|2004 [[Ames, Iowa|Ames]]|174 lb}}\n{{MedalSilver|2005 [[Omaha]]|174 lb}}\n{{MedalGold|2006 [[Ames, Iowa|Ames]]|174 lb}} {{MedalGold|2007 [[Columbia, Missouri|Columbia]]|174 lb}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[grappling]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FILA World Grappling Championships|World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Fort Lauderdale|-84 kg (No-Gi) }}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Benjamin Franklin Askren''' (born July 18, 1984), nicknamed \"'''Funky'''\",<ref name=\"ESPN\">{{cite web |title=Ben Askren |url=http://www.espn.com/mma/fighter/_/id/2500597/ben-askren |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=January 13, 2019}}</ref> is an American retired professional [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] and former [[Olympic wrestling|Olympic wrestler]].<ref>https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/11/4/18060798/dana-white-says-bringing-ben-askren-to-the-ufc-was-a-great-deal-for-me</ref> Askren was a former [[List of ONE Championship champions#Welterweight Championship|ONE Welterweight Champion]] and former [[Bellator Fighting Championships|Bellator]] [[Welterweight]]  Champion.  He also competed in the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC).\n\n== Wrestling ==\nAskren was an assistant [[wrestling]] coach at [[Arizona State University]] and was an American [[collegiate wrestling|amateur wrestler]] for the [[University of Missouri]]. He is a two-time state champion in wrestling at [[Arrowhead High School]] in [[Hartland, Wisconsin]].<ref>http://wrestling.teamusa.org/athletes/ben-askren</ref>\n\n=== Collegiate wrestling ===\n\nIn college, he wrestled in the 174&nbsp;lb. [[weight class]]. He lost the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) championship match to [[Chris Pendleton]] in both 2004 and 2005 before winning it in 2006 and 2007. He is known for his pinning ability (he holds the single-season NCAA pin record); his massive afro; and his \"funky\", or unorthodox, wrestling style. For example, while being ridden in the 2005 championship match, he attempted to reach around and apply a [[headlock]] to Pendleton, a move that any wrestling coach would disavow. His tall, lanky body \u2014 in sharp contrast to the squat, muscular physiques of many top wrestlers \u2014 allows him to attempt moves that most wrestlers could not. This characteristic later led to a challenging transition to freestyle wrestling early in his career, as the freestyle rules differ from folkstyle wrestling and penalize a wrestler for exposing his back. His younger brother Max also wrestled for Missouri and won a national championship in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mizzouwire.missouri.edu/stories/2010/askren-champion/ |title=Taking it to the Max |publisher=University of Missouri via website |date=April 16, 2010 |access-date=September 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911220342/http://mizzouwire.missouri.edu/stories/2010/askren-champion/ |archive-date=September 11, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAskren had a dominant Junior season in 2005\u201306, winning all 45 of his matches and pinning in 25 of them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mutigers.com/news/2006/3/27/Ben_Askren_Named_2006_Recipient_of_Dan_Hodge_Trophy.aspx?path=wrestling  |title=Ben Askren Named 2006 Recipient of Dan Hodge Trophy |publisher=MU Tigers Athletics via website |date=March 27, 2006}}</ref> He won the 174 pound weight class easily at both the [[Big 12]] and NCAA Championships. He won his Big 12 finals match 17\u20136 over Jacob Klein of Nebraska and his NCAA finals match 14\u20132 over future two time NCAA champion, [[Dan Hodge Trophy]] winner, and World silver medalist [[Jake Herbert]] of [[Northwestern University|Northwestern]]. Herbert was also undefeated going into the NCAA finals. Askren's season earned him the Outstanding Wrestler award at the NCAA Championships as well as the Dan Hodge Trophy and the Rev Wrestler of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mutigers.com/news/2006/3/23/Askren_Named_2006_Rev_Wrestler_of_the_Year.aspx?path=wrestling |title=Askren Named 2006 Rev Wrestler of the Year |publisher=MU Tigers Athletics via website |date=March 23, 2006}}</ref>\n\nAskren continued that dominance going into his Senior year in 2006\u201307, going undefeated again with a record of 42\u20130.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mutigers.com/news/2007/3/17/Ben_Askren_Repeats_as_National_Champ_Tigers_Finish_Third.aspx?path=wrestling |title=Ben Askren Repeats as National Champ, Tigers Finish Third |publisher=MU Tigers Athletics via website |date=March 17, 2007}}</ref>  He won his second consecutive NCAA Championship at 174 pounds by defeating another future NCAA champion, second-ranked Keith Gavin of Pittsburgh, 8\u20132. Askren finished his collegiate career with an 87 match winning streak. He also became only the second person to win the Dan Hodge Trophy twice, as W.I.N. Magazine named the 2007 winner. Askren was again named the Rev Wrestler of the Year. He also received the [[Schalles Award]], named after [[Wade Schalles]] and given to the most prolific pinner at the end of each season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mutigers.com/news/2007/5/14/Missouri_Wrestling_Coach_and_Athlete_Earn_Honors.aspx?path=wrestling\n |title=Missouri Wrestling Coach and Athlete Earn Honors |publisher=MU Tigers Athletics via website |date=May 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAskren finished his collegiate wrestling career with a record of 153\u20138, with 91 of those victories coming by way of fall.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} Those 91 pins put him at third on the all-time NCAA [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] pins list. In his four-year career at Missouri, Askren only lost to two opponents, Chris Pendleton of Oklahoma St. and Ryan Lange of Purdue.  He was also a four-time [[All-American]], including being only the twelfth Division I wrestler ever to be a four-time finalist. Askren was also nominated for an [[ESPY]] in 2007 in the category Best Male College Athlete.\nOn January 9, 2012 it was announced that Askren would be one of six new inductees to the [[University of Missouri]] Intercollegiate Athletics Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heartlandconnection.com/sports/story.aspx?id=705673 |title=Six chosen for University of Missouri Athletics Hall of Fame |publisher=KTVO-TV via website |date=2012-01-09 |accessdate=2012-01-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918161234/http://www.heartlandconnection.com/sports/story.aspx?id=705673 |archive-date=2013-09-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== 2008 Olympics ===\n{{For|more about wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\nIn the summer of 2008, Askren defeated national runner-up Tyrone Lewis in two consecutive matches by decision at the US Olympic Trials in Las Vegas, becoming the second University of Missouri wrestler to qualify for the Olympics. [[Sammie Henson]], who also attended Missouri but finished his college wrestling career at [[Clemson University|Clemson]], competed in the 2000 Olympics winning a silver medal. Askren competed in the 74&nbsp;kg. weight class at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]]. Askren won his first match via pin against Hungarian [[Istv\u00e1n Ver\u00e9b]]. In his round of 8 match he lost to Cuba's [[Ivan Fundora]] 1\u20133, 0\u20134. The Cuban's loss to Russia's [[Buvaisar Saitiev]] in the quarterfinal round ended Askren's hopes of a medal at the [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Games]].\n\nAskren was asked if inexperience was a factor. Though he was a two-time NCAA champion at the University of Missouri he was relatively new to freestyle after wrestling folkstyle in college. \"That wasn't it,\" he said with tears in his eyes, \"I just wasn't good enough. I sucked.\" <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.com/olympics/summer08/columns/story?id=3544007 | title=Askren's long wait for shot on Olympic mat ends in tears | publisher=ESPN via website}}</ref>\n\n=== Post-Olympic Career ===\nAlthough Askren decided to pursue a career in MMA after the Olympics, he continued to compete in wrestling occasionally. In 2010, he avenged his Olympic loss by defeating Fundora in the semifinals of the [[Cerro Pelado International]], in Cuba. This came shortly after Askren won the [[Dave Schultz (wrestling)|Dave Schultz]] Memorial International. Later in the same year, Askren defeated 2009 world silver medalist Jake Herbert in a folkstyle rules match at the Midlands Tournament. Askren also competed in the Agon Wrestling Championships and the Flo Premier League. In May 2019, Askren lost by technical superiority to [[Jordan Burroughs]] in the annual Beat the Streets benefit event.<ref>https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/5/7/18535315/ben-askren-got-smoked-at-beat-the-streets-but-wrestling-is-alive-and-well</ref>\n\n== Mixed martial arts career ==\n\nAskren is now an active [[submission wrestling|submission wrestler]], and is a self-proclaimed black belt, which is not recognized in IBJJF in [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu|jiu-jitsu]]. In December 2008, he went to [[Coconut Creek, Florida]] to train at the [[American Top Team]] main school where many top fighters train. He currently{{when|date=July 2014}} trains at Roufusport in [[Milwaukee]], where he is the wrestling coach.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n=== Early career ===\nAskren made his professional MMA debut on February 7, 2009.<ref name=mmadebut>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/13837/collegiate-wrestling-stand-out-ben-askren-makes-pro-mma-debut-feb-7.mma |title=Collegiate wrestling stand-out Ben Askren makes pro MMA debut Feb. 7 |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2009-01-27 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308091114/http://mmajunkie.com/news/13837/collegiate-wrestling-stand-out-ben-askren-makes-pro-mma-debut-feb-7.mma |archivedate=2009-03-08 }}</ref> It was held by Headhunter Productions at the Holiday Inn Select Executive Center in [[Columbia, Missouri]]. He defeated Josh Flowers via TKO early in the first round.<ref name=mmafight1>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/13950/mma-rookie-and-olympian-ben-askren-ufc-vet-din-thomas-win-in-missouri.mma |title=MMA rookie and Olympian Ben Askren, UFC vet Din Thomas win in Missouri |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2009-02-08 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090314045827/http://mmajunkie.com/news/13950/mma-rookie-and-olympian-ben-askren-ufc-vet-din-thomas-win-in-missouri.mma |archivedate=2009-03-14 }}</ref>\n\nAskren had his second fight at Patriot Act 2 in [[Columbia, Missouri]]. He defeated Mitchell Harris via submission by arm triangle. The fight was at a [[catchweight]] of 175 pounds.<ref name=mmafight2>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14701/ncaa-champ-ben-askren-moves-to-2-0-with-weekend-mma-win.mma |title=NCAA champ Ben Askren moves to 2\u20130 with weekend MMA win |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2009-04-27 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430095722/http://mmajunkie.com/news/14701/ncaa-champ-ben-askren-moves-to-2-0-with-weekend-mma-win.mma |archivedate=2009-04-30 }}</ref>\n\n=== Grappling ===\nAskren competed at the 2009 [[ADCC Submission Wrestling World Championship]] from September 26\u201427, in Barcelona, Spain. He won his first match against Toni Linden by [[arm triangle choke]]. He lost his second match to [[Pablo Popovitch]], a veteran grappler he had trained with the previous summer, by figure four [[footlock]] early in the match. Popovitch went on to win the championship in the under 77&nbsp;kg (169&nbsp;lb) division.<ref>{{cite web |author=SCHEDULE September 23, 2009 \u2014 sebastianvalle |url=http://adccbarcelona.com/ |title=ADCC WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP BARCELONA 2009 |publisher=Adccbarcelona.com |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nAskren also competed at the 2009 [[International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles|FILA]] 2\u00b0 World Grappling Championship. Askren faced the 2008 World Champion, [[Jacob Volkmann]], in the 84&nbsp;kg [[no-gi]] division. Askren out-wrestled Volkmann and won gold in the category.<ref>{{cite web |author=International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles |url=http://www.fila-official.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=567%3Achampionnat-du-monde-a-fort-lauderdale&catid=56%3Aactualite&Itemid=100210 |title=Championnat du Monde en Floride |publisher=Fila-official.com |accessdate=2014-04-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316213824/http://www.fila-official.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=567:championnat-du-monde-a-fort-lauderdale&catid=56:actualite&Itemid=100210 |archive-date=2012-03-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Bellator Fighting Championships ===\nAskren was a participant in [[Bellator Fighting Championships]] [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Two|Season 2]] Welterweight Tournament.<ref name=bellator>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/17138/welterweight-prospect-ben-asken-announced-as-bellators-newest-signee.mma |title=Welterweight prospect Ben Askren announced as Bellator's newest signee |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2009-12-09 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208232126/http://mmajunkie.com/news/17138/welterweight-prospect-ben-asken-announced-as-bellators-newest-signee.mma |archivedate=2010-02-08 }}</ref> In his first fight, Askren defeated [[Ryan Thomas (fighter)|Ryan Thomas]] via technical submission at [[Bellator 14]] on April 15, 2010. The outcome of the fight was controversial because Thomas protested the stoppage as soon as Askren released the choke.<ref name=bellator14>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/18738/bellator-14-recap-imada-askren-reis-and-curran-advance-in-tourney-action.mma |title=Bellator 14 recap: Imada, Askren, Reis and Curran advance in tourney action |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2010-04-15 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629161615/http://mmajunkie.com/news/18738/bellator-14-recap-imada-askren-reis-and-curran-advance-in-tourney-action.mma |archivedate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Jim Wallhead]] was pulled from the tournament, Thomas was given another chance to compete. Thomas defeated [[Jacob McClintock]] by TKO in the first round at [[Bellator 15]] and was awarded a rematch with Askren. When the two fought at [[Bellator 19]], Askren came out victorious again with a unanimous decision after controlling Thomas with [[wrestling]] for three rounds.<ref name=bellator19>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/19230/bellator-19-recap-soto-stops-saraiva-askren-and-hornbuckle-book-finals-date.mma |title=Bellator 19 recap: Soto stops Saraiva; Askren and Hornbuckle book finals date |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629161009/http://mmajunkie.com/news/19230/bellator-19-recap-soto-stops-saraiva-askren-and-hornbuckle-book-finals-date.mma |archivedate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt [[Bellator 22]], Askren defeated [[Dan Hornbuckle]] via unanimous decision with his superior wrestling dominating Hornbuckle for all three rounds, becoming the [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Two#Welterweight Tournament Bracket|Bellator Season Two Welterweight Tournament Champion]].<ref name=bellator22>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/19589/bellator-22-recap-dan-hornbuckle-cant-stop-the-funk-ben-askren-claims-tourney-win.mma |title=Bellator 22 recap: Dan Hornbuckle can't stop the funk; Ben Askren claims tourney win |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621030731/http://mmajunkie.com/news/19589/bellator-22-recap-dan-hornbuckle-cant-stop-the-funk-ben-askren-claims-tourney-win.mma |archivedate=2010-06-21 }}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2010 in Philadelphia Askren took on the Bellator Welterweight Champion [[Lyman Good]]. Despite being hit with a brutal upkick and almost getting caught in a triangle choke with one minute left, he was able to take down and control Good in every round. Askren won via unanimous decision (49\u201346, 48\u201347, and 50\u201345) to win the Bellator Welterweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2010/10/21/ben-askren-beats-lyman-good-for-bellator-welterweight-title/ |title=Ben Askren Beats Lyman Good for Bellator Welterweight Title |publisher=MMA Fighting |date= |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nAskren next returned at [[Bellator 40]] to fight and defeat [[Nick Thompson (fighter)|Nick Thompson]] after taking down and controlling Thompson for all three rounds. Although Askren started off quickly in the third round with a spinning back fist and several other strikes, he was caught with an overhand right by Thompson, causing Askren to take down and control Thompson for the remainder of the round. Askren went on to win by unanimous decision (30\u201326, 30\u201327, and 30\u201327).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/mma/2011/4/9/2101575/bellator-40-results-ben-askren-vs-nick-thompson |title=Bellator 40 Results: Ben Askren Dominates Nick Thompson Over Fifteen Minutes |publisher=SBNation.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his unanimous decision win over  Thompson in a non-title affair at [[Bellator 40]] in [[Newkirk, Oklahoma]], Askren revealed that he will relocate to [[Milwaukee]] in the near future to train under [[Duke Roufus]] at Roufusport.<ref>{{cite web |last=Breen |first=Jordan |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Bellator-Champ-Askren-Milwaukee-Bound-Set-to-Join-Roufusport-Camp-31477 |title=Bellator Champ Askren Milwaukee-Bound, Set to Join Roufusport Camp |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2011-04-09 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nAskren successfully defended his title against season 4 welterweight tournament winner [[Jay Hieron]] at [[Bellator 56]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Leidecker |first=Tim |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/10-October-Tussles-Worth-Watching-36076 |title=10 October Tussles Worth Watching |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2011-09-30 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref> following a close split decision.\n\nAskren successfully defended his title against season 5 welterweight tournament winner [[Douglas Lima]] at [[Bellator 64]] on April 6, 2012 on Good Friday at the Caesars in Windsor, Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmainterplay.com/bellator-news/ben-askren-vs-douglas-lima-welterweight-title-bout-set-for-bellator-64-56951/ |title=Ben Askren vs. Douglas Lima welterweight title bout set for Bellator 64 &#124; MMA News |publisher=Mmainterplay.com |date=2012-02-08 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nNext for Askren was a title defense against [[Karl Amoussou]],<ref name=\"mmajunkie.com\">[http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/29818/bellator-72-results.mma/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724015828/http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/29818/bellator-72-results.mma/ |date=July 24, 2012 }}</ref> the fight taking place at [[Bellator 86]] on January 24, 2013. Askren once again used his top control wrestling to shut down his opponents [[grappling]], and opened a cut on Amoussou's forehead with an elbow strike. The doctor stepped in between the third and fourth rounds, judging the cut too severe for Amoussou to continue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Bellator-86-Results-PlaybyPlay-Updates-49273#ben-askren-karl-amoussou |title=BELLATOR 86 RESULTS: PLAY-BY-PLAY & UPDATES |first=Mike |last=Whitman |website=Sherdog |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the final fight of his contract, Askren faced tournament winner [[Andrey Koreshkov]] at [[Bellator 97]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://themmareport.com/2013/05/bellator-97-takes-place-on-july-31st-in-new-mexico-with-askren-koreshkov-and-lima-saunders/ |title=Bellator 97 takes place on July 31st in New Mexico with Askren-Koreshkov and Lima-Saunders |publisher=The MMA Report |date=2013-05-21 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref> He dominated the fight with his wrestling and ground strikes, outstriking his opponent by a wide 248 to 3 margin before winning via TKO in the fourth round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2013/7/31/4576730/bellator-97-results-michael-chandler-ben-askren-cruise-to-easy-title |title=Bellator 97 results: Michael Chandler, Ben Askren cruise to easy title defenses |author=Thomas, Luke |date=July 31, 2013 |publisher=MMAJunkie.com}}</ref>\n\nOn November 14, 2013, following a negotiation period, Bellator announced they had released Askren from the company, and that he was now an unrestricted free agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2013/11/14/bellator-releases-welterweight-champion-ben-askren/ |title=Bellator releases welterweight champion Ben Askren |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2013-11-14 |accessdate=2013-11-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114154253/http://mmajunkie.com/2013/11/14/bellator-releases-welterweight-champion-ben-askren/ |archivedate=2013-11-14 }}</ref>\n\n=== ONE Championship ===\nOn December 9, 2013, Askren signed a 2 year/6 fight contract with [[ONE Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/undefeated-former-bellator-champion-ben-011835957--mma.html |title=Undefeated Former Bellator Champion Ben Askren Signs with One FC}}</ref>\n\nAskren met Bakhtiyar Abbasov, who had been riding a nine-fight win streak, in the main event of ONE FC: Honor and Glory on May 30.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmanuts.com/news/ben-askren-make-one-fc-debut-may/ |title=Ben Askren to Make One FC Debut in May |publisher=mmanuts.com |author=Chris Pagliuca |date=April 7, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> He won the fight via submission (arm-triangle choke) in the first round, and proceeded to call out ONE champion [[Nobutatsu Suzuki]], stating \"Suzuki is going to bring me my belt. He can put it in the middle of the cage and give it to me, or I can take it the hard way!\u201d<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cagepages.com/2014/05/30/one-fc-16-honor-glory-results-askren/ |title=ONE FC 16: Honor & Glory Results: Ben Askren Submits Abbasov in Debut, Latoel Upsets Ng |publisher=cagepages.com |author=Kevin Thang |date=May 30, 2014 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAskren faced Suzuki at ONE Fighting Championship: Reign of Champions on August 29, 2014. He won the fight via TKO due to strikes in the first round to become the new ONE Welterweight Champion.\n\nAskren faced [[Luis Santos (fighter)|Luis Santos]] in the main event at [[ONE Championship]]: Valor of Champions on April 24.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmacrazytv.com/2015/03/06/ben-askren-set-to-face-luis-santos/ |title=Ben Askren vs Luis Santos at ONE: Valor of Champions |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402190609/http://mmacrazytv.com/2015/03/06/ben-askren-set-to-face-luis-santos/ |archivedate=2015-04-02 }}</ref>  The fight was ruled \"no contest\" after an accidental eye poke from Askren at 2:19 of round 1 rendered Santos unable to continue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://prommanow.com/2015/04/24/one-valor-of-champions-full-results-askren-retains-title-against-veteran-santos-due-to-no-contest/ |title=ONE: Valor of Champions full results; Askren retains title against veteran Santos due to No Contest |publisher=prommanow.com |author=Jack Bratcher |date=April 24, 2015 |accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the next fight Askren beat Russia's Nikolay Aleksakhin at the ONE Championship: Global Warriors on April 15, 2016 by unanimous decision.\n\nAskren then fought Agilan Thani at the ONE Championship: Dynasty of Heroes on May 26, 2017. He won the fight via submission due to an arm-triangle choke in the first round.\n\nAskren then faced Zebaztian Kadestam at the ONE Championship: Shanghai on September 7, 2017. He won the fight via TKO due to punches.\n\nIn his last fight, Askren faced fellow veteran Shinya Aoki at ONE Championship: Immortal Pursuit on November 24, 2017. Prior to the fight, he claimed this would be his last fight. He won the fight via TKO due to punches in the first round. He retired from MMA after the win.\n\nAskren left the door open for one last fight if he was made an offer to \"prove I'm the best welterweight in the world\". He discussed the possibility of facing Georges St. Pierre, claiming \"He doesn't want a title fight. He just wants to build on his legacy,\" adding that he felt he would be the perfect opponent for St. Pierre. Askren later claimed he would fight St. Pierre in spring of 2019.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n=== Ultimate Fighting Championship ===\nOn November 3, 2018, it was announced that the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] had signed Askren under the \"trade UFC and One Championship agreement\", in exchange for former [[List of UFC champions#Flyweight Championship|UFC Flyweight Champion]] [[Demetrious Johnson (fighter)|Demetrious Johnson]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/11/4/18060798/dana-white-says-bringing-ben-askren-to-the-ufc-was-a-great-deal-for-me|title=Dana White says bringing Ben Askren to the UFC was \u2018a great deal for me\u2019|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nAskren made his UFC debut against the former [[UFC Welterweight Champion]] [[Robbie Lawler]] on March 2, 2019 at [[UFC 235]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/12/13/18139529/ben-askren-vs-robbie-lawler-rescheduled-for-ufc-235|title=Ben Askren vs. Robbie Lawler rescheduled for UFC 235|last=Al-Shatti|first=Shaun|date=2018-12-13|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref> The bout was initially scheduled for [[UFC 233]], but after the event was cancelled the fight was rescheduled for UFC 235. Askren won the fight via bulldog choke in the first round, through a controversial stoppage by referee Herb Dean. Lawler appeared unconscious, prompting referee [[Herb Dean]] to stop the fight. Immediately after, Lawler stood up protesting the stoppage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/03/ufc-235-results-ben-askren-controversial-stoppage-over-robbie-lawler-after-vicious-onslaught|title=UFC 235 results: Ben Askren survives vicious onslaught, earns controversial stoppage over Robbie Lawler|date=2019-03-03|website=MMA Junkie|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> Replays appear to show Lawler's arm going limp and giving a thumbs up right after, which some attribute to Lawler slipping in and out of consciousness. Although controversial, Nevada Athletic Commission executive director Bob Bennett explained that the commission had \"no problem\" with Dean's decision to stop the fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebodylockmma.com/ufc/commission-has-no-problem-with-no-brainer-decision-to-end-ben-askren-vs-robbie-lawler-fight/|title=Commission has 'no problem' with 'no-brainer' decision to end Ben Askren vs. Robbie Lawler fight|last=Nichols|first=Jake|date=2019-03-03|website=The Body Lock|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nAskren faced [[Jorge Masvidal]] on July 6, 2019 at [[UFC 239]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmanews.com/ben-askren-jorge-masvidal-set-ufc-239/|title=Ben Askren vs. Jorge Masvidal Set For UFC 239 \u2022 MMA News|last=Fuentes|first=Jon|date=2019-04-11|website=MMA News|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> Askren was violently knocked out with a flying knee 5 seconds into the first round, the fastest knockout in UFC history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2019/7/6/20684562/ufc-239-results-jorge-masvidal-instantly-ko-ben-askren-flying-knee-5-seconds-mma-news|title=UFC 239 results: Jorge Masvidal KOs Ben Askren with flying knee in record-setting time|last=Mercado|first=Eddie|date=2019-07-06|website=Bloody Elbow}}</ref>\n\nAskren faced [[Demian Maia]] on October 26, 2019 at [[UFC on ESPN+ 20]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmadna.nl/demian-maia-vs-ben-askren-is-het-main-event-van-ufc-singapore/|title=Demian Maia vs. Ben Askren is het Main Event van UFC Singapore|last=DNA|first=MMA|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref> He lost the fight via submission in round three.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cagesidepress.com/2019/10/26/ufc-singapore-results-demian-maia-finishes-ben-askren-submission/|title=UFC Singapore Results: Demian Maia Finishes Ben Askren with Third-Round Submission|last=Harshman|first=Heath|date=2019-10-26|website=Cageside Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref> This fight earned him the ''[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Fight of the Night]]'' award.<ref name=\"UFConESON+20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2019/10/26/20933630/ufc-singapore-bonuses-ciryl-gane-banks-extra-50k-for-heel-hook-finish-maia-askren-dariush-espn-mma|title=Singapore Bonuses! Gane\u2019s Heel Hook Finish Leads $50K Winners|last=Hiergesell|first=Dan|date=2019-10-26|website=MMAmania.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref>\n\nOn November 18, 2019 Askren announced his retirement from mixed martial arts competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lowkickmma.com/breaking-ben-askren-officially-retires-from-mma-competition/|title=Breaking: Ben Askren Officially Retires From MMA Competition|last=Kini|first=Abhinav|date=2019-11-18|website=LowKickMMA.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAskren is married and has 3 children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marriedbiography.com/ben-askren-biography/|title=Ben Askren Biography - Affair, Married, Wife, Ethnicity, Nationality, Salary, Net Worth, Height|website=Married Biography|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> \n<!-- Needs a better source, see talk page.\nAskren has [[aspergers]]. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dnFxegf6tfU&t=288 |title=Ben Askren: I'll beat Jorge Masvidal 'any way I want' &#124; UFC 239 &#124; ESPN MMA\n|publisher=ESPN MMA}}</ref>\n-->\nHe is also competitive in the sport of [[disc golf]]. In 2009, Askren finished 9th in the Amateur World Championships.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pdga.com/tournament_results/13814/Open |title=2009 PDGA Amateur World Championships Results}}</ref> Askren is sponsored by [[Discraft]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://discgolf.discraft.com/team_askren.html |title=Team Discraft profile: Ben Askren}}</ref> He is also involved in [[cryptocurrency]] investing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/27952345/former-champion-ben-askren-considering-retirement|title=Former champion Askren considering retirement|date=2019-10-28|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\nAskren co-hosts a couple of weekly wrestling podcasts: 'The Funky & FRB Show' with Front Row Brian on [https://rokfin.com/stack/17 Rokfin] and 'The T-Row & Funky Show' with 2x NCAA Champion [[Tommy Rowlands]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/the-t-row-funky-show/id1059934839 |title=iTunes: The T-Row & Funky Show}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n\n=== Mixed martial arts ===\n*'''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Fight of the Night]] (One time) {{small| vs. [[Demian Maia]]}}<ref name=\"UFConESON+20\" />\n* '''[[Bellator Fighting Championships]]'''\n** [[List of Bellator champions#Welterweight Championship|Bellator Welterweight Championship]] (One time)\n**Four successful title defenses\n** [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Two#Welterweight Tournament Bracket|Bellator Season 2 Welterweight Tournament Championship]]\n** Most consecutive title defenses in Bellator history (4)\n** Most successful title defenses in Bellator history (4)\n**Undefeated (9-0)\n* '''[[ONE Championship]]'''\n** [[List of ONE Championship champions#Welterweight Championship|ONE Welterweight Championship]] (One time)\n**Three successful title defenses\n***undefeated (7-0)\n=== Disc golf ===\n* '''[[Professional Disc Golf Association]]'''\n** 2011 United States Amateur Disc Golf Championship 2nd Place\n** 2009 PDGA Amateur World Doubles Championships Advanced 4th Place\n** 2009 St. Louis Open Advanced 2nd Place\n** 2009 Mighty MO Advanced 1st Place\n** 2009 First Class Challenge 3rd place\n** 2006 Alabama Amateur Open Intermediate 3rd Place\n** 2005 Highnoon at Indiantown Intermediate 2nd Place\n\n=== Submission grappling ===\n* '''Abu Dhabi Combat Club'''\n** 2009 ADCC Submission Wrestling World Championships Quarterfinalist\n* '''[[International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles]]'''\n** [[International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles|FILA]] 2009 Grappling World Championships Senior No-Gi Gold Medalist\n* '''[[USA Wrestling]]'''\n** [[International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles|FILA]] World Team Trials Senior No-Gi Winner (2009)\n\n{{Col-2}}\n\n=== Amateur wrestling ===\n* '''[[International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles]]'''\n** 2010 Cerro Pelado International Senior Freestyle Silver Medalist\n** 2010 Dave Schultz Memorial International Open Senior Freestyle Gold Medalist\n** 2009 Hargobind International Senior Freestyle Gold Medalist\n** 2009 Sunkist Kids International Open Senior Freestyle Silver Medalist\n** 2008 Kiev International Senior Freestyle Bronze Medalist\n** 2007 NYAC Holiday International Open Senior Freestyle Gold Medalist\n** 2007 Hargobind International Tournament Senior Freestyle Gold Medalist\n** 2005 Pan American Championships Senior Freestyle Gold Medalist\n* '''[[USA Wrestling]]'''\n** USA Senior Freestyle Olympic Team Trials Winner (2008)\n** USA Junior Freestyle World Team Trials Winner (2004)\n** USA Senior Freestyle National Championship (2008)\n** [[ASICS]] Tiger High School All-American (2002)\n** West Junior Freestyle Regional Championship (2002)\n** Northern Plains Junior Freestyle Regional Championship (2001, 2002)\n* '''[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]'''\n** [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] Collegiate National Champion (2006, 2007)\n** [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[All-American]] (2004, 2005, 2006, 2007) 4x NCAA Finalist\n** [[Big 12 Conference]] Championship (2004, 2006, 2007)\n** [[Dan Hodge Trophy]] Collegiate Wrestler of the Year (2006, 2007)\n** [[University of Missouri]] Intercollegiate Athletics Hall of Fame (2012)\n* '''National Wrestling Coaches Association'''\n** [[Schalles Award]] Top Collegiate Pinner of the Year (2006, 2007)\n* '''National High School Coaches Association'''\n** NHSCA Senior High School National Championship Runner-up (2002)\n** NHSCA Senior All-American (2002)\n* '''[[Wisconsin Interscholastic Athletic Association]]'''\n** [[Wisconsin Interscholastic Athletic Association|WIAA]] Division I High School State Championship (2000, 2001)\n** [[Wisconsin Interscholastic Athletic Association|WIAA]] Division I All-State (1999, 2000, 2001)\n** [[Classic 8 Conference]] Championship (1999, 2000, 2001, 2002)\n*'''[[George Tragos/Lou Thesz Professional Wrestling Hall of Fame]]'''\n**George Tragos Award (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/03/26/national-wrestling-hall-of-fame-announced-class-of-2018-details-on-hof-induction-weekend-including-ross-booker-t-animal/|title=National Wrestling Hall of Fame announced Class of 2018, details on HOF Induction Weekend including Ross, Booker T, Animal|last=Keller|first=Wade|authorlink=Wade Keller|website=PWTorch.com|date=March 26, 2018|accessdate=August 27, 2018}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n== Mixed martial arts record ==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws=\n| nc=1\n| ko-wins=6\n| sub-wins=6\n| dec-wins=7\n| ko-losses=1\n| sub-losses=1\n| dec-losses=\n| dq-wins=\n| dq-losses=\n| other-wins=\n| other-losses=\n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|align=center|19\u20132 (1)\n|[[Demian Maia]]\n|Technical Submission (rear-naked choke)<!--PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE THIS AS THIS IS THE OFFICIAL RESULT LISTED BY SHERDOG-->\n|[[UFC Fight Night: Maia vs. Askren]] \n|{{dts|2019|October|26}}\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|3:54\n|[[Kallang]], Singapore \n|{{small|Fight of the Night.}}   \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 19\u20131 (1)\n| [[Jorge Masvidal]]\n| KO (flying knee)\n| [[UFC 239]]\n| {{dts|2019|July|6}}\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|0:05\n| [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], United States\n|<!--PLEASE DO NOT PUT ANYTHING HERE, 'FASTEST KNOCKOUT IN UFC HISTORY' IS NOT AN ACHIEVEMENT IF HE LOST-->\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 19\u20130 (1)\n| [[Robbie Lawler]]\n| Technical Submission (bulldog choke) <!--PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE THIS AS THIS IS THE OFFICIAL RESULT LISTED BY SHERDOG-->\n| [[UFC 235]]\n| {{dts|2019|March|2}}\n| align=center|1\n| align=center|3:20\n| [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], United States\n|{{small|Return to Welterweight (170 lbs).}}\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| alig