[[Middleweight (MMA)|Middleweight (185 lbs)]] (2016\u20132017){{efn|During Askren's tenure in ONE Championship, he competed at 185 lbs. ONE Championship refers to their 185 lb division as Welterweight, but per the Association of Boxing Commissions in the United States, 185 lbs is considered Middleweight.}}\n| reach_in        = 72\n| reach_footnote  = <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ufc.com/athlete/ben-askren|title=Ben Askren {{!}} UFC|website=www.ufc.com|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n| style           = [[Wrestling]]\n| stance          = \n| fighting_out_of = [[Hartland, Wisconsin]], United States\n| team            = [[Duke Roufus|Roufusport]]<br />[[Evolve MMA]]\n| wrestling       = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[Collegiate wrestling|Wrestling]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teamusa.org/usa-wrestling/athletes/Ben-Askren|title=Ben Askren|publisher=United States Olympic Committee|website=teamusa.org|accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref> <br> Olympic [[Freestyle wrestling|Freestyle Wrestling]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.flocombat.com/articles/6050393-ben-askren-complete-story-of-a-wrestling-legend|title=Ben Askren: Complete Story Of A Wrestling Legend|website=flocombat.com|author=Duane Finley|date=November 23, 2017}}</ref>\n| years_active    = 2009\u20132019\n| mma_kowin       = 6\n| mma_subwin      = 6\n| mma_decwin      = 7\n| mma_koloss      = 1\n| mma_subloss     = 1\n| mma_decloss     = \n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_nc          = 1\n| occupation      = \n| university      = [[University of Missouri]]\n| spouse          = \n| relatives       = Max Askren (brother)\n| students        = \n| club            = [[Sunkist Kids]]\n| school          = [[Arrowhead High School]]\n| url             = \n| sherdog         = 42390\n| footnotes       = \n| updated         = \n}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Freestyle Wrestling|freestyle wrestling]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | Pan American Championships }}\n{{MedalGold | 2005 Guatemala City|-84 kg }}\n{{MedalCompetition | United States Championships }}\n{{MedalGold | 2008 Las Vegas|-84 kg }}\n{{MedalSport | [[Collegiate Wrestling]]}}{{MedalCountry | the}} [[Missouri Tigers]] {{MedalCompetition|[[NCAA Division I Wrestling Championships]]}} {{MedalSilver|2004 [[St. Louis]]|174 lb}} {{MedalSilver|2005 [[St. Louis]]|174 lb}} {{MedalGold|2006 [[Oklahoma City]]|174 lb}} {{MedalGold|2007 [[Auburn Hills]]|174 lb}}{{MedalCompetition|Big 12 Championships}}\n{{MedalSilver|2004 [[Ames, Iowa|Ames]]|174 lb}}\n{{MedalSilver|2005 [[Omaha]]|174 lb}}\n{{MedalGold|2006 [[Ames, Iowa|Ames]]|174 lb}} {{MedalGold|2007 [[Columbia, Missouri|Columbia]]|174 lb}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[grappling]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FILA World Grappling Championships|World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Fort Lauderdale|-84 kg (No-Gi) }}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Ben Askren''' (born July 18, 1984), nicknamed \"'''Funky'''\",<ref name=\"ESPN\">{{cite web |title=Ben Askren |url=http://www.espn.com/mma/fighter/_/id/2500597/ben-askren |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=January 13, 2019}}</ref> is an American retired professional [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] and former [[Olympic wrestling|Olympic wrestler]].<ref>https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/11/4/18060798/dana-white-says-bringing-ben-askren-to-the-ufc-was-a-great-deal-for-me</ref> Askren was a former [[List of ONE Championship champions#Welterweight Championship|ONE Welterweight Champion]] and former [[Bellator Fighting Championships|Bellator]] [[Welterweight]]  Champion.  He also competed in the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC).\n\n== Wrestling ==\nAskren was an assistant [[wrestling]] coach at [[Arizona State University]] and was an American [[collegiate wrestling|amateur wrestler]] for the [[University of Missouri]]. He is a two-time state champion in wrestling at [[Arrowhead High School]] in [[Hartland, Wisconsin]].<ref>http://wrestling.teamusa.org/athletes/ben-askren</ref>\n\n=== Collegiate wrestling ===\n\nIn college, he wrestled in the 174&nbsp;lb. [[weight class]]. He lost the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) championship match to [[Chris Pendleton]] in both 2004 and 2005 before winning it in 2006 and 2007. He is known for his pinning ability (he holds the single-season NCAA pin record); his massive afro; and his \"funky\", or unorthodox, wrestling style. For example, while being ridden in the 2005 championship match, he attempted to reach around and apply a [[headlock]] to Pendleton, a move that any wrestling coach would disavow. His tall, lanky body \u2014 in sharp contrast to the squat, muscular physiques of many top wrestlers \u2014 allows him to attempt moves that most wrestlers could not. This characteristic later led to a challenging transition to freestyle wrestling early in his career, as the freestyle rules differ from folkstyle wrestling and penalize a wrestler for exposing his back. His younger brother Max also wrestled for Missouri and won a national championship in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mizzouwire.missouri.edu/stories/2010/askren-champion/ |title=Taking it to the Max |publisher=University of Missouri via website |date=April 16, 2010 |access-date=September 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911220342/http://mizzouwire.missouri.edu/stories/2010/askren-champion/ |archive-date=September 11, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAskren had a dominant Junior season in 2005\u201306, winning all 45 of his matches and pinning in 25 of them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mutigers.com/news/2006/3/27/Ben_Askren_Named_2006_Recipient_of_Dan_Hodge_Trophy.aspx?path=wrestling  |title=Ben Askren Named 2006 Recipient of Dan Hodge Trophy |publisher=MU Tigers Athletics via website |date=March 27, 2006}}</ref> He won the 174 pound weight class easily at both the [[Big 12]] and NCAA Championships. He won his Big 12 finals match 17\u20136 over Jacob Klein of Nebraska and his NCAA finals match 14\u20132 over future two time NCAA champion, [[Dan Hodge Trophy]] winner, and World silver medalist [[Jake Herbert]] of [[Northwestern University|Northwestern]]. Herbert was also undefeated going into the NCAA finals. Askren's season earned him the Outstanding Wrestler award at the NCAA Championships as well as the Dan Hodge Trophy and the Rev Wrestler of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mutigers.com/news/2006/3/23/Askren_Named_2006_Rev_Wrestler_of_the_Year.aspx?path=wrestling |title=Askren Named 2006 Rev Wrestler of the Year |publisher=MU Tigers Athletics via website |date=March 23, 2006}}</ref>\n\nAskren continued that dominance going into his Senior year in 2006\u201307, going undefeated again with a record of 42\u20130.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mutigers.com/news/2007/3/17/Ben_Askren_Repeats_as_National_Champ_Tigers_Finish_Third.aspx?path=wrestling |title=Ben Askren Repeats as National Champ, Tigers Finish Third |publisher=MU Tigers Athletics via website |date=March 17, 2007}}</ref>  He won his second consecutive NCAA Championship at 174 pounds by defeating another future NCAA champion, second-ranked Keith Gavin of Pittsburgh, 8\u20132. Askren finished his collegiate career with an 87 match winning streak. He also became only the second person to win the Dan Hodge Trophy twice, as W.I.N. Magazine named the 2007 winner. Askren was again named the Rev Wrestler of the Year. He also received the [[Schalles Award]], named after [[Wade Schalles]] and given to the most prolific pinner at the end of each season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mutigers.com/news/2007/5/14/Missouri_Wrestling_Coach_and_Athlete_Earn_Honors.aspx?path=wrestling\n |title=Missouri Wrestling Coach and Athlete Earn Honors |publisher=MU Tigers Athletics via website |date=May 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAskren finished his collegiate wrestling career with a record of 153\u20138, with 91 of those victories coming by way of fall.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} Those 91 pins put him at third on the all-time NCAA [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] pins list. In his four-year career at Missouri, Askren only lost to two opponents, Chris Pendleton of Oklahoma St. and Ryan Lange of Purdue.  He was also a four-time [[All-American]], including being only the twelfth Division I wrestler ever to be a four-time finalist. Askren was also nominated for an [[ESPY]] in 2007 in the category Best Male College Athlete.\nOn January 9, 2012 it was announced that Askren would be one of six new inductees to the [[University of Missouri]] Intercollegiate Athletics Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heartlandconnection.com/sports/story.aspx?id=705673 |title=Six chosen for University of Missouri Athletics Hall of Fame |publisher=KTVO-TV via website |date=2012-01-09 |accessdate=2012-01-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918161234/http://www.heartlandconnection.com/sports/story.aspx?id=705673 |archive-date=2013-09-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== 2008 Olympics ===\n{{For|more about wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}\nIn the summer of 2008, Askren defeated national runner-up Tyrone Lewis in two consecutive matches by decision at the US Olympic Trials in Las Vegas, becoming the second University of Missouri wrestler to qualify for the Olympics. [[Sammie Henson]], who also attended Missouri but finished his college wrestling career at [[Clemson University|Clemson]], competed in the 2000 Olympics winning a silver medal. Askren competed in the 74&nbsp;kg. weight class at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]]. Askren won his first match via pin against Hungarian [[Istv\u00e1n Ver\u00e9b]]. In his round of 8 match he lost to Cuba's [[Ivan Fundora]] 1\u20133, 0\u20134. The Cuban's loss to Russia's [[Buvaisar Saitiev]] in the quarterfinal round ended Askren's hopes of a medal at the [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Games]].\n\nAskren was asked if inexperience was a factor. Though he was a two-time NCAA champion at the University of Missouri he was relatively new to freestyle after wrestling folkstyle in college. \"That wasn't it,\" he said with tears in his eyes, \"I just wasn't good enough. I sucked.\" <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.com/olympics/summer08/columns/story?id=3544007 | title=Askren's long wait for shot on Olympic mat ends in tears | publisher=ESPN via website}}</ref>\n\n=== Post-Olympic Career ===\nAlthough Askren decided to pursue a career in MMA after the Olympics, he continued to compete in wrestling occasionally. In 2010, he avenged his Olympic loss by defeating Fundora in the semifinals of the [[Cerro Pelado International]], in Cuba. This came shortly after Askren won the [[Dave Schultz (wrestling)|Dave Schultz]] Memorial International. Later in the same year, Askren defeated 2009 world silver medalist Jake Herbert in a folkstyle rules match at the Midlands Tournament. Askren also competed in the Agon Wrestling Championships and the Flo Premier League. In May 2019, Askren lost by technical superiority to [[Jordan Burroughs]] in the annual Beat the Streets benefit event.<ref>https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/5/7/18535315/ben-askren-got-smoked-at-beat-the-streets-but-wrestling-is-alive-and-well</ref>\n\n== Mixed martial arts career ==\n\nAskren is now an active [[submission wrestling|submission wrestler]], and is a self-proclaimed black belt, which is not recognized in IBJJF in [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu|jiu-jitsu]]. In December 2008, he went to [[Coconut Creek, Florida]] to train at the [[American Top Team]] main school where many top fighters train. He currently{{when|date=July 2014}} trains at Roufusport in [[Milwaukee]], where he is the wrestling coach.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n=== Early career ===\nAskren made his professional MMA debut on February 7, 2009.<ref name=mmadebut>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/13837/collegiate-wrestling-stand-out-ben-askren-makes-pro-mma-debut-feb-7.mma |title=Collegiate wrestling stand-out Ben Askren makes pro MMA debut Feb. 7 |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2009-01-27 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308091114/http://mmajunkie.com/news/13837/collegiate-wrestling-stand-out-ben-askren-makes-pro-mma-debut-feb-7.mma |archivedate=2009-03-08 }}</ref> It was held by Headhunter Productions at the Holiday Inn Select Executive Center in [[Columbia, Missouri]]. He defeated Josh Flowers via TKO early in the first round.<ref name=mmafight1>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/13950/mma-rookie-and-olympian-ben-askren-ufc-vet-din-thomas-win-in-missouri.mma |title=MMA rookie and Olympian Ben Askren, UFC vet Din Thomas win in Missouri |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2009-02-08 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090314045827/http://mmajunkie.com/news/13950/mma-rookie-and-olympian-ben-askren-ufc-vet-din-thomas-win-in-missouri.mma |archivedate=2009-03-14 }}</ref>\n\nAskren had his second fight at Patriot Act 2 in [[Columbia, Missouri]]. He defeated Mitchell Harris via submission by arm triangle. The fight was at a [[catchweight]] of 175 pounds.<ref name=mmafight2>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14701/ncaa-champ-ben-askren-moves-to-2-0-with-weekend-mma-win.mma |title=NCAA champ Ben Askren moves to 2\u20130 with weekend MMA win |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2009-04-27 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430095722/http://mmajunkie.com/news/14701/ncaa-champ-ben-askren-moves-to-2-0-with-weekend-mma-win.mma |archivedate=2009-04-30 }}</ref>\n\n=== Grappling ===\nAskren competed at the 2009 [[ADCC Submission Wrestling World Championship]] from September 26\u201427, in Barcelona, Spain. He won his first match against Toni Linden by [[arm triangle choke]]. He lost his second match to [[Pablo Popovitch]], a veteran grappler he had trained with the previous summer, by figure four [[footlock]] early in the match. Popovitch went on to win the championship in the under 77&nbsp;kg (169&nbsp;lb) division.<ref>{{cite web |author=SCHEDULE September 23, 2009 \u2014 sebastianvalle |url=http://adccbarcelona.com/ |title=ADCC WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP BARCELONA 2009 |publisher=Adccbarcelona.com |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nAskren also competed at the 2009 [[International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles|FILA]] 2\u00b0 World Grappling Championship. Askren faced the 2008 World Champion, [[Jacob Volkmann]], in the 84&nbsp;kg [[no-gi]] division. Askren out-wrestled Volkmann and won gold in the category.<ref>{{cite web |author=International Federation of Associated Wrestling Styles |url=http://www.fila-official.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=567%3Achampionnat-du-monde-a-fort-lauderdale&catid=56%3Aactualite&Itemid=100210 |title=Championnat du Monde en Floride |publisher=Fila-official.com |accessdate=2014-04-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316213824/http://www.fila-official.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=567:championnat-du-monde-a-fort-lauderdale&catid=56:actualite&Itemid=100210 |archive-date=2012-03-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Bellator Fighting Championships ===\nAskren was a participant in [[Bellator Fighting Championships]] [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Two|Season 2]] Welterweight Tournament.<ref name=bellator>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/17138/welterweight-prospect-ben-asken-announced-as-bellators-newest-signee.mma |title=Welterweight prospect Ben Askren announced as Bellator's newest signee |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2009-12-09 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208232126/http://mmajunkie.com/news/17138/welterweight-prospect-ben-asken-announced-as-bellators-newest-signee.mma |archivedate=2010-02-08 }}</ref> In his first fight, Askren defeated [[Ryan Thomas (fighter)|Ryan Thomas]] via technical submission at [[Bellator 14]] on April 15, 2010. The outcome of the fight was controversial because Thomas protested the stoppage as soon as Askren released the choke.<ref name=bellator14>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/18738/bellator-14-recap-imada-askren-reis-and-curran-advance-in-tourney-action.mma |title=Bellator 14 recap: Imada, Askren, Reis and Curran advance in tourney action |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2010-04-15 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629161615/http://mmajunkie.com/news/18738/bellator-14-recap-imada-askren-reis-and-curran-advance-in-tourney-action.mma |archivedate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Jim Wallhead]] was pulled from the tournament, Thomas was given another chance to compete. Thomas defeated [[Jacob McClintock]] by TKO in the first round at [[Bellator 15]] and was awarded a rematch with Askren. When the two fought at [[Bellator 19]], Askren came out victorious again with a unanimous decision after controlling Thomas with [[wrestling]] for three rounds.<ref name=bellator19>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/19230/bellator-19-recap-soto-stops-saraiva-askren-and-hornbuckle-book-finals-date.mma |title=Bellator 19 recap: Soto stops Saraiva; Askren and Hornbuckle book finals date |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629161009/http://mmajunkie.com/news/19230/bellator-19-recap-soto-stops-saraiva-askren-and-hornbuckle-book-finals-date.mma |archivedate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt [[Bellator 22]], Askren defeated [[Dan Hornbuckle]] via unanimous decision with his superior wrestling dominating Hornbuckle for all three rounds, becoming the [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Two#Welterweight Tournament Bracket|Bellator Season Two Welterweight Tournament Champion]].<ref name=bellator22>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/19589/bellator-22-recap-dan-hornbuckle-cant-stop-the-funk-ben-askren-claims-tourney-win.mma |title=Bellator 22 recap: Dan Hornbuckle can't stop the funk; Ben Askren claims tourney win |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621030731/http://mmajunkie.com/news/19589/bellator-22-recap-dan-hornbuckle-cant-stop-the-funk-ben-askren-claims-tourney-win.mma |archivedate=2010-06-21 }}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2010 in Philadelphia Askren took on the Bellator Welterweight Champion [[Lyman Good]]. Despite being hit with a brutal upkick and almost getting caught in a triangle choke with one minute left, he was able to take down and control Good in every round. Askren won via unanimous decision (49\u201346, 48\u201347, and 50\u201345) to win the Bellator Welterweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2010/10/21/ben-askren-beats-lyman-good-for-bellator-welterweight-title/ |title=Ben Askren Beats Lyman Good for Bellator Welterweight Title |publisher=MMA Fighting |date= |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nAskren next returned at [[Bellator 40]] to fight and defeat [[Nick Thompson (fighter)|Nick Thompson]] after taking down and controlling Thompson for all three rounds. Although Askren started off quickly in the third round with a spinning back fist and several other strikes, he was caught with an overhand right by Thompson, causing Askren to take down and control Thompson for the remainder of the round. Askren went on to win by unanimous decision (30\u201326, 30\u201327, and 30\u201327).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/mma/2011/4/9/2101575/bellator-40-results-ben-askren-vs-nick-thompson |title=Bellator 40 Results: Ben Askren Dominates Nick Thompson Over Fifteen Minutes |publisher=SBNation.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his unanimous decision win over  Thompson in a non-title affair at [[Bellator 40]] in [[Newkirk, Oklahoma]], Askren revealed that he will relocate to [[Milwaukee]] in the near future to train under [[Duke Roufus]] at Roufusport.<ref>{{cite web |last=Breen |first=Jordan |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Bellator-Champ-Askren-Milwaukee-Bound-Set-to-Join-Roufusport-Camp-31477 |title=Bellator Champ Askren Milwaukee-Bound, Set to Join Roufusport Camp |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2011-04-09 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nAskren successfully defended his title against season 4 welterweight tournament winner [[Jay Hieron]] at [[Bellator 56]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Leidecker |first=Tim |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/10-October-Tussles-Worth-Watching-36076 |title=10 October Tussles Worth Watching |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2011-09-30 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref> following a close split decision.\n\nAskren successfully defended his title against season 5 welterweight tournament winner [[Douglas Lima]] at [[Bellator 64]] on April 6, 2012 on Good Friday at the Caesars in Windsor, Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmainterplay.com/bellator-news/ben-askren-vs-douglas-lima-welterweight-title-bout-set-for-bellator-64-56951/ |title=Ben Askren vs. Douglas Lima welterweight title bout set for Bellator 64 &#124; MMA News |publisher=Mmainterplay.com |date=2012-02-08 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\nNext for Askren was a title defense against [[Karl Amoussou]],<ref name=\"mmajunkie.com\">[http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/29818/bellator-72-results.mma/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724015828/http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/29818/bellator-72-results.mma/ |date=July 24, 2012 }}</ref> the fight taking place at [[Bellator 86]] on January 24, 2013. Askren once again used his top control wrestling to shut down his opponents [[grappling]], and opened a cut on Amoussou's forehead with an elbow strike. The doctor stepped in between the third and fourth rounds, judging the cut too severe for Amoussou to continue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Bellator-86-Results-PlaybyPlay-Updates-49273#ben-askren-karl-amoussou |title=BELLATOR 86 RESULTS: PLAY-BY-PLAY & UPDATES |first=Mike |last=Whitman |website=Sherdog |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the final fight of his contract, Askren faced tournament winner [[Andrey Koreshkov]] at [[Bellator 97]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://themmareport.com/2013/05/bellator-97-takes-place-on-july-31st-in-new-mexico-with-askren-koreshkov-and-lima-saunders/ |title=Bellator 97 takes place on July 31st in New Mexico with Askren-Koreshkov and Lima-Saunders |publisher=The MMA Report |date=2013-05-21 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref> He dominated the fight with his wrestling and ground strikes, outstriking his opponent by a wide 248 to 3 margin before winning via TKO in the fourth round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2013/7/31/4576730/bellator-97-results-michael-chandler-ben-askren-cruise-to-easy-title |title=Bellator 97 results: Michael Chandler, Ben Askren cruise to easy title defenses |author=Thomas, Luke |date=July 31, 2013 |publisher=MMAJunkie.com}}</ref>\n\nOn November 14, 2013, following a negotiation period, Bellator announced they had released Askren from the company, and that he was now an unrestricted free agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2013/11/14/bellator-releases-welterweight-champion-ben-askren/ |title=Bellator releases welterweight champion Ben Askren |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=2013-11-14 |accessdate=2013-11-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114154253/http://mmajunkie.com/2013/11/14/bellator-releases-welterweight-champion-ben-askren/ |archivedate=2013-11-14 }}</ref>\n\n=== ONE Championship ===\nOn December 9, 2013, Askren signed a 2 year/6 fight contract with [[ONE Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/undefeated-former-bellator-champion-ben-011835957--mma.html |title=Undefeated Former Bellator Champion Ben Askren Signs with One FC}}</ref>\n\nAskren met Bakhtiyar Abbasov, who had been riding a nine-fight win streak, in the main event of ONE FC: Honor and Glory on May 30.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmanuts.com/news/ben-askren-make-one-fc-debut-may/ |title=Ben Askren to Make One FC Debut in May |publisher=mmanuts.com |author=Chris Pagliuca |date=April 7, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> He won the fight via submission (arm-triangle choke) in the first round, and proceeded to call out ONE champion [[Nobutatsu Suzuki]], stating \"Suzuki is going to bring me my belt. He can put it in the middle of the cage and give it to me, or I can take it the hard way!\u201d<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cagepages.com/2014/05/30/one-fc-16-honor-glory-results-askren/ |title=ONE FC 16: Honor & Glory Results: Ben Askren Submits Abbasov in Debut, Latoel Upsets Ng |publisher=cagepages.com |author=Kevin Thang |date=May 30, 2014 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAskren faced Suzuki at ONE Fighting Championship: Reign of Champions on August 29, 2014. He won the fight via TKO due to strikes in the first round to become the new ONE Welterweight Champion.\n\nAskren faced [[Luis Santos (fighter)|Luis Santos]] in the main event at [[ONE Championship]]: Valor of Champions on April 24.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmacrazytv.com/2015/03/06/ben-askren-set-to-face-luis-santos/ |title=Ben Askren vs Luis Santos at ONE: Valor of Champions |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402190609/http://mmacrazytv.com/2015/03/06/ben-askren-set-to-face-luis-santos/ |archivedate=2015-04-02 }}</ref>  The fight was ruled \"no contest\" after an accidental eye poke from Askren at 2:19 of round 1 rendered Santos unable to continue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://prommanow.com/2015/04/24/one-valor-of-champions-full-results-askren-retains-title-against-veteran-santos-due-to-no-contest/ |title=ONE: Valor of Champions full results; Askren retains title against veteran Santos due to No Contest |publisher=prommanow.com |author=Jack Bratcher |date=April 24, 2015 |accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the next fight Askren beat Russia's Nikolay Aleksakhin at the ONE Championship: Global Warriors on April 15, 2016 by unanimous decision.\n\nAskren then fought Agilan Thani at the ONE Championship: Dynasty of Heroes on May 26, 2017. He won the fight via submission due to an arm-triangle choke in the first round.\n\nAskren then faced Zebaztian Kadestam at the ONE Championship: Shanghai on September 7, 2017. He won the fight via TKO due to punches.\n\nIn his last fight, Askren faced fellow veteran Shinya Aoki at ONE Championship: Immortal Pursuit on November 24, 2017. Prior to the fight, he claimed this would be his last fight. He won the fight via TKO due to punches in the first round. He retired from MMA after the win.\n\nAskren left the door open for one last fight if he was made an offer to \"prove I'm the best welterweight in the world\". He discussed the possibility of facing Georges St. Pierre, claiming \"He doesn't want a title fight. He just wants to build on his legacy,\" adding that he felt he would be the perfect opponent for St. Pierre. Askren later claimed he would fight St. Pierre in spring of 2019.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n=== Ultimate Fighting Championship ===\nOn November 3, 2018, it was announced that the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] had signed Askren under the \"trade UFC and One Championship agreement\", in exchange for former [[List of UFC champions#Flyweight Championship|UFC Flyweight Champion]] [[Demetrious Johnson (fighter)|Demetrious Johnson]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/11/4/18060798/dana-white-says-bringing-ben-askren-to-the-ufc-was-a-great-deal-for-me|title=Dana White says bringing Ben Askren to the UFC was \u2018a great deal for me\u2019|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nAskren made his UFC debut against the former [[UFC Welterweight Champion]] [[Robbie Lawler]] on March 2, 2019 at [[UFC 235]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/12/13/18139529/ben-askren-vs-robbie-lawler-rescheduled-for-ufc-235|title=Ben Askren vs. Robbie Lawler rescheduled for UFC 235|last=Al-Shatti|first=Shaun|date=2018-12-13|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref> The bout was initially scheduled for [[UFC 233]], but after the event was cancelled the fight was rescheduled for UFC 235. Askren won the fight via bulldog choke in the first round, through a controversial stoppage by referee Herb Dean. Lawler appeared unconscious, prompting referee [[Herb Dean]] to stop the fight. Immediately after, Lawler stood up protesting the stoppage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/03/ufc-235-results-ben-askren-controversial-stoppage-over-robbie-lawler-after-vicious-onslaught|title=UFC 235 results: Ben Askren survives vicious onslaught, earns controversial stoppage over Robbie Lawler|date=2019-03-03|website=MMA Junkie|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> Replays appear to show Lawler's arm going limp and giving a thumbs up right after, which some attribute to Lawler slipping in and out of consciousness. Although controversial, Nevada Athletic Commission executive director Bob Bennett explained that the commission had \"no problem\" with Dean's decision to stop the fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebodylockmma.com/ufc/commission-has-no-problem-with-no-brainer-decision-to-end-ben-askren-vs-robbie-lawler-fight/|title=Commission has 'no problem' with 'no-brainer' decision to end Ben Askren vs. Robbie Lawler fight|last=Nichols|first=Jake|date=2019-03-03|website=The Body Lock|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nAskren faced [[Jorge Masvidal]] on July 6, 2019 at [[UFC 239]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmanews.com/ben-askren-jorge-masvidal-set-ufc-239/|title=Ben Askren vs. Jorge Masvidal Set For UFC 239 \u2022 MMA News|last=Fuentes|first=Jon|date=2019-04-11|website=MMA News|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> Askren was violently knocked out with a flying knee 5 seconds into the first round, the fastest knockout in UFC history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2019/7/6/20684562/ufc-239-results-jorge-masvidal-instantly-ko-ben-askren-flying-knee-5-seconds-mma-news|title=UFC 239 results: Jorge Masvidal KOs Ben Askren with flying knee in record-setting time|last=Mercado|first=Eddie|date=2019-07-06|website=Bloody Elbow}}</ref>\n\nAskren faced [[Demian Maia]] on October 26, 2019 at [[UFC on ESPN+ 20]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmadna.nl/demian-maia-vs-ben-askren-is-het-main-event-van-ufc-singapore/|title=Demian Maia vs. Ben Askren is het Main Event van UFC Singapore|last=DNA|first=MMA|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref> He lost the fight via submission in round three.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cagesidepress.com/2019/10/26/ufc-singapore-results-demian-maia-finishes-ben-askren-submission/|title=UFC Singapore Results: Demian Maia Finishes Ben Askren with Third-Round Submission|last=Harshman|first=Heath|date=2019-10-26|website=Cageside Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref> This fight earned him the ''[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Fight of the Night]]'' award.<ref name=\"UFConESON+20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2019/10/26/20933630/ufc-singapore-bonuses-ciryl-gane-banks-extra-50k-for-heel-hook-finish-maia-askren-dariush-espn-mma|title=Singapore Bonuses! Gane\u2019s Heel Hook Finish Leads $50K Winners|last=Hiergesell|first=Dan|date=2019-10-26|website=MMAmania.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref>\n\nOn November 18, 2019 Askren announced his retirement from mixed martial arts competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lowkickmma.com/breaking-ben-askren-officially-retires-from-mma-competition/|title=Breaking: Ben Askren Officially Retires From MMA Competition|last=Kini|first=Abhinav|date=2019-11-18|website=LowKickMMA.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAskren is married and has 3 children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marriedbiography.com/ben-askren-biography/|title=Ben Askren Biography - Affair, Married, Wife, Ethnicity, Nationality, Salary, Net Worth, Height|website=Married Biography|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> \n<!-- Needs a better source, see talk page.\nAskren has [[aspergers]]. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dnFxegf6tfU&t=288 |title=Ben Askren: I'll beat Jorge Masvidal 'any way I want' &#124; UFC 239 &#124; ESPN MMA\n|publisher=ESPN MMA}}</ref>\n-->\nHe is also competitive in the sport of [[disc golf]]. In 2009, Askren finished 9th in the Amateur World Championships.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pdga.com/tournament_results/13814/Open |title=2009 PDGA Amateur World Championships Results}}</ref> Askren is sponsored by [[Discraft]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://discgolf.discraft.com/team_askren.html |title=Team Discraft profile: Ben Askren}}</ref> He is also involved in [[cryptocurrency]] investing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/27952345/former-champion-ben-askren-considering-retirement|title=Former champion Askren considering retirement|date=2019-10-28|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\nAskren co-hosts a couple of weekly wrestling podcasts: 'The Funky & FRB Show' with Front Row Brian on [https://rokfin.com/stack/17 Rokfin] and 'The T-Row & Funky Show' with 2x NCAA Champion [[Tommy Rowlands]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/the-t-row-funky-show/id1059934839 |title=iTunes: The T-Row & Funky Show}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n\n=== Mixed martial arts ===\n*'''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Fight of the Night]] (One time) {{small| vs. [[Demian Maia]]}}<ref name=\"UFConESON+20\" />\n* '''[[Bellator Fighting Championships]]'''\n** [[List of Bellator champions#Welterweight Championship|Bellator Welterweight Championship]] (One time)\n**Four successful title defenses\n** [[Bellator Fighting Championships: Season Two#Welterweight Tournament Bracket|Bellator Season 2 Welterweight Tournament Championship]]\n** Most consecutive title defenses in Bellator history (4)